<HTML>
<TITLE>1994 Annual Report - Domestic and Economic Policy -- Heritage</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2><I><FONT SIZE = "+3">R</FONT>esearch</I></H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><I><FONT SIZE = "+2">D</FONT>omestic and <FONT SIZE = "+2">E</FONT>conomic 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">P</FONT>olicy</I></H3></CENTER>

<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>
<P>
If not dishonest, Washington's traditional misuse of numbers certainly is misleading. 
The use of a technical device known as "baseline budgeting" has enabled policy-makers 
for 20 years to claim spending reductions while increasing spending. Everything, 
it seems - from omnibus spending bills to the budget reconciliation process 
- has been intended to hide from the public the true cost of Washington's actions. 
Just what does a $260 billion tax increase mean to the average family or the 
typical community?
<P>


The Heritage Foundation can now provide the answers. Thanks to a major half-million-dollar 
technical upgrade of our computer-analysis capabilities, Heritage's Roe Institute 
for Economic Policy Studies can now provide - overnight, if necessary - the 
kind of "hard numbers" and statistical analysis that can change the course 
of debate. Over and over again in 1994 - on the crime bill, on the flood of 
health-care reform plans that threatened to overwhelm Capitol Hill, on the 
fiscal year 1995 budget - Heritage showed that its data-analysis capabilities 
now rival those of the Congressional Budget Office and Office of Management 
and Budget. But that's not all; as often as possible, Heritage analysts attempted 
to make the numbers understandable, showing how various policy proposals would 
impact individual businesses, workers, families, and the cities and states 
where they live.

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">T</FONT>he <FONT SIZE = "+2">R</FONT>oe 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">I</FONT>nstitute</H3></CENTER>

Endowed by The Roe Foundation of Greenville, S.C., and other supporters, the 
Roe Institute staff specializes in budget and tax issues, the effects of regulation 
on the economy, environmental policy, competitiveness, and trade. Recommendations 
in 1994 included a call for a $500-per-child tax credit, repeal of the Social 
Security earnings tax, and reduction and indexation of the capital gains tax. 
The Roe Institute staff also identified numerous wasteful and inefficient government 
programs that should be cut back or eliminated and helped convince lawmakers 
of the merits of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). And, of 
course, they continued to argue persuasively for a balanced budget amendment 
to the Constitution, which became a major component of the House GOP's "Contract 
with America." 
<P>



<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">P</FONT>utting <FONT SIZE = "+2">F</FONT>amilies 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">F</FONT>irst</H3></CENTER>

Heritage's popular prosperity plan for America, called "Putting Families First," 
served as the basis for the alternative budget offered by House and Senate 
Republicans in 1994. While the plan, written by <a href="/heritage/s
taff/hodge.htm">Scott Hodge</a>, Heritage's Grover 
M. Hermann Fellow in Federal Budgetary Affairs, fell short in the 103rd Congress, 
most of its components were included in the "Contract with America."  
<P>



<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">R</FONT>egulatory <FONT SIZE = "+2">R</FONT>eform</H3></CENTER>

Roe Institute analysts also focused in 1994 on the regulatory burden placed 
on the economy, environmental policies that threaten private-property rights, 
and "unfunded mandates" - regulations the federal government imposes on businesses 
and state and local governments without paying for them. Among the most widely 
quoted studies published during the year was then Deputy Director Susan Eckerly's 
first-ever "Citizen's Guide to Regulation," which illustrated the real damage 
overzealous federal bureaucrats can do to the economy, businesses, and individuals.

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">H</FONT>ealth-<FONT SIZE = "+2">C</FONT>are 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">R</FONT>eform</H3></CENTER>

The expertise built up over five years of intensive research, aided by new 
data-processing capabilities, enabled Heritage's health-policy experts, headed 
by <a href="/heritage/staff/butler.htm">Stuart
Butler</a>, Vice President and Director, Domestic Policy Studies, and 
Deputy Director <a href="/heritage/staff/moffit.htm">Robert Moffit</a>, to play a significant role in the defeat of 
government-controlled health care in 1994. After providing Congress and the 
media with a wealth of material showing why the Clinton health-care plan would 
be a disaster, the Heritage analysts produced more than a dozen papers during 
a three-week summer period analyzing in detail the many alternative plans that 
flooded the marketplace after the collapse of the Clinton plan. The result: 
Any hope of placing one-seventh of the U.S. economy under the control of the 
federal government vanished.
<P>
Meanwhile, Heritage continued to argue that the best way to reform health care 
is to de-link health insurance from the workplace so individuals can own their 
own health policies and have a direct stake in their cost. This idea was the 
model for the Consumer Choice Health Security Act, sponsored in the 103rd Congress 
by Sen. Don Nickles (R-OK) and Rep. Cliff Stearns (R-FL). 
<P>



<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">M</FONT>ending <FONT SIZE = "+2">A</FONT>merica's 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">F</FONT>abric</H3></CENTER>

Even as Heritage Welfare and Family Issues Analyst <a href="/heritage/staff/rector.htm">Robert Rector</a> was exposing 
President Clinton's welfare-reform plan as another expansion of the welfare 
state, Cultural Policy Analyst <a href="/heritage/staff/fagan.htm">Patrick Fagan</a> was helping focus the nation's 
attention on the connection between the startling rise in illegitimate births 
and other social pathologies, such as crime and failure in school. In both 
the House and Senate, 1994 saw the introduction of legislation based on Rector's 
research and recommendations. Many of these same ideas - such as banning increased 
benefits for unwed mothers under age 21 who have additional children, requiring 
welfare recipients to work for their benefits, and putting an overall cap on 
welfare spending - were included in the House GOP's "Contract with America."

Also in 1994, Heritage Distinguished Fellow in Cultural Policy Studies <a href="/heritage/staff/bennett.htm">William 
Bennett</a>'s "Index of Leading Cultural Indicators" was updated, expanded, and 
published as a quality paperback by Touchstone Books, a division of Simon and 
Schuster. Americans now have at their fingertips the information they need 
to monitor long-term trends in America's social health. Bennett's "The Book 
of Virtues," meanwhile, remained on The New York Times bestseller list throughout 
the year.

         



</DOC>
