<HTML>
<TITLE>1994 Annual Report - Foreign and Defense Policy -- Heritage</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2><I><FONT SIZE = "+3">R</FONT>esearch</I></H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><H3><I><FONT SIZE = "+2">F</FONT>oreign and <FONT SIZE = "+2">D</FONT>efense 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">P</FONT>olicy</I></H3></CENTER>

<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>
"The Clinton administration does take national interests into account when 
formulating foreign policy. The trouble is, they are frequently the interests 
of other nations," Lawrence Di Rita, Deputy Director of Foreign and Defense 
Policy Studies, told reporters in one of several well-attended briefings in 
1994. 
<P>

<p>
Heritage analysts throughout the year continued their efforts to bring needed 
clarity and focus to America's meandering foreign policy. The big picture was 
provided by the updated monograph, "<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/safe.html">A Safe and Prosperous America</a>," which went 
into a second printing in 1994. With more than 10,000 copies in print, the 
global blueprint is now used by more than two dozen universities and graduate 
schools, including America's war colleges, as a primer on foreign policy and 
national security. The book explains how U.S. national interests should be 
used to establish foreign policy goals, how to evaluate potential threats to 
those interests, and how to build and maintain the military forces needed to 
respond to potential threats.
<P>

<p>
Individual papers during the year examined the dangers of putting U.S. forces 
under foreign command as part of U.N. "peacekeeping" missions, warned of the 
danger of cutting too deeply into the U.S. defense budget, urged the United 
States not to abandon the idea of building missile defenses, and developed 
a strategy for revamping the U.S. foreign-aid program.

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">A</FONT>merican <FONT SIZE = "+2">T</FONT>rader 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">I</FONT>nitiative</H3></CENTER>

With the approval of  the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) shortly 
after Thanksgiving, Heritage's ongoing efforts to promote the global expansion 
of free trade reached another important milestone. The long march, however, 
is far from over: Of the 101 countries ranked on Heritage's "Index of Economic 
Freedom," released at year's end, just 25 had free or "mostly free" trading 
policies.
<P>


One of the main objectives of Heritage's two-year-old American Trader Initiative, 
a joint effort involving both the business and policy communities,  is the 
liberalization of the rules governing international commerce. The program is 
based on the belief not only that free trade furthers U.S. national interests 
by creating new business opportunities for American companies, but that economic 
freedom helps spawn political freedom as well. The long-term goal of the program 
is a free-trade area encompassing both the Western Hemisphere and Pacific Rim. 
<P>

<P>

In addition to their work on the GATT agreement, Heritage trade experts pushed 
the administration to make trade liberalization the centerpiece of two important 
1994 summit meetings: the November meeting in Indonesia of the Asia-Pacific 
Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum and the December '94 "Summit of the Americas" 
in Miami. In both cases, the United States and its trading partners agreed 
to phase out all trade barriers - by the year 2005 in the Americas and by the 
year 2020 in the Asia-Pacific region.

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">I</FONT>ndex of <FONT SIZE = "+2">E</FONT>conomic 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">F</FONT>reedom</H3></CENTER>

Just one day after The Heritage Foundation released its first-ever global report 
card on economic freedom, Sen. Mitch McConnell 
(R-KY), incoming Chairman of the Appropriations Committee's Foreign Operations 
Subcommittee, suggested major changes in America's $14 billion-per-year foreign 
aid program. As Heritage Vice President and Director of Foreign Policy and 
Defense Studies Kim Holmes told reporters at a Dec. 16 media briefing, most 
U.S. development aid is being given to countries "that don't deserve it" because 
their state-controlled economies will waste it. Countries with free economies, 
he noted, generally don't need U.S. aid. 
<P>


<P>
Earlier in the week, Holmes had said in a Wall Street Journal op-ed page article 
that "People in Angola, Haiti, Mozambique and Ukraine are not poor because 
wealthy people in the West haven't been generous toward them." They are poor, 
he said, because their governments' "misguided economic policies" retard economic 
growth and prosperity.
<P>

<P>

This long-overdue debate over U.S. foreign-aid policy was precipitated  by 
the publication of "<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/indx.html">The Index of Economic Freedom</a>," a 258-page comparative 

analysis compiled by Heritage's <a href="/heritage/staff/johnson.htm">Bryan Johnson</a> and Thomas Sheehy.  Released on Dec. 12, the "Index" examines the economies of 101 countries. As Investor's 
Business Daily noted, Heritage created the "Index," which is similar to Freedom 
House's annual country-by-country survey of political freedom, "to help U.S. 
and international policy-makers better craft their aid policies. If aid money 
is given to a country that is following poor economic policies, the chances 
are good it will be wasted or do little, if any, good."

 

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">A</FONT>sian <FONT SIZE = "+2">S</FONT>tudies 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">C</FONT>enter</H3></CENTER>

Not surprisingly, four of the ten countries with the best ratings on Heritage's 
"Index of Economic Freedom" - and eight of the top 20 - were from the Asia-Pacific 
region. When the United States, Canada, and Chile are included - all of which 
belong to the 18-member Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum (APEC) - the 
more broadly defined region boasts 11 of the 20 freest economies in the world. 
The APEC nations also now account for 40 percent of all global trade.
<P>

<P>

In recognition of the growing importance of the Asia-Pacific community, The 
Heritage Foundation's Asian Studies Center was established in 1983. Today, 
the Center is recognized on both sides of the Pacific as one of the most important 
research and policy centers on diplomatic, economic, and security issues affecting 
the United States and Asia.
<P>
While trade and security issues dominated the calendar, Director <a href="/heritage/staff/przystup.htm">James Przystup</a> 
and the Asian Studies Center staff made a strong case in 1994 for significantly 
upgrading U.S. relations with the Republic of China on Taiwan, a booming country 
of more than 20 million people that continues to be treated as a second-class 
world citizen by the United States. Visiting Fellow Daryl Plunk and Richard 
V. Allen, National Security Advisor to President Reagan and Chairman of the 
Asian Studies Center's Advisory Council, provided Washington with much-needed 
guidance on defusing the growing crisis over North Korea's nuclear-weapons 
program. And Policy Analyst <a href="/heritage/staff/oquinn.htm">Robert O'Quinn</a> offered the White House an agenda 
for the mid-November APEC summit, proposing that leaders of the 18 member countries 
set a "time certain" for establishing a trans-Pacific free-trade area, the 
topic of an Oct. 27 Asian Studies Center conference featuring Nancy Adams, 
U.S. Trade Representative for APEC Affairs, and Paula Stern, former Chairwoman 
of the U.S. International Trade Commission.   
<P>

<P>

The Heritage-sponsored Washington Roundtable for the Asia-Pacific Press (WRAPP) 
hosted several "newsmaker" breakfasts during the year. Rep. Floyd Spence (R-SC), 
then ranking Republican on the House Armed Services Committee, discussed the 
North Korean nuclear threat. Political analysts Victor Kamber, a liberal Democrat, 
 and Bradley O'Leary, a conservative Republican, discussed the congressional 
elections. And Heritage's <a href="/heritage/staff/holmes.htm">Kim Holmes</a> discussed "The Index of Economic Freedom" 
and proposed changes in U.S. foreign aid policy. 
<P>
Important financial support for many of the Asian Studies Center's programs 
continues to be provided by the Korea Foundation Endowment for Korean Studies. 


  

<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">R</FONT>ussian <FONT SIZE = "+2">R</FONT>eform</H3></CENTER>

Russian political scientist Evgueni Volk was appointed coordinator of the Heritage 
Foundation's Moscow Office in 1994, succeeding Senior Fellow Jeffrey Gayner, 
who had directed the office since its opening in 1993. 
<P>
Heritage's Moscow office is now seen in Russia as a neutral meeting ground 
where reformers can work out their public differences in private. This is done 
through the Heritage Reform Forum, a monthly "summit" meeting of Moscow's leading 
reform politicians, businessmen, and journalists.    
<P>
The Moscow Office also is involved in more traditional policy analysis. Volk 
and Salvatori Fellow in Russian and Eurasian Studies Ariel Cohen distribute 
draft legislation being considered by the Russian parliament to experts in 
the United States, Europe, and Russia. Comments and suggestions are then sent 
to members of the parliament and appropriate staff. During 1994, legislation 
on defense, "peacekeeping" operations, lobbying, and non-governmental organizations 
was refined in this way.

<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></BODY>
</HTML>
         



