<HTML>
<TITLE>1994 Annual Report - Public Relations</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2><I><FONT SIZE = "+3">M</FONT>arketing</I></H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><B>Public Relations</B></CENTER><P>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>
<p>
"This is Mike Rosen, KOA, Denver broadcasting live from the studios of The 
Heritage Foundation in Washington."
<P>
Those and similar words were heard frequently by talk-radio listeners around 
the country in 1994, following the opening of Heritage's new broadcast facilities. 
Equipped with state-of-the-art equipment, the studio enables talk-show hosts 
to do live broadcasts from Heritage's Capitol Hill headquarters.
<P>
Heritage already was becoming a "home away from home" for talk show hosts visiting 
the nation's capital, with live broadcasts during the year by Boston's Earl 
Jackson, Seattle's Dave Ross, and Richmond's Blanquita Walsh Cullum, among 
others. The remote broadcast facilities were opened to meet the growing demand. 
<P>

<P>
Heritage's work with talk radio, part of a broader broadcast media program, 
began several years ago - long before most other organizations realized the 
potential impact of this alternative communications medium.  
<P>
During 1994, Heritage experts made hundreds of guest appearances on radio talk 
shows, on  major television news and public affairs shows, and on the America's 
Talking, CNN, CNBC, C-SPAN, and National Empowerment Television (NET) call-in 
shows. Dozens of Heritage lectures and events also were seen on C-SPAN.  
<P>
The work with the broadcast media is just one facet of Heritage's wide-ranging 
communications program. Intended to familiarize political activists, opinion 
leaders, and the broader general public with the positive message of contemporary 
conservatism, the program also includes the Heritage Speakers Bureau, Heritage's 
pioneering "op-ed page" program, and a variety of other activities aimed at 
specialized audiences.
<P>
<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">O</FONT>pinion and <FONT SIZE = "+2">C</FONT>ommentary</H3></CENTER>

<P>
The op-ed page program provides Heritage analysts and executives with an opportunity 
to give their views on the important issues of the day without having to go 
through the usual news "filtering" process. During 1994, Heritage bylines appeared 
in hundreds of  U.S. and overseas newspapers, including the Wall Street Journal, 
Washington Post, New York Times, Los Angeles Times, Chicago Tribune, Washington 
Times,  International Herald Tribune, USA Today, Buffalo News, Charlotte Observer, 
Oklahoma City Oklahoman, Orange County Register, and Pittsburgh Tribune Review. 
  <P>


Heritage also continued its relationship with Knight-Ridder/Tribune News Service, 
one of the largest supplemental newswires in the country, which distributes 
Heritage op-ed page essays every week as part of a <a href="/heritage/commentary/welcome.html">commentary</a> package.
<P>
<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">T</FONT>argeted <FONT SIZE = "+2">C</FONT>ommunications</H3></CENTER>
<P>
While most Heritage public relations activities involve the mass media, targeted 
communications also are important. 
<P>
The Speakers Bureau, for example, helped bring Heritage's conservative message 
to dozens of college campuses and business, professional, and civic organizations 
in 1994. While their primary focus remained  research, writing, and policy, 
Heritage analysts and executives met collectively with thousands of individuals 
around the country who had come to hear them speak. Among the many institutions 
providing Heritage speakers with a platform were the American Association of 
Colleges and Universities, American Society of Association Executives, Chautauqua 
Institution, Close Up Foundation, Colorado State University, and Grove City 
College, where Ed Feulner delivered the 1994 commencement address. Others included 
the Inter-American Defense College, National Petroleum Refiners Association, 
National Youth Leadership Forum, People to People, Rubber Manufacturers Association, 
St. Lawrence University, Texas A&M University, and World Affairs Council of 
Orange County. 
<P>

<P>

In addition to <a href="http://www.townhall.com/">Town Hall</a>, the "interactive" computer network co-owned by 
Heritage and National Review magazine, Heritage in 1994 was included in "Profnet," 
a national computer information network linking U.S. newsrooms with colleges 
and universities and a handful of think tanks around the country.
<P>
Heritage also continued to work closely in 1994 with Westcott Communications, 
a major publicly traded company that provides information and produces workplace 
training videos for corporate managers and executives in a number of specialized 
fields, including health care and financial management.
<P>


And Heritage successfully relaunched the Washington Roundtable for the Asia-Pacific 
Press (WRAPP). The organization, which had existed for several years in the 
1980s, is intended to help provide Washington-based Asian correspondents with 
better access to the Washington policymaking .
<P>
<BR><HR WIDTH="30%"><BR><CENTER><A HREF="/heritage/hbut.map"><IMG SRC="/heritage/hbut.gif" ISMAP BORDER=0></A></CENTER></BODY>
</HTML>


