Content-length: 18185
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<TITLE>1994 Annual Report - Chairman's Report -- Heritage</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H2><I><FONT SIZE = "+3">C</FONT>hairman's <FONT SIZE = "+3">R</FONT>eport</I></H2></CENTER>

<CENTER><B>Making a Difference</B></CENTER>
<P>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>
<P>
In August, at the end of a mind-numbing, daylong congressional hearing on welfare 
reform, Heritage Foundation Senior Policy Analyst <a href="/heritage/staff/rector.htm">Robert Rector</a> began his remarks.
<P>
"The `War on Poverty' has been an incredibly costly failure," he told the House 
Human Relations Subcommittee.
<P>
The "welfare state" is made up of some 75 programs targeted to low-income and 
poor Americans, with a total annual cost exceeding $324 billion; the nation 
has spent $5.3 trillion since the War on Poverty began, he said.
<P>
"What are the names of these programs? Do you have a listing of these programs?" 
interrupted the Subcommittee Chairman, Rep. Harold Ford, Tennessee Democrat.
<P>
"They're listed in my testimony," said Mr. Rector, who went on to explain that 
the average tax-paying household spent $3,400 in 1993 to combat poverty and 
that by 1999, the nation could be spending $550 billion a year on welfare.
<P>
"I'm going to correct you now," Mr. Ford interrupted again. The subcommittee, 
he explained, was only interested in hearing about Aid to Families with Dependent 
Children (AFDC), food stamps, and Medicaid.
<P>
"With all due respect ... you are not going to come here to this committee 
and give us these numbers," Mr. Ford said. "You are not going to leave the 
public perception that we are spending all these billions and billions of dollars 
on welfare."
<P>

<P>

<P>
The above story was recalled in <a href="http://www.townhall.com/townhall/Wash_Times/">The Washington Times</a> in a major year-end feature 
on welfare reform. Despite Congressman Ford's denials, Heritage's Robert Rector 
is correct: The official Congressional Research Service includes more than 
80 distinct programs in its inventory of "means-tested"  federal welfare programs. 
<P>

Like others at Heritage, Rector spends much of his time challenging conventional 
wisdom. You can't "end welfare as we know it," he says, unless you first understand 
both the nature of poverty and the patchwork system cobbled together during 
the past 30 years to fight it. Rector is one of the few in Washington who understands 
both, and the "fix" he proposed in his August testimony - and in numerous speeches 
and talk-radio appearances throughout the year - can be seen in the House GOP's 
"Contract with America." As <a href="http://www.townhall.com/nationalreview/">National Review</a> described Rector's proposal in 
a Dec. 31, 1994, editorial: "The Heritage Foundation-inspired Talent-Faircloth 
bill takes 65 welfare programs with 10,000 pages of regulations and boils them 
down to one block grant with a short set of guiding principles." The rest of 
the story will be written in 1995.
<P>
<HR SIZE = 3 WIDTH = 30%>
<P>

<P>

Throughout 1994, Heritage Foundation analysts repeatedly challenged both the 
conventional wisdom and the status quo. 
<P>
In a few instances, Heritage's role was primarily that of honest critic. The 
administration's crime bill, for example, almost failed after Heritage's Scott 
Hodge examined the fine print and found that the bulk of the funds would be 
spent on spurious "crime prevention" measures, such as arts and crafts and 
midnight basketball leagues. Heritage also was a vigorous critic of the administration's 
health-care plan, its re-regulation of the economy, its misguided foreign policy, 
and the haphazard way in which it has reduced defense spending.
<P>
In most cases, Heritage analysts were ready with concrete alternatives to the 
flawed proposals. The Heritage Consumer Choice Health Plan, for example, provided 
Washington with a principled private-sector solution to America's health-care 
problems - a solution that would increase the choices available to most Americans 
while still helping to control medical costs. Heritage's foreign-policy blueprint, 
"<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/safe.html">A Safe and Prosperous America</a>,"  brought to international affairs a sense 
of mission and purpose lacking in the administration's foreign policy. Heritage's 
updated prosperity plan for America, "Putting Families First" - a comprehensive 
program for strengthening family finances, promoting capital expansion, and 
balancing the budget - served as the basis of the alternative budget offered 
by congressional Republicans. And "The Index of Economic Freedom," released 
at year end, not only showed how the U.S. foreign aid program has gone astray, 
but offered a focused free-market approach to revitalizing the wasteful program.
<P>

<P>

There were even instances when the administration and The Heritage Foundation 
found themselves in agreement. John M. Olin Senior Fellow <a href="/heritage/staff/cobb.htm">Joe Cobb</a>, for example, 
played a pivotal role in the debate over the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade (GATT) and was publicly credited by both the White House and the media 
with helping to blunt protectionist attacks on the global trade pact.
<P>
Throughout its 21-year history, The Heritage Foundation has always tried to 
make a difference. As the following stories show, the entire Heritage organization 
- research; government, media, and business relations; the lectures and seminars 
program; Policy Review; and Heritage's more than 200,000 community ambassadors: 
its members - all play a role in Heritage's efforts to change the direction 
of public policy. Sometimes, the entire organization may be involved in a project. 
Other times, a single analyst or a single study - when properly marketed to 
key members of Congress and the right mix of media opinion-leaders - can change 
the course of the debate.
<P>
<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">I</FONT>t's a <FONT SIZE = "+2">C</FONT>rime</H3></CENTER>
<P>
Congress's bitter summer debate over the administration's crime bill, for example, 
might never have taken place if it weren't for the tenacity of Heritage's <a href="/heritage/staff/bennett.htm">Bill 
Bennett</a> and <a href="/heritage/staff/hodge.htm">Scott Hodge</a>.  
<P>
When the anti-crime package was first introduced, the bill was expected to 
sail through both houses of Congress by wide margins. After all, with drug-related 
street crime running rampant in most urban areas, what politician wanted to 
be seen as an opponent of crime control? Then Bennett, the former Secretary 
of Education and U.S. drug czar, and Hodge, Heritage's Grover M. Hermann Fellow 
in Federal Budgetary Affairs, took a closer look at the proposal. 
<P>
Bennett, the first public figure to criticize the proposal, found that the 
federal government was once again usurping the power and authority of state 
and local government. Hodge's analysis struck closer to home. Rather than put 
100,000 new police officers on America's streets, as the administration claimed, 
Hodge found that the crime bill would finance only 20,000 police officers - 
leaving state and local government with the rest of the tab. [A subsequent 
Heritage study showed each state exactly how much.] The remainder of the more 
than $30 billion Congress was being asked to approve, Hodge's analysis showed, 
was earmarked for various "crime prevention" initiatives - urban pork - that 
duplicated existing programs, none of which had done much to deter crime. 
<P>
Hodge's findings were marketed aggressively to the news media and immediately 
vaulted to the top of talk radio's list of hottest topics. Critics on Capitol 
Hill quickly joined the fray, and support for the legislation went into free 
fall - all because of a single study that looked beyond the rhetoric at the 
details. So compelling were the Heritage data that the White House communications 
office issued a formal rebuttal in an effort to discredit Heritage's analysis. 
This prompted several reporters to do some homework of their own. To the great 
consternation of the White House, they found that Hodge was correct. As a Harris 
poll later confirmed, a majority of the public got the Heritage message: the 
crime bill was more about pork than about fighting crime. 
<P>
The White House effort to discredit Heritage failed - and the crime bill nearly 
failed with it. In the end, the legislation was approved by a very narrow margin, 
but congressional pork-busters are revisiting the bill in 1995.
<P>
<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">A</FONT> <FONT SIZE = "+2">S</FONT>ick 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">H</FONT>ealth <FONT SIZE = "+2">P</FONT>lan </H3></CENTER> 
<P>
Heritage's involvement in the health-care debate began in 1989 before there 
was a national health-care debate. Since the publication of that original Heritage 
Foundation monograph, "A National Health System for America" (Stuart M. Butler 
and Edmund F. Haislmaier, editors), Heritage has published more than 50 papers 
on the various problems plaguing the health financing system and the proposals 
- good and bad - for fixing those problems. During the summer of 1994, for 
example, as Congress rushed ahead with alternatives to the mortally wounded 
Clinton Health Security Act,  Heritage's research team worked around the clock 
to offer detailed analyses of proposed alternatives. In one three-week period 
in August, Heritage published and publicized 12 different studies detailing 
the serious problems with various health-care proposals.
<P>
In the end,  the entire effort to increase the government's control over health 
care in America collapsed. The final chapter was a war of words over which 
reform plan would give ordinary Americans the same kind of health coverage 
enjoyed by government officials. 
<P>
It was a war Heritage's analysts and media specialists had spent all year preparing 
for - because only Heritage could win this war. As Heritage asked in a widely 
published advertisement: "Hillary Rodham Clinton Has It. George Stephanopoulos 
Has It. Donna Shalala and all Cabinet Members Have It. Ted Kennedy Has It. 
So Why Can't All Americans Have What They Have?" 
<P>


What they have, we explained, is "a health benefits system that allows them 
to choose among dozens of competing health-care insurers and providers, works 
with a minimum of regulation ... and because it relies on the principles of 
choice and competition, has successfully controlled costs." This was important 
because just one reform proposal, the Heritage Consumer Choice Health Plan 
(and its legislative version, the Nickles-Stearns Consumer Choice Health Security 
Act), was similar in design to the Federal Employee Health Benefits Program 
(FEHBP). 
<P>
In truth, FEHBP is a government program in name only; all benefits are provided 
by private insurers who compete with one another for business. By focusing 
attention on FEHBP - in hundreds of radio talk-show appearances, speeches, 
congressional Town Hall meetings, Capitol Hill briefings, and newspaper editorial 
board meetings - Heritage experts were able not only to point to an existing 
market-based system that works, but to demonstrate the insincerity of Washington 
officials who would impose a government-run system on most Americans while 
retaining a consumer-based system for themselves.
<P>

<P>
With time running out, most major sponsors of reform legislation - including 
President Clinton, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy (D-MA), and other backers of government-run 
health care - had no choice but to claim their proposals' kinship to FEHBP, 
even if it wasn't true. Those who had been closely following the health-care 
debate knew better; only the Heritage plan - based on the principles of individual 
choice and market competition  - followed the successful model.
<P>
While support for the other reform plans withered as the details became better 
known, support for the Heritage approach increased as details became more widely 
known. The support was as broad as it was deep. Some 25 members of the Senate 
and an equal number of House members co-sponsored the Nickles-Stearns bill. 
The Heritage approach also was endorsed by several state medical societies, 
a national association of nursing homes, and more than 150 newspapers, magazines, 
and columnists. Meanwhile, some 700 individual doctors became personal advocates 
of the consumer-choice plan as members of the Heritage Foundation Physician's 
Council.
<P>
<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">B</FONT>ottoms <FONT SIZE = "+2">U</FONT>p</H3></CENTER>
<P>
When Heritage defense analysts <a href="/heritage/staff/spring.htm">Baker Spring</a> and John Luddy warned in March 
that the Clinton administration had underfunded its own defense plan, the so-called 
"Bottom-Up Review," by a five-year total of $100 billion, the White House and 
Pentagon cried foul.
<P>
A few months later, they - and the rest of Washington - discovered that The 
Heritage Foundation is true to its word when it describes itself as a "conservative" 
think tank. Congress's auditing arm, the General Accounting Office (GAO), took 
its own look at the mismatch between the administration's defense plan and 
the Pentagon budget and found that Heritage's $100 billion estimate had been 
very conservative. The shortfall, GAO said, was closer to $150 billion.
<P>
After the GOP takeover of Congress - which catapulted two long-time friends 
of Heritage's,  Sen. Strom Thurmond and Rep. Floyd Spence, South Carolina Republicans, 
into the chairmanship of the Senate and House Armed Services committees - the 
administration suddenly "got religion" and admitted that the defense budget 
would have to be increased substantially in order to maintain military readiness. 
The increase the administration proposed was inadequate, but at least it was 
a start.
<P>
Heritage's analysts, meanwhile, continued to identify billions of dollars in 
non-defense pork that had been buried in the defense budget. Defense spending, 
no doubt, will be a major policy issue in 1995. 
<P>
<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">T</FONT>he <FONT SIZE = "+2">F</FONT>reshman 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">C</FONT>lass</H3></CENTER>
<P>
From the crush of reporters and the bank of television cameras lined up in 
the long, rectangular room, you would have thought that President Clinton or 
Pope John Paul II was present. Instead, the star attraction was a radio talk-show 
host. Not any talk-show host, mind you, but the king: Rush Limbaugh.
<P>
The occasion was The Heritage Foundation's orientation conference for newly 
elected members of the 104th Congress. For many of the more than 65 new members 
of the House and Senate who attended the three-day (Dec. 8-10) Baltimore conference, 
co-sponsored with Empower America, the conference was more like a family reunion. 
They already knew Heritage. One new congressman told <a href="/heritage/staff/feulner.html">Ed Feulner</a> he had refined 
his political philosophy over the years by reading <a href="/heritage/p_review/welcome.html">Policy Review</a>, Heritage's 
quarterly journal. Many of the others had used Heritage research during their 
campaigns.
<P>
No election in recent memory was more about issues and ideas than the contests 
that took place on Nov. 8, 1994. The House GOP's "Contract with America" - 
attacked by liberals throughout the campaign - provided voters with a concrete 
list of institutional and policy changes. As a number of reporters noted, many 
of the proposals had been seen before - in Heritage books and policy papers.
<P>
True to their promise, Congress's new Republican majority used the first day 
of the 104th Congress to perform surgery on the Congress itself. The "Contract 
with America" had promised a series of far-reaching changes "aimed at restoring 
the faith and trust of the American people in government." Virtually every 
one of these sweeping institutional changes - including a measure that would 
apply all U.S. laws to the Congress itself - had been proposed in Heritage's 
1993 book, "<a href="/townhall/townhall_shop/ruli.html">The Ruling Class</a>," and fleshed out in subsequent Heritage papers. 

<P>
As Seattle talk-show host Mike Siegel reminded his listeners in a week-long 
series of broadcasts from Heritage's radio studio the week after the election, 
the Heritage recipe for reforming Congress had been a popular staple on talk 
radio throughout 1994. Now these proposals - embraced by millions of ordinary 
Americans while bitterly opposed by much of official Washington - had made 
their way back to the Nation's Capital, and a new revolution in government 
had begun.
<P>
<CENTER><H3><FONT SIZE = "+2">A</FONT>n <FONT SIZE = "+2">A</FONT>merican 
<FONT SIZE = "+2">O</FONT>riginal </H3></CENTER>   
<P>
What follows is a report on the people and programs that make The Heritage 
Foundation an American original. 
<P>

<p>


None of the programs should be viewed in a vacuum. The wide range of activities 
is possible only because of the encouragement and active support of Heritage's 
donors. In a city long dominated by the liberal left, Heritage's research papers 
command attention not just because they are timely and thorough, but because 
they are  professionally marketed and always on the mark. And Heritage's lectures 
and seminars, Policy Review and the Resource Bank all help widen the conservative 
circle. 
<P>

<p>
The Heritage Foundation's continuing efforts to build a better America and 
a safer world involve more than 150 dedicated employees and more than 200,000 
members who express their confidence each year by providing the financial support 
that has helped Heritage make a difference for 21 years. n
<P>
David R. Brown, M.D.<BR>
<i>Chairman</i><BR>
<I>March 16, 1994</I>
