<title>Look-Out Study, Round 2 Questionnaire, Section 1</title>
<body bgcolor="#96E1FA">
<hr><p>
<center><font size=+3>1996 GLOBAL LOOK-OUT PANEL</font>
<p><hr><p>
<font size=+2>ROUND 2 QUESTIONNAIRE<p><b>SECTION I</b></font><p>
<font size=+1>SUMMARY OF SUGGESTED DEVELOPMENTS</font></center><p>
<br>
A summary of all of the developments suggested by respondents to the first round is presented in
this
section. Your judgment about the likelihood and importance of each of these developments is
requested. In addition please provide your judgment about the leadership category that should be
the
most responsible for "handling" the development.<p>

If you respond by email, there is no need to duplicate the entire section below: just repeat the
development number, followed by the three numbers that reflect your judgement from the three
scales
below.<p>

1. Likelihood that the development as described by a Round 1 participant is underway. In
answering
this question, please use the following key:<p>

<ul><ul><ul><ul>
         <TABLE WIDTH= BORDER=0>
<TR><TD>1 = almost certain </TD><TD> </TD><TD><ul><ul> 4 = unlikely</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>2 = likely </TD><TD> </TD><TD><ul><ul> 5 = almost impossible</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>3 = as likely as not</TD><TD></TD></TR>
</TABLE><p></ul></ul></ul></ul>   

2. Relative importance of the development, using these criteria: severity or amount of benefit,
number
of people who may ultimately be affected, possibility that policy can make a difference
(susceptibility
to our influence if we act in time), imminence of impacts, permanence of effects, and lack of a
responsible decision maker (making attention to the development important to attract responsible
decision maker or leader).  Please use this key in answering this question:<p>

<ul><ul><ul><ul>
         <TABLE WIDTH= BORDER=0>
<TR><TD> 1 = urgently important</TD><TD> </TD><TD><ul><ul> 4 =
unimportant</TD></TR>
<TR><TD> 2 = important</TD><TD></TD><TD><ul><ul> 5 = trivial</TD></TR>
<TR><TD> 3 = modest</TD><TD></TD></TR>
</TABLE><p></ul></ul></ul></ul>    

3. Agency or group that should be primarily responsible for leading strategy to address
development:
<p><ul>

          1 = Individuals or small groups with common interests<br>
          2 = Governments and government agencies<br>
          3 = Non governmental agencies (foundations, large special interest groups, 
                    universities, international NGOs, etc.)<br>
          4 = Corporations<br>
          5 = United Nations System (specify organ: Secretariat, General Assembly, UNDP, Security
Council, World Bank, UNESCO, UNICEF, UNU, UNEP, WHO, etc.<br>
          6= Not clear<br>
          7= Other (specify)
<p></ul>

Please write three numbers after each item. The first will represent your judgment about
likelihood,
the second, importance, and the third, responsible organizations.<p>

Please add comments, if you wish, at the end of the list. Particularly for those items that you have
judged both
relatively almost certain and urgently important, please note some consequences that you think
may flow from
the development and some appropriate strategies or goals.<p>

You may, of course, add other  developments to the list. These developments should have already
begun in some
small way, and have important implications for the future.  For these newly added items, please
also include your
view of possible consequences, possible policies or goals and any notes and sources of
information about the
developments you have identified. Items suggested in Round 1 are listed in the table below:<p>

<HR><P>


Each development is preceded with an index number assigned to it upon arrive at the Project's
coordinating office.  To avoid long fax, airmail, and email, just write this number followed by your
section of the three numbers.  For example: 155-2-1-4 would mean development number 155 is
likely,
and if it occurs, then it is urgently important, and corporations should lead the strategy to make
the
development evolve in the best possible way.<p>

<font size=+2><i><b>One-Line Summaries of developments from <br>
Round 1 of the Global Look-Out Study</i></b></font><p>
<font  size=+1><i><b>Domain 1: Demographics and Human Resources</b></i><p></font>

     <b>Population:</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      24. High population growth among poor nations and
people.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      25. The growth of use and effectiveness of social
marketing.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      31, 59. Development of a means of extending life span by
at least 25% through genetics or bio-drugs.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      38. Population growth seen as necessary to achieve
economic growth and human vitality.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      79. Proposed pensions schemes and incentives to invite
parents to have fewer or no
children.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      92.Discovery that the maintenance of the tips of DNA is
common to "immortal cells" (sperm,
egg, and cancer cells) and
     hence, we may learn how to genetically engineer the age of different parts of the body.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      114, 132. Increasing life span and changing age
composition of the population.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      122. Development and widespread availability of a
chemical which permits the selection of a
male or female child
     before conception.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      138. Drastic reduction in the quality of human population
in the Third World in the next 15-20
years as a result of  hunger, growth of infections and chronic diseases.<p>

     <b>    Migration</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      34. Ecological migration from countries affected by
desertification, floods, deforestation.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      52. Migration of large numbers of people from the
developing world to the developed world
and from rural to urban
     settings<p>

     <b>    Medicine and Health</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      18. Gene therapy becoming a conventional therapeutic
approach in medicine; initiative in the
genetic approach to human
     health (GAHH)<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      19. Completion of the Human Genome Mapping Project,
leading to the capacity for predictive
diagnosis and anticipation
     of behavioral propensities.  <br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      32. The spread of sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) to
women and young girls<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      48. Increased frequency of re-emerging and new
diseases.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      58. Some governments abdicating their responsibilities in
public health as a result of budget
contractions.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      108. Presence of HIV in 25% of the adult population of 
essentially all cities in sub-Sahara
Africa.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      113. Increasing resistance to antibiotics.<p>

     <b>    Food and Water</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      39. Increased food scarcity owing to population growth
and a general inability to increase
production to keep up with
     that growth<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      40. Increased scarcity of fresh water, possibly exacerbated
by global warming.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      61. Increasing need to improve water resources, for larger
populations, and to alleviate
demand and pollution pressures on existing waterways.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      102. Novel protein foods significantly replacing meat.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      119. China's buying of food on the world market impedes
the ability of poorer countries to
provide themselves with
     food.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      140. Deterioriation of public and personal hygiene (public
sanitation of water and waste
streams).<p>

     <b>    Education and Leisure</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      22,  84.  Proliferation of information technology displacing
many low- skilled, well-paid
workers in the developed
     world; simultaneously, shortage of people with adequate skills.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      66. Distance learning increasingly practical, through the
Internet and World Wide Web
multimedia capabilities.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      71. 'Learning Organization' concepts increasingly
recognized as the most innovative and useful
new management
     technique of the past decade.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      73. Through satellite TV/Computer links, instant access to
essentially everyone, and to all the
information that is
     available in the world.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      93. Integration of human consciousness and technology:
increasingly technology is being put
into and on the human
     body; and intelligent technology is being put in the environment.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      125. As a result of entry of many countries into the
post-industrial era, growth of
unemployment and  free time, and the
     division of the population into "able" and "unable."<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      139. Non-technological development of natural capabilities
for increasing the effectiveness of
the human brain by    three-four times (now 6-8%).<p>

<font  size=+1><i><b>Domain 2: Environmental Change and Biodiversity</b></i><p></font>

     <b>    Pollution</b> <br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      4. Development of affordable cars that produce 1/3 the
amount of CO2, are otherwise
pollution free and do not require
     petroleum. <br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      27. Doubling of the demand for energy in less than 30
years as a result of population and
economic growth<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      30, 135. Industrialization of China, India, etc., increasing
the load on the environment by a
factor of five to ten.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      83. Gridlock: Excessive urban motor vehicle traffic
congestion, resulting pollution, and
political backlash.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      109. Increasing appearance of estrogen mimicking
compounds in the environment resulting
from the breakdown of
     plastics, insecticides, and other manufactured materials.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      112, 116. Environmental issues on the horizon include:
chlorine, electromagnetic fields, life
cycle assessment,
     ultraviolet exposure, environmental hormones, and biological contamination standards for
drinking water.<p>

     <b>    Biodiversity</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      8. Increasing number of micro-organisms that are immune
to pharmaceuticals or
pesticides.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      49. Essentially full control of the genetic and biochemical
processes of living organisms<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      50. Adoption of an effects-oriented approach to the
monitoring of ecological systems, rather
than measuring
     contaminants or physico-chemical properties.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      60. Initiating a search for and cataloging the vast variety of
bacteria of the planet<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      127. Destruction of the environment, especially loss of
biodiversity.<p>

     <b>    Sustainability</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      14. A false sense of security about the extent of natural
resources.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      20, 21. Increased understanding and education about
interactions between human activities
and the environment; e.g.
     Environment and Climate Program (CEC) and Consortia for International Earth Science
Information Network
     (CEISIN)<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      41. Corporate support for sustainable concepts <br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      86, 87.  Sustainable communities; e.g. China's
Comprehensive Experimental Communities for
Sustainable
     Development, and Sustainable Technology Demonstration Project<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      142. Increasing pressure under the seabed associated with
the plates' movement, accumulating
energy to cause         earthquakes, especially around Tokyo area.<p>

<b>    Policy</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      89. Key opinion shapers making light of the risk of global
climate change; the existence of
uncertainty is being widely
     interpreted as meaning that there will be little or no effect.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      105. Environmental security becoming an important
concern in foreign policy.<p>

<font  size=+1><i><b>Domain 3: Technological Capacity</b></i><p></font>

     <b>    Information, Communications</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      15. Extremely smart and flexible computers; real artificial
intelligence<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      111. Availability of continuous speech, user-independent,
computer voice input systems
making possible a new sort
     of human to machine interface that requires no training.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      136. The spread of the Internet. <p>

<b>    Biomedicine and Psychiatry</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      6. Development of brain-like intelligent systems using
neural networks, to help achieve a more
functional understanding
     of human intelligence.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      47. Personal health history records in the form of
intelligent credit cards<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      62. Symbiosis with the computer - even via the
keyboard.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      104. New understanding of the functioning of the brain,
leading, perhaps to understanding of
self consciousness..<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      123. Ability to change basic human characteristics,
through genetic engineering or chemical
interventions.<p>

     <b>    Search for Extra Terrestrial Intelligence</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      16, 45. Successful scientific search for extraterrestrial
intelligence.<P>

     <b>    Search for Knowledge</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      7. Recognition that there is far more to learn in physics
and other disciplines, that the frontiers
of knowledge are
     unbounded.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      26, 43.  So-called 'cold fusion' (which is probably neither);
tapping new energy sources by
several different routes.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      46. Development of faster than light travel.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      51. Decreasing human skills development in concept
formation and communication in an
increasingly complex
     world.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      56. Need for scientific and philosophical thinking to
explore the ethical foundation of advanced
sciences and the
     scientific foundation of contemporary ethic. <br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      141. New kinds of knowledge production and
certification, new carriers of knowledge (think
of environmental          groups as one example).  <p>

     <b>    Machines</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      5. Airplanes that can reach orbit at much lower costs than
current methods.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      42. Development of viable hybrid automotive
technology.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      100. Power Relay Satellites in geosynchronous orbit, Solar
Power Satellites in Earth orbits,
and Lunar Power Satellites
     on the lunar surface.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      101. Satellite systems providing virtually instant,
ubiquitous communications connectivity
between both fixed and
     mobile users, including telephony, video, data, and multi-media.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      110. Nanotechnology (or molecular engineering) --
construction atom by atom on the scale of
a nanometer (one billionth
     of a meter).<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      133. Aging of existing nuclear power plants.<p>

<font  size=+1><i><b>Domain 4: Giovernance and Conflict</b></i><p></font>

     <b>    War and Political Instability</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      11. The threat of weapons in outer space.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      23, 33.  Religious, racial, ethnic, ideological wars such as
in Rwanda and Liberia.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      36. Mexico's recurrent economic and political crises
provoke national disintegration posing
severe and immediate
     challenges to the U.S. and the North American Region, including low intensity conlict.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      77. Emergence of nationalism in Asia, e.g. Japan
(including the possibility of a Japanese
military buildup),  in response
     to the continued pressure from the US, China and Korea.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      90. Information warfare; the deliberate insertion of false
data or manipulation or falsification of 
information by  electronic means to achieve political ends.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      106. The "patriot" movement gains strength in the US and
causes legal, police, and military
responses to assure public
     tranquillity in the nation.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      115. Deepening of ethnic sentiments in populations
(homogenization of economies and
knowledge, but heterogeneity
     in terms of ethnic affiliation and stronger determination of ethnic boundaries).<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      118. China turns militant; possible wars with India and
Russia or against an alliance between
these two, possible war
     with Formosa.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      120. US retreats from the position of "world policemen."
<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      129. Threat of regional nuclear conflict when more and
more countries and potentially terrorist
groups will have access
     to nuclear weapons.
     <p>

<b>    Terrorism and Crime</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      3, 134.  Nuclear terrorism and proliferation posing far
more of a threat to the survival of the
human species than is
     generally appreciated.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      37. High-tech terrorism<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      70. Organized crime groups becoming sophisticated global
enterprises with the know-how to
yield enormous illegal
     profits (information fraud, organ traffic, arms traffic, etc.).<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      107. The public becoming fed up with crime, recidivism,
and liberal courts: reinstitution of the
death penalty, harsher
     penalties, pushing the limits of "cruel and unusual" penalties.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      131. A generation of children whose behavior has included
extreme criminality at an early age,
resulting in an increasing
     siege mentality among law-abiding citizens.<p>

     <b>    Violence</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      54. Violence as a global problem. Sources, instruments,
promotion and exploitation of
violence abound (movies, TV,
     drugs, fundamentalism, racism, terrorism).<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      103. Introduction into military, police and terrorist
arsenals of non-lethal weapons, including
for example, aerosols that
     induce sleep, and sticky foams.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      128. Violence in the mass media and aggressive
advertising support the increasing
expectations of a consumer society
     that cannot be fulfilled in real life.<p>

<b>  Therapies for Conflict</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      55. Globalization: increasingly clear demand for global
thinking, responsibility, ethics,
approach, effort, action and
     results.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      63. Space as insurance against the destruction of
humanity<p>
       
     <b>    Governance</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      2. The global Islamic community beginning to adopt
futures thinking in establishing its plans
and goals.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      12. Increasing complexity of issues that lead to conflict,
outstripping ability of institutions to
anticipate and deal with
     the issues.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      13. Failure of education system to develop leadership
skills<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      67. Increasing failure of governments in 1st world
countries due to inability to manage
complex systems in a global
     village - widening gap between rate of technological change and societal/institutional
change.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      68. Information/communication technologies increasing
the ability to simultaneously
decentralize/localize/fragment and
     to centralize/globalize/integrate.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      72. A preoccupation with  power at all levels of society
(and in our education system).<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      124. Ineffectiveness of political and economic institutions,
above all at a supranational
level.<p>
     
     <b>    Economic Systems</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      65. Capitalism stands essentially unchallenged as the
dominant economic system throughout
the world.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      121. Europe turns into a major world player, rejuvenates
and creates a new identity of the
occident.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      126. The uneven and unfair distribution of wealth among
nations (North/South divide) and
also within nations.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      130. The increasing deterioration of the international
monetary system, based mainly on US
dollars.<p>

<font  size=+1><i><b>Domain 5: International Economics and Wealth</b></i><p></font>

     <b>    Rich,  Poor, and Other Gaps</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      9. Increasingly apparent conflicts between economic and
societal aims: economic measurement
and incentives subvert
     social growth<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      10. Growth in the number of aging seniors place burden on
younger generation.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      53. The inability of developing countries to use developed
technologies: the power of
technology is limited by the
     ignorance of users.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      57. Improving economic status of many "developing"
countries, thus increasing global demand
for food, energy and
     manufactured products.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      74. The widening economic gap between the 'haves' and
'have nots' within and between
countries.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      85. High population growth and high educational
achievement of many developing nations
producing more highly
     educated citizens than their economies can productively employ.<p>
       
     <b>Work</b> <br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      29. Interactive information technology systems become
widely used in work, education, and
other social functions.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      35.  Increase in the impact of new technologies, especially
in the service sector.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      137. Changing composition of the workforce; shift in labor
from industrial to service
sector<p>

     <b>    Organizations</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      28. Decentralization of institutions: big corporations are
breaking up into small,
self-supporting units, big government
     welfare state policies are being dismantled.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      69. The human tendency to discount distant space and
time (i.e., focus on the "here and now")
is increasingly
     dangerous.<p>

     <b>    International Economics</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      75. Natural resources being bought by international
cartels, with unprecedented speed and
scale; in a decade, 70% of
     natural resources will be controlled by private financial powers.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      76. Family business increasing its presence, power and
influence over many aspects of politics,
economics and culture,
     without proper market competition or public scrutiny.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      88. Environmentally-adverse forms of energy perpetuated
in part because of economic
distortions and incomplete
     accounting for costs.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      91. Tele-national citizens (Third World people who live
and work in First World but help
develop their countries via
     tele-commuting)<p>

<font  size=+1><i><b>Domain 6: Integration and Whole Futures</b></i><p></font>

     <b>    Planning and Futures Research</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      1. The failure of linear thinking about the future <br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      81. Increasing  ability of individuals and decisions makers
to assess a broader range of issues
and consequences
     including force and violence.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      94. Growing distance between dreams and expectations,
deriving from fear of dystopic
futures.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      97. The economic value of information is becoming more
important than information sought
for other purposes.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      98. The growth and change of the meaning of expertise:
the tendency to lean on experts and
leave it to them to tell the
     rest of us what to do.<p>

     <b>    The Pursuit of Meaning</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      17. The eager pursuit of greater meaning and purpose
from work and from life (among many
groups of people, not just
     those with plenty of food and possessions).<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      99. The growing feeling of guilt: we know more and more
about human-made problems,
environmental and other, and
     feel less and less comfortable with our everyday life and practices.<P>

<b>    Social Change</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      64. Memes (postulated as the smallest unit of social
evolution) becoming a new method for
planning and directing the
     evolution of technology and society.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      82. Participatory round tables that include the ability to
weigh interest and quality of
contributions in given time frames
     and creating a new form of structuring meetings and conferences.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      95. The blurring of the borderline between truth and
fiction; the certainty of reality is
disappearing from our conception
     of the world.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      96. The blurring of the borderline between private and
public.<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      117. Changing role of women in society
     <p>

     <b>    New Age</b><br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      44. Wild Card: Return of the Messiah, Sri Satha Sai
Baba<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      78. Reconsidering consciousness, wholeness, and
synthesis<br>
Likelihood__ Importance __ Leadership __      80. Use of space and visual access as a new way to
approach synthetic realms, making use of
VR and Cyberspace in
     design.<p>

