<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="eisaku"><B>1996 EISAKU SATO ESSAY CONTEST ANNOUNCED</B></A></CENTER>
<P>
The Eisaku Sato Memorial Foundation for Cooperation with the United
Nations University has announced the theme for its 1996 international
essay contest as follows: 
<P>
The United Nations University and other bodies in the United Nations
system are undertaking research on such global issues as peace,
development and the environment and are making policy recommendations
to enhance international cooperation on these issues. What kind
of concrete actions are required for strengthening and expanding
the cooperative relationship among the academic and research entities
of the United Nations system, such as the United Nations University,
and the international academic community? (Contributors are free
to select the specific wording for the title of their essays.)

<P>
The contest is open to international participation. Those persons
who have an interest in the United Nations University (UNU) and
in the above subjects, regardless of age, nationality or profession,
are eligible to participate. Essays will be accepted either in
Japanese (8,000 to 16,000 characters) or in English (3,000 to
6,000) words). The entries in English must be typed on A4-size
paper and should be accompanied by an abstract of not more than
450 words. A covering sheet should be prepared for each entry
and should contain the title of the essay, the contributor's name,
affiliation, age, sex (F/M), nationality, address and telephone
and/or fax number. All entries should be sent to: 
<P>
The Eisaku Sato Memorial Foundation for Cooperation<BR>
with the United Nations University<BR>
c/o Daiichi Mutual Fire and Marine Insurance Company<BR>
5-1, Nibancho, Chiyoda-ku, Tokyo 102, JAPAN<BR>

<P>
The deadline for entry is 30 November 1996. 
<P>
The best essay will be awarded a grand prize of Yen500,000. Two
second prizes of Yen200,000 each and several third prizes of Yen50,000
each will also be awarded to selected essay contributions. 
<P>
The winners will be notified by the Foundation in early 1997,
and a prize awarding ceremony will be held at the United Nations
University headquarters in June 1997. 
<P>
The Eisaku Sato Memorial Foundation for Cooperation with the United
Nations University was established by the late Mr. Eisaku Sato,
former Prime Minister of Japan, with the monetary award he received
with the 1974 Nobel Peace Prize. The Foundation devotes its activities
to provide support for the development of the United Nations University,
a part of the United Nations which carries out research, advanced
training and the dissemination of knowledge in addressing global
problems which threaten human survival development and welfare.
The UNU is the only United Nations organization that has its headquarters
in Japan. 
<P>
* * * * * 
<P>
Note: For further information on the 1996 Eisaku Sato Essay Contest,
please contact:<BR>

<P>
The Eisaku Sato Memorial Foundation for Cooperation with the United
Nations Un$ c/o Daiichi Mutual Fire and Marine Insurance Company
<BR>
5-1, Nibancho, Chiyoda-ku, Tokyo 102, JAPAN<BR>
Telephone: (03) 3239-0011 Fax: (03) 3238-9193<BR>
