<P>
<CENTER><A NAME="zero"><B>PRESS BRIEFING TO BE HELD ON UNU'S ZERO
EMISSIONS RESEARCH INITIATIVE</B></A></CENTER>
<P>
The United Nations University (UNU) will hold a press briefing
on its Zero Emissions Research Initiative (UNU/ZERI) on Tuesday,
16 July 1996, at 16.00 hours at the UNU Headquarters in Shibuya.
<P>
The UNU launched the UNU/ZERI project under the leadership of
Mr. Gunter Pauli, a Belgian businessman and author in 1994. During
the first year of activity, UNU/ZERI focused on the development
of the scientific theory for zero emissions and the design of
a methodology universally acceptable to all industries. The second
year of UNU/ZERI work was directed to the launching and set up
of pilot projects in Fiji, Namibia and Tanzania.
<P>
The press briefing on 16 July 1996 is meant to describe the plans
for the third year of UNU/ZERI work. In its next phase, UNU/ZERI
will focus on the organization of postgraduate training courses
on zero emissions on each continent and on the expansion of the
research and pilot projects which are to cover some 30 different
agricultural and industrial sectors.
<P>
During its first two years, UNU/ZERI has benefited from growing
private support. Additional funding in the next phase will be
used to scale up the pilot projects to industrial test plants.
The first two test plants will be constructed in Indonesia and
Malaysia. The potential impact of UNU/ZERI research and development
in South-East Asia goes beyond a reduction in the level of pollution
in the region; it could generate additional employment, enhance
competitiveness and create one of the largest new carbon sinks
in the region.
<P>
The press briefing on 16 July will seek to provide more detailed
information on developments with UNU/ZERI and will review the
results of the recent Second UNU World Congress on Zero Emissions
held in Chattanooga, Tennessee, USA, during 29-31 May 1996.
<P>
Members of the news media are cordially invited to attend the
briefing. Prof. Tarcisio Della Senta, Director a.i., of the UNU's
newly established Institute of Advanced Studies (UNU/IAS), the
institutional base of the UNU/ZERI project, will chair the briefing.
Mr. Gunter Pauli, the director of the UNU/ZERI project, will provide
detailed information and respond to questions from the press.
Japanese/English interpretation will be provided.
<P>
<CENTER>* * * * * <BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>For further information, please contact:<BR>
UNU Public Affairs Section<BR>
Tel.: (03) 5467-1243, -1246<BR>
Fax: (03) 3406-7346<BR>
</CENTER>
