<H3><CENTER><A NAME="women">UNU SYMPOSIUM ON WOMEN AND MAINSTREAMING</A>
</CENTER></H3>

<P>
Wednesday, 19 June 1996<BR>
09.30-17.30 hours<BR>
International Conference Hall<BR>
United Nations University Headquarters, Tokyo<BR>

<P>
The United Nations University will organize an international symposium
on Women and Mainstreaming on Wednesday, 19 June 1996, at the
UNU Headquarters in Tokyo. 
<P>
At the Fourth World Conference on Women held in Beijing in September
1995 attention was focused on the issue of women and mainstreaming.
This symposium will provide an opportunity to discuss further
the &quot;mainstreaming&quot; concept, inviting prominent figures
specializing in women's studies and the advancement of women's
status. 
<P>
The speakers and panelists include Ms. Sharon Brennen-Haylock,
Chairperson, United Nations Commission on the Status of Women,
Ms. Martha Duenas-Loza, Acting Director, United Nations International
Research and Training Institute for the Advancement of Women (INSTRAW),
HE Mrs. Mervat Mehani Tallawy, Ambassador of the Arab Republic
of Egypt to Japan, Ms. Makiko Arima, President, Yokohama Women's
Association for Communication and Networking/Delegate of Japan
to the UN Commission on the Status of Women. Please see the attached
programme for details. Simultaneous interpretation in English
and Japanese will be provided.
<P>
Representatives of news media are cordially invited to attend.
