<title>Futures Research Guide</title>
<hr>
<strong><center>
A GUIDE TO SUCCESSFUL FUTURES RESEARCH ON THE INTERNET
</center></strong>
<hr>
As you may have already discovered in searching for futurist
 pages on the Internet, it is easy to be pointed in 
multiple directions;  none of which are where you initially intended 
to go.  The chart below offers some helpful hints and starting points, 
but it is by no means exhaustive.<br>
<p>
The information available on the WWW is constantly and rapidly
 changing.  If you find any of the following information is out-dated,  
or find other excellent futurists pages, please contact the Millennium
Project webmaster so that this page can serve as a valuable resource
 for interns to come.<br>
<hr>
<strong>
Some Background Information on Search Engines
</strong>
<hr>
The variety of search engines continues to expand.  Each search engine searches 
from different databases and matches the key word(s) in different 
manners.  For this reason, it sometimes can take multiple attempts 
on multiple search engines to find what you are searching for on the 
Internet.  Some search engines may prove more effective for specific 
searches (ie proper names, book titles), while other search engines may 
are more effective for general searches (ie concepts, general fields 
of study).  Before starting a search, it is well worth your time 
to read any "searching tips" that might be available from the search 
engine's main page.  The tips explain how you can make your search 
more effective while using that specific search engine.  Check out 
<a href="http://www.indiana.edu/~librcsd/search">http://www.indiana.edu/~librcsd/search</a> 
for a good comparison of search engines.
<br>

<hr>
<strong>
Futurist Research on the Internet
</strong>
<hr>
This following lists represent the results of futurist studies searches 
on 4 popular search engines <ul>
<li>AltaVista, <a href="http://www.altavista.com">http://www.altavista.com</a>
<li>Infoseek, <a href="http://www.infoseek.com">http://www.infoseek.com</a>
<li>Lycos, <a href="http://www.lycos.com">http://www.lycos.com</a>
<li>Yahoo, <a href="http://www.yahoo.com">http://www.yahoo.com</a>
</ul>
The key words used for the searches are the following: <ol>
<li>FUTURIST
<li>FUTURES STUDIES
<li>FUTURES RESEARCH</ol>
All of the relevant sites 
are listed with hotlinks for quick access.  With the turning of the 
millennium on the close horizon, the term "futurist" is implemented 
more and more frequently in reference to anyone thinking past the 
year 2000.  This chart is only the beginning, and will be more useful 
as interns add additional input and findings.
<br>
