<HTML> 
<TITLE>1995 Youth Summit</TITLE> 
<body text=000000 link=#0000dd vlink=#0000dd bgcolor=a0ffa0>
<CENTER> 
<FONT SIZE=6><i>PARTNERS FOR THE PLANET</font><FONT SIZE=1>SM</i></font><p>
<IMG SRC="partners.gif" border=0><p>  
<FONT SIZE=7> 1995 NATIONAL YOUTH SUMMIT</font><p>
<table border=5 cellpadding=3>
<tr>
<td width=200 height=155>
<IMG SRC="snowbird.jpg"><p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<P>
<Font SIZE=4>On July 5-9 in Snowbird, Utah, the 
second "by kids for kids" National Youth Summit took place.</FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=4>A MUST for Young Environmentalists!</FONT><p>
<FONT SIZE=4><UL><LI>Banquet and Dinner Show,   Ice Breaker 
Reception,
<LI> General Sessions,  		 Youth Speakers, 
<LI> Entertainment, 		 Networking,  
<LI> Field Trips,  			 Workshops,  
<LI> Exhibits,  			 Dances.</UL></FONT><p>
<HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=80% ALIGN=CENTER>
<table border=5 cellpadding=3>
<tr>
<td>
<ul>
<li><a href="#info">Summit Info</a>
<li><a href="#play">The Major Players</a>
</ul>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=80% ALIGN=CENTER><P>
</CENTER>
<DL><DT><a name="info">FOR YOUTH AGES 10-18 YEARS OLD</a>
<DD>The Summit brought a diverse cross-section of ethnicity, age, 
gender, physical ability, and environmental activism from all corners 
of the country and beyond together as the youth environmental 
movement.  Partners for the Planet includes youth and adults from 
major nonprofits, grassroots groups, government agencies, 
professional associations, corporate America, and YOU!  The second 
"by-kids" National Partners for the Planet Youth Summit was a 
forum in which young activists could network, learn, share ideas, and 
have fun.<BR></DL>
<DL><DT>PRESENTED BY YOUTH!<BR>
	<DD>The Summit is about more than environmental 
education. Kids who attended got to experience the issues hands-on 
through outdoor activities.<BR>
	<DD>Young people presented workshops, sessions and 
speakers with a focus on youth and other natural resources. Kids
learned about everything from the ecosystem of the Great Salt Lake to 
the exploration of the mountain`s forest integrity!<BR>		
	<DD>Delegates returned to their communities with the 
knowledge and skills necessary to take action.<BR></DL>

<DL><DT>ADULT PARTNERS WELCOME!
	<DD>Many families attended the Summit as part of their summer 
vacation. Workshops for adult partners were planned, as well as 
separate dances and events to allow these very special supporters to 
network and enjoy themselves.</DL><BR>

<DL><DT>YOUNG ADULTS NEEDED!
<DD>19-23 year-olds are invited to serve as Workshop Facilitators to 
ensure the "by youth" spirit of workshops is preserved.  No 
experience is necessary, but applicants must believe in the power 
and value of youth in environmentalism.<P>
<dd>Please Contact:   	Tree Amigos<br>
		        Marisol Cruz or Monica Rogers<br>
		        616/771-3935	fax:  616/771-4005<br>
<dd>E-Mail:  <A HREF="mailto:mrogers@post.grcc.cc.mi.us">mrogers@post.grcc.cc.mi.us</A><br>
<dd>Note: Travel-related expenses are responsibility of the Workshop 
Facilitator.</DL>

<dl><dt>HOSTED BY YOUTH!
	<dd>We want to introduce you, our 
readers, to the Summiters who sat on the Steering Committee for the 
1995 National Youth Summit. They are youth/ adult teams from 19 
different organizations all working together as Partners for the 
Planet. Each team chairs a subcommittee (a group of volunteers who 
planned one certain part of the whole event such as a banquet), and 
reports on their progress to the whole group. Your youth hosts are 
11-18 years of age and together, the membership is nearly six 
million people from all 50 states and 44 foreign countries. There are 
a lot of kids represented on the planning team for the Summit. 
Maybe you're one of them!<br></dl>

<DL><DT>PARTNERS FOR THE PLANET PHILOSOPHY
<DD>The focus is on solutions--not problems, so there is no 
sitting in judgement or pointing fingers of blame.  Partners for the 
Planet projects avoid duplicating efforts of others thereby paving the 
way for ongoing partnerships.<BR>
<DD>All programs are youth-led, and adults serve as a support 
system for the young decisions makers.<BR>  
<DD>Human development is integral to all program activity, and an 
extended definition of diversity is sought.
<DD>  We write, speak, act, and think with integrity.</DL><br>

<center>

<HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=80%><p>


<FONT SIZE=5><b><a name="play">THE MAJOR PLAYERS</a></b></FONT><br>
Who did what at the 1995 Summit: <br>
the National Partners for the Planet Youth Summit Steering 
Committee.<br>
</center>

<dl><dt>YMCA EARTH SERVICE CORPS<br>
Summit Job: General Session<br>
	<dd>Earth Service Corps promotes global environmental 
understanding and action by youth through education, project 
development, leadership training, and international/cross-cultural 
exchange. It also focuses on the empowerment of students to make 
their own decisions.<br>
<dt>Contacts: Casey Cabblequinto  & Charlie Murphy. Phone (206) 
282-7892 ext. 5079.</dl>

<dl><dt>THE NATURAL GUARD<br>
Summit Job: Scholarships
	<dd>The Natural Guard Inc. is a not-for-profit experiential, 
environmental education organization for young people that is 
grassroots in focus and international in scope. TNG programs offer a 
multi-cultural perspective of ecological issues.
	<dt>Contacts: Joseph Golden & Diana Edmonds. Phone (203) 
787-0229.</dl>

<dl><dt>TREE AMIGOS<br>
Summit Job: Workshop Facilitation
	<dd>The Tree Amigos program is a cross-cultural program using 
trees as our common bond to the environment. It has three major 
components: 1) tree planting and restoration; 2) development of 
creative education materials; and 3) development of classroom, 
corporate and professional affiliations.
	<dt>Contacts: Marisol Cruz & Monica Rogers. Phone (616) 771-
3935.</dl>

<dl><dt><a href="treemusk.html">TREE MUSKETEERS</a><br>
Summit Job: Administration
	<dd>Tree Musketeers is a nonprofit corporation founded and 
run by kids, for kids. It specializes in community forestry and youth 
empowerment. Its Partners for the Planet network creates 
communication within the youth movement.
	<dt>Contacts: Sabrina Alimahomed & Gail Church. Phone (310) 
322-0263.</dl>

<dl><dt>UTAH COMMUNITY
FOREST COUNCIL<br>
Summit Job: Banquet
	<dd>A nonprofit organization of citizens, UCFC has put emphasis 
on a variety of areas including certification of arborists and the 
development of the Tree City USA program.
	<dt>Contacts: Audrey Chase & Dick Klason. Phone (801) 649-
3263.</dl>

<dl><dt>HP RAPP ARBOR CLUB<br>
Summit Job: General Session
	<dd>The Highland Park Restoration and Preservation Program, 
Inc. (HP RAPP), a nonprofit corporation, has been devoted to 
increasing the quality of life in Highland Park, VA. It works to 
restore and preserve the culture, character, safety, housing, and life 
performance of its residents.
	<dt>Contacts: Quintrail Lambert & Trina Fleming. Phone (703) 
568-4460.</dl>

<dl><dt>CENTERSTAGE CHILDREN'S
THEATRE TROUPE<br>
Summit Job: General Session
	<dd>The CenterStage Children`s Theatre Troupe is a touring 
troupe of youth performers from Wisconsin. Its material is 
intergenerational and multicultural, leaving a lasting impression 
wherever it performs.
	<dt>Contacts: Hannah Dorsey & Teresa Dorsey. Phone (414) 735-
0430.</dl>


<dl><dt>KIDS FOR A CLEAN ENVIRONMENT
(KIDS F.A.C.E.)<br>
Summit Job: Workshops
	<dd>Kids F.A.C.E. is a youth environmental organization started 
in 1987 by a child for children. With a membership of over 200,000 
youths, the organization's current projects include The Kid's Earth 
Flag and "Kid's Yard."
	<dt>Contacts: Mason Poe & Trish Poe. Phone (615) 331-
7381.</dl>

<dl><dt>INTERNATIONAL SOCIETY
 OF ARBORICULTURE<br>
Summit Job: Facilities
	<dd>The International Society of Arboriculture (ISA) is a 
worldwide organization representing professional arborists. It 
focuses on research and education, and scientifically correct ways to 
plant and care for trees. The ISA also conducts an arborist 
certification program.
	<dt>Contacts: Becky Ottman & Ken Ottman. Phone (414) 286-
3593.</dl>

<dl><dt>LOUISIANA-PACIFIC
CORPORATION<br>
Summit Job: Ice Breaker Reception
	<dd>Louisiana-Pacific is dedicated to making environmentally 
friendly, affordable building products. The corporation believes it is 
possible to work alongside the environment rather than against it.
	<dt>Contacts: Lauren Ulmer & Alisa Ulmer/Heide Meihoff. 
Phone (503) 232-3954.</dl>

<dl><dt>KIDS ORGANIZED to 
PROTECT our ENVIRONMENT (KOPE)<br>
Summit Job: Local Arrangements
	<dd>KOPE was organized by elementary students to find 
solutions for local environmental problems. The organization 
publishes an environmental newsletter, and hosts annual 
conferences. Projects include "Naturescaping" and a program to 
protect burrowing owl habitat.
	<dt>Contacts: Cassie Olson & Sharry Pickett/Lynne Olson. Phone 
(801) 484-8352.</dl>

<dl><dt>USDA NATURAL RESOURCE
CONSERVATION SERVICE<br>
Summit Job: Exhibits
	<dd>The USDA Natural Resource Conservation Service provides 
technical information and services to the public. Its objective is to 
achieve land adjustments that will conserve land, water, and related 
resources.
	<dt>Contacts: Ben Pearson & Skip Nelson/Rick Pearson. Phone 
(801) 524-5954.</dl>

<dl><dt>USDA FOREST SERVICE
Co-Op Forestry<br>
Summit Job: Media & Promotions
	<dt>Contacts: Tara Church & Robert Conrad. Phone (310) 322-
0263.</dl>

<dl><dt>USDA FOREST SERVICEt
Wildlife Group<br>
Summit Job: Outreach
	<dd>The USDA Forest Service has been actively involved in 
urban and community forestry since the early '70s. Program 
elements include volunteer involvement in tree planting, 
maintenance and protection activities.
	<dt>Contacts: Branic Keltz & Jerry Fernandez. Phone (202) 205-
0812.</dl>

<dl><dt>CARETAKERS OF
THE ENVIRONMENT,
INTERNATIONAL/USA<br>
Summit Job: Registration
	<dd>Caretakers of the Environment, organized in 1987, has a 
few major goals: to establish Caretakers clubs in high schools across 
the country and to encourage high school students to participate in 
environmental action.
	<dt>Contacts: Junior Fields & Wayne Schimpff. Phone (312) 631-4648.</dl>

<dl><dt>EARTH FORCE<br>
Summit Job: Fundraising
	<dd>Earth Force is an organization created to enable young 
people to act on behalf of the Earth. The organization also provides 
materials, services and support to parents, teachers and other 
advisors.
	<dt>Contacts: Josh Propp & Glen Gaskins. Phone (410) 997-8533.</dl><P>

