<P>
<A NAME="water">
<B>27 September 1996</B><BR>
<B>PR/E13/96</B>
<P>
<CENTER><B>UNITED NATIONS UNIVERSITY</B> <B>WATER
NETWORK OPENS IN CANADA<BR>
</B></A></CENTER>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Canadian Heritage, Ms. Sheila
Copps, together with the Rector of the United Nations University
(UNU), Prof. Heitor Gurgulino de Souza, inaugurated the International
Network on Water, Environment and Health (INWEH), the first research
and training programme of UNU to be located in Canada. 
<P>
Rector de Souza and Minister Copps, on behalf of Environment Minister
Sergio Marchi, signed the agreement concerning UNU/INWEH at McMaster
University in Hamilton, Ontario, Canada, in the areas of aquatic
ecosystem protection and management, water and wastewater treatment
and emediation, environmental assessment, ecotoxicology, and water-related
human health impacts in the developing regions of the world. 
<P>
The activitieswill be project-based, responsive to the needs of
governments and UN organizations, and proactive &quot;The establishment
of UNU/INWEH,&quot; said Rector de Souza, &quot;marks an import
milestone in the history of the United National University, and
embodies a unique and timely effort to better address one of the
most challenging environmental issues facing humanity in the decades
ahead.&quot; &quot;Our support for the UNU,&quot; said Minister
Copps, &quot;reinforces Canada's determination to show leadership
in addressing the critical and intertwined issues of water, human
health and our shared global environment.&quot; The Chairman of
the Governing Council of the UNU, Dr. Lucien Michaud, from the
University of Sudbury, Canada, also participated in the ceremony.
&quot;I welcome the establishment of UNU/INWEH in Canada and thank
both the Government of Canada for its support and the many partners
of UNU/INWEH for their dedication in making the Network a reality,&quot;
said Dr. Michaud. Rector de Souza announced the appointment of
Dr. Ralph J. Daley, as Director of UNU/INWEH. Dr. Daley joins
the UNU from the National Water Research Institute of Environment
Canada, where he served as Executive Director. 
<P>
The UNU/INWEH headquarters will be located at McMaster University,
with supporting facilities at Environment Canada's Canada Centre
for Inland Waters in Burlington,Ontario. Rector de Souza further
announced the membership of the UNU/INWEH International Advisory
Committee: <BR>
Dr. Nii Boi Ayebotele, former Director, Water Resources Research
Institute,Ghana; <BR>
Mr. James Bruce, Chairman of the Board, Canadian Climate Program;
<BR>
Dr. Indira Chakravarty, Director Professor and Dean, All India
Institute of Hygiene and Public Health, Calcutta, India; <BR>
Dr. Peter George, President and Vice Rector, McMaster University,
Canada; and <BR>
Dr. Jose Tundisi, President, National Council for Scientificand
Technological Development, Brazil. <BR>
The Rector of UNU and the Director of UNU/INWEH will both be exofficio
members of the International Advisory Committee. 
<P>
October 09, 1996
<HR>
<P>
<A HREF="#index">Back to the Index</A>
</B>

<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="appointments">
15 October 1996<BR>
PR/E14/96
<P>
<CENTER><B>UNU RECTOR ANNOUNCES THREE SENIOR
APPOINTMENTS</B></A></CENTER>
<P>
Prof. Heitor Gurgulino de Souza, Rector of the United Nations
University (UNU) announced today the formal appointments of three
Directors of UNU research and training centers and programs (RTC/Ps):
Dr. Ralph James Daley, currently Executive Director of the National
Water Research Institute, Burlington, Ontario, Canada, has been
named as the Director of the UNU International Network on Water,
Environment and Health (UNU/INWEH), a UNU research and training
program. The UNU and the Government of Canada recently concluded
the necessary legal instruments for the location and operation
of UNU/INWEH in Canada. 
<P>
UNU/INWEH will address issues relating water to environment and
human health, a concern which is of particular relevance to developing
countries. The headquarters of UNU/INWEH will be located at McMaster
University in Hamilton, Ontario, Canada. Dr. Daley has served
in a number of capacities at the National Water Research Institute,
including Chief, Science Liaison Division, Science Liaison Coordinator
and Research Limnologist. He received his B.A. in General Biology
(1966), his M.Sc. degree in Phytoplankton Physiology (1968), and
his Ph.D. in Biological Limnology (1971), all at Queen's University,
Ontario, Canada. Dr. Daley formally takes up his appointment as
Director of UNU/INWEH on 15 October 1996.
<P>
Prof. Tarcisio G. Della Senta, currently Director, a.i., of the
UNU Institute of Advanced Studies (UNU/IAS) in Tokyo has been
named Director of UNU/IAS asfrom 7 October 1996. The UNU/IAS is
a new UNU research and training center that commenced operations
formally in April 1996. The UNU/IAS currently has three major
program focuses: eco-restructuring for sustainable development;
mega-cities and urban development; and multilateralism and governance.
<P>
Prof. Della Senta has served in various capacities at the UNU
since joining in 1988. He has served as Director of Planning and
Development, Vice-Rector, a.i. and as Acting Director of the UNU/IAS.
Prior to his service with the UNU, Prof. Della Senta served as
an Assistant and Full Professor at the Federal University of Rio
Grande do Sul and Catholic University of Sao Paulo, Brazil, respectively.
He has served in various capacities as an official of the Government
of Brazil, including Vice President of the Postgraduate Education
Development Agency (CAPES), Program Coordinator of Scientific
and Technological Development at the National Council for Scientific
and Technological Development (CNPq), Secretary of Higher Education,
and Special Adviser to the Minister of Education, at the Ministry
of Education; and Head of the Planning and Budgeting Division
of CNPq. He has also served as a Member of the Federal Council
of Education, appointed by the President of Brazil.
<P>
Prof. Della Senta received his B.Sc. in Neo-Latin Languages at
the Catholic University of Rio Grande do Sul, Porto Alegre, Brazil,
in 1957, his Master's degree (diplome) in Education at the Institute
Catholique de Paris, France in1960, and his Doctorate in Educational
Planning and Administration at Harvard University, United States,
in 1974.
<P>
Dr. Adel Safty has been named as the Director of the UNU International
Leadership Academy (UNU/ILA), a UNU research and training program.
Dr.Safty has since 1990 been the Director of the Center for International
Studies, Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada.
<P>
The initial activities of the Academy have been made possible
by funding from the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan. The offices of
UNU/ILA are located within the campus of the University of Jordan
in Amman. The Academy aims to train potential leaders by direct
interaction with present leaders and through a series of seminars
and group training activities related to pressing global issues.
<P>
Dr. Safty, originally from Egypt, received his Bachelors degree
from the University of Paris III in1974. He received his Master's
degree in English Political Sociology from the University of Paris
III in 1975 and his Doctorate in Political Science (International
Relations) with distinction from the University of Paris I, La
Sorbonne, Paris, in 1980. He is a well-known commentator and analyst
for the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation and UTV, an affiliate
of Global Television.
<P>
Dr. Safty took up his post on 7 October 1996.
<P>
<CENTER>* * *</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>For further information, please contact:<BR>
UNU Public Affairs Section<BR>
Tel.: (03) 5467-1243, -1246<BR>
Fax: (03) 3406-7346</CENTER>
