<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="language">
PR/E15/96
<P>
<CENTER><B>PRESS BRIEFING TO BE HELD ON UNU'S
UNIVERSAL NETWORKING LANGUAGE PROJECT<BR>
</B></A></CENTER>
<P>
The United Nations University (UNU) will hold a press briefing
on its Universal Networking Language (UNL) project on Thursday,
17 October 1996, at 15.00 hours at the UNU Headquarters. UNL is
an Internet plug-in that will facilitate communication between
peoples with different languages. Along with its companion software
&quot;Enconverter&quot; and &quot;Deconverter,&quot; it will allow
anyone with Internet access to &quot;enconvert&quot; text from
a UN Member State language into UNL, or &quot;deconvert&quot;
text from UNL into another language. 
<P>
The UNU's Institute of Advanced Studies (UNU/IAS), located adjacent
to UNU Headquarters, launched the UNL project in April 1996, and
will take 10 years to complete. The first three years will be
devoted to creating conversion modules for Arabic, Chinese, English,
French, German, Hindi, Indonesian, Italian, Japanese, Portuguese,
Russian and Spanish. The remaining Member State language modules
will be developed in the following seven years. 
<P>
The press briefing on 17 October will provide more detailed information
on UNL. Members of the news media are cordially invited to attend
the briefing. English-Japanese interpretation will be provided.
<P>
<CENTER>* * *</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>For further information, please contact:<BR>
UNU Public Affairs Section<BR>
Tel.: (03) 5467-1243, -1246<BR>
Fax: (03) 3406-7346</CENTER>
<P>
Yukiko Kobayashi<BR>
Public Affairs<BR>
United Nations University
<HR>
