<HR>
<A NAME="earthquake">
31 October 1996<BR>
PR/E19/96<BR>


<P>
<CENTER><B><FONT SIZE=4>NATO Earthquake Workshop Held in Central Asia</CENTER></B></FONT>
<P>
       Half of the Central Asian Republics' six million people live, work, and go
to school in buildings that are vulnerable to collapse during earthquakes.  And the tragedies in Armenia and Sakhalin will be repeated in Kazakhstan, Kyrgystan, Tajikistan,
Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan unless these buildings are strengthened.
<P>
       This grim warning was issued by an international team of structural and
geophysics experts attending a NATO Advanced Research Workshop on Earthquakes in
Almaty, Kazakhstan. The United Nations University (UNU) and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO)organized the 22-25 October workshop to assess earthquake hazards in the region's major cities and devise ways of reducing them.
<P>
       The problem is urgent.  According to Bruce Bolt of the University of California,
Berkeley, "There is a high probability that a severe earthquake will occur near one of the
region's capital cities within the next 20 years, resulting in devastation similar to the
1988 quake in Leninakan, Armenia.
<P>
       Delegates said they will urge their governments to address earthquake
safety at schools, day-care centers, hospitals and emergency response agencies.  "The very
future of Central Asia is dependent on the integrity and continued functioning of these
facilities," said Bolt.
<P>
       Brian Tucker, President of GeoHazards International and Dr. Vitaly Khalturin of the
Russian Academy of Sciences' United Institute of Physics of the Earth, co-chaired the
workshop.  They said one of  its major goals was to identify available resources.  "Rather
than just ask their governments for money, participants committed to taking steps themselves," said Tucker.  They agreed that engineering teams from Central Asian and other countries will design and implement measures to upgrade important buildings.  They also created a joint Central Asian Urban Earthquake Risk Management Working
Group, made up of foreign experts and delegation heads from the five attending republics.
The group's purpose is to promote urban earthquake risk management throughout Central
Asia.  The workshop's results were presented to Nikolay Makivesky, Deputy Prime
Minister of Kazakhstan and Director of the Kazakh Committee of Emergencies.

<CENTER>* * * * *</CENTER>

       <CENTER>For further information, please contact:</CENTER>

       <CENTER>UNU Public Affairs Section</CENTER>
       <CENTER>Tel.:   (03) 5467-1243, -1246</CENTER>
       <CENTER>Fax:    (03) 3406-7346</CENTER>
<P>
Yukiko Kobayashi<BR>
Public Affairs<BR>
United Nations University
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A HREF="#index">Back to the Index</A>
<HR>

<A NAME="Symposium">
November 7, 1996<BR>
PR/E20/96
<P>
<CENTER><B>UNU Symposium on Peace and Security<BR></B></CENTER>
<HR>
<P><I>
8-9 November 1996
<BR>
Friday: 9.15-17.30 hours<BR> 
Saturday: 9.15-15.30 hours
<BR>
International Conference Hall
<BR>
United Nations University Headquarters, Tokyo</I>
<P>
<P>
The United Nations University (UNU) will hold a symposium on &quot;Peace
and Security&quot; as part of its project on the United Nations
System in the 21<SUP>st</SUP> Century (UN21), at the UNU Headquarters
in Tokyo from 8-9 November 1996. The purpose of the symposium
is to enable researchers working on this multi-year project to
present and discuss their initial research results.
<P>
The UN21 project analyses the role of international organizations,
searching for next century's best UN model. It is divided into
five actor-specific research groups: states and sovereignty, global
citizenship, market forces, regional arrangements, and international
organizations. Each year, research groups focus on a specific
theme - this year's is peace and security.
<P>
The UNU's UN21 project is unique. While others may be contemplating
the UN's future, the UNU has already established a research framework,
gathered prominent scholars from diverse backgrounds, and selected
specialized UN practitioners to discuss the UN of the past and
to formulate what the UN of the future should be.
<P>
Representatives of the media are cordially invited to attend.
Simultaneous English-Japanese interpretation will be provided.
<P>
<CENTER> *  *  *
<P>
       For further information, please contact:<BR>

<BR>UNU Public Affairs Section
<BR>Tel.:   (03) 5467-1243, -1246
<BR>Fax:    (03) 3406-7346<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
Yukiko Kobayashi
<BR>
Public Affairs
<BR>
United Nations University
<HR>
<P>
<A HREF="#index">Back to the Index</A>
<HR>
<A NAME="Workshop">
14 November 1996<BR>
PR/E21/96<BR>
UNU/IAS
<P>
<CENTER><B>Multilateral Diplomacy Workshop</CENTER>
</B><HR>
<P><I>
Date: 18-23 November 1996 (Monday-Saturday)
<BR>
Time: 09.30-18.00 hours (Moday through Friday)
<BR>
09.30-13.00 hours (Saturday)
<BR>
Place: International Conference Hall
<BR>
The United Nations University Headquarters<BR>
</I>
<P>
The First Workshop of the United Nations University's Institute
of Advanced Studies (UNU/IAS) Multilateral Diplomacy Project will
convene from 18-23 November 1996 in the International Conference
Hall of the United Nations University Headquarters. The topic
for the First Workshop is the environment in the East Asian region.
<P>
The UNU/IAS Multilateral Diplomacy Project was launched last June
with the objective of providing a forum for ideas and discussions
that would contribute to making multilateral diplomatic activities
both at the global and regional level more effective, as problem-solving
instruments of transnational issues, such as the environment.
<P>
Diplomats from capitals of 15 South and North-East Asian countries
(Brunei, Cambodia, China, Indonesia, Japan, South and North Korea,
Laos, Malaysia, Mongolia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore,
Thailand, Viet Nam) have been awarded fellowships to participate
in the First Workshop.
<P>
Eminent statesmen and scholars such as former Prime Minister of
the Netherlands, the Honorable Andries van Agt, Ambassador Kazuo
Chiba, Professor Yozo Yokota and Professor Akihiko Tanaka of Tokyo
University, Professor Tsuneyoshi Morita of National Institute
of Environment Studies, Professor Mikoto Usui of Shukutoku University,
Professor Catherine Redgwell of Nottingham University, Mr. Peider
Koenz of the UNU Office in Europe, Paris, Dr. Lin Sun of the United
Nations Environment (UNEP) will participate.
<P>
Furthermore, following the welcome speech by the Rector of the
United Nations University, Professor Heitor Gurgulino de Souza,
and the keynote address by the Honorable Takao Onishi, Administrative
Vice Minister of the Environment Agency, the Honorable Wakako
Hironaka of the House of Councillors and former Director-General
of the Environment Agency, Director-General Kazuo Asakai of the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs, will address the opening of the Workshop.
<P>
Updates on the Workshop, program and news are also available via
e-mail. Please send an e-mail to: listserv@msias.ias.unu.edu and
write the message:
<P><I>
<CENTER>SUBSCRIBE MD-ANN your first name your last name, organization,</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>e.g. subscribe md-ann Chan Buom Lee, UNU/IAS Tokyo.</CENTER>
<P></I>
Representatives of the media are cordially invited to attend.
Simultaneous English-Japanese interpretation will be provided.
<BR>

<P>

<P>
<CENTER> *  *  *
<P>
       For further information, please contact:<BR>

<BR>UNU Public Affairs Section
<BR>Tel.:   (03) 5467-1243, -1246
<BR>Fax:    (03) 3406-7346<BR>
</CENTER>
<P>
Yukiko Kobayashi
<BR>
Public Affairs
<BR>
United Nations University
