<HTML>

<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z">
<TITLE>Untitled</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="96E1FA">

<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=5 FACE="Times New Roman">ISSUE 10:</FONT><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">
</FONT></B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Times New Roman"> Information Technology's
Promise and Perils<BR>
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman">Interactive cyberspace has become
an important new and unprecedented medium for civilization.  Prices
for telecommunications, computers, and software are continuing
to fall while capacity grows and these systems are spreading throughout
poorer regions of the world.  Email and other gateways connected
virtually all countries by the end of 1994.  AT&amp;T's Africa
One Project and the Global Information Infrastructure vision of
U.S. Vice President Al Gore are expected to accelerate Internet
growth in developing countries. By the year 2000, the Internet
Society expects 187 million hosts connected world-wide, 2 million
networks outside the U.S., 2.5 billion users, and more traffic
than voice telephone.  <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman">The Internet is vast, confusing,
and unorganized to many people, but exciting and self-organizing
to others. It is both staggering in scope and trivial in some
content.  It is expected to become simpler, more accessible, and
faster within the next decade.  It is already one of the most
powerful agents of change in the world, affecting education, science,
health care, and business. It is becoming the first location for
the discussion of new ideas, publishing, advertising, and commerce.
 To some developing countries, it will provide the means to accelerate
their development processes, provide access to much of the world's
knowledge, and become the medium for participating in the global
economy.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman">Pornography and other influences
deemed culturally unacceptable are creating hostility toward the
free growth of the Internet.  In addition, regulatory constraints
on content have been proposed in many countries.  Currently, automation
is displacing routine human behavior, giving rise to the possibility
of economic growth with less employment.  If new kinds of enterprises
and employment are not created to address computer and automation-induced
unemployment, the unemployed and underemployed could well create
an anti-technology  sentiment and political crises. <BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT FACE="Times New Roman">At the same time, sabotage through
the Internet, should be expected: credit and bank fraud, computer
viruses, other forms of criminal manipulation and even information
warfare by individuals, groups, corporations, and nations are
possible.  Privacy and property rights are also issues of concern.
 Authenticity of information will be difficult to establish. 
Despite these and other problems, information technology is </FONT><FONT FACE="CG Times">creating
a planetary &quot;nervous system&quot; necessary for improving
the prospects for humanity.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4 FACE="Times New Roman">Round 3 questions:  </FONT></B><FONT FACE="Times New Roman">Please
use the scales shown in the instructions to provide your judgments
about the following actions. You are also welcome to add other
actions that you think are likely to be practical and effective.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="WP MathB">      </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FACE="WP MathB">                           </FONT>
<TABLE BORDER=1>

<TR><TD BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF WIDTH=408><B><FONT FACE="WP MathB">Suggested Actions:</FONT></B>
</TD><TD BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF WIDTH=84><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="WP MathB">Effectiveness</FONT>
</TD><TD BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF WIDTH=72><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="WP MathB">Practicality</FONT>
</TD><TD BGCOLOR=#FFFFFF WIDTH=60><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="WP MathB">Agency</FONT>
</TD></TR>

<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Times New Roman">1. Use the ITU or establish a new UN agency (which might include private sector) to regulate Internet and future similar systems to promote their application toward human development, especially for raising the standard of living in the developing countries.</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Times New Roman">2.  Encourage a hands-off posture toward the regulation of the content and use of international networks such as the Internet.</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Times New Roman">3.  Promote policies that expand network capabilities and tend to help avoid communications overload.</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Times New Roman">4. Recognize potential impacts of information technologies on employment and institute large-scale job and entrepreneurial training for emergent or growing economic activities. </FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Times New Roman">5</FONT><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="WP MathB">. Create an on-going global forum to freely explore the potentials of the emerging world of cyberspace.</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="WP MathB">6. Create incentives for foreign investors to accelerate the introduction of computer communications and related equipment to developing countries and facilitate the use of global networks.</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="WP MathB">7. Develop computers and software adapted for Third World and non-western cultures.</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="WP MathB">8. Develop systems to protect children and some other people's right not to be exposed to unwanted information. </FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="CG Times">9. Abandon or at least regulate to its minimum level intellectual property rights so that information can be more efficiently shared and utilized.</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="Times New Roman">10. Strengthen international property rights to encourage develop-ment of information technology products that can be marketed in developing countries.</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="WP MathB">11. Change medical and education laws to accommodate on&#173;line consultation as legitimate and covered by insurance.</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="WP MathB">12. Provide more free Internet access to the public, e.g. at public libraries and schools.</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


<TR><TD WIDTH=408><FONT SIZE=3 FACE="WP MathB">13. Promote tele&#173;national citizenship (Third World people who live and work in First World but help develop their countries via tele&#173;commuting).</FONT>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH=84><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=72><BR></TD>
<TD WIDTH=60><BR></TD>
</TR>


