<html>
<title>Look-Out Panel, Round 2 Questionnaire, Section 2, Domain 3</title>
<body bgcolor="#96E1FA">
<hr><p>
<center><font size=+3>1996 GLOBAL LOOK-OUT PANEL</font>
<p><hr><p>
<font size=+2>ROUND 2 QUESTIONNAIRE<p><b>SECTION 2</b></font><p>
<font size=+1>FULL-TEXT OF DEVELOPMENTS</font></center><p>
<br>
The second round of the 1996 Global Look-Out questionnaire comes in two sections.  You
should already have Section 1. Section 2 includes the full text of developments in only one of the
six Millennium Project domains.  Selection of the domain sent to you was based on your first
round responses, resume, publications, previous expressions of interest and or our best judgment. 
If you want to comment and add to the full text of developments in other domains, please
download them from the Millennium Project's home page:
<i>http//nko.mhpcc.edu/millennium/Millennium_Project.html</i> or request them from the
Project's coordinating office.<p>

In this second section, you are asked for comments, improvements, or additions to the material
submitted by yourself and others in the first round.  You do not have to comment on every
development in this domain, just those developments that are important to you and to which
you can contribute new consquences, strategies, and references. <p>

You can respond in several ways:<p>

1. If you received the material via email or downloaded it from the homepage, you can simply
insert you YOUR COMMENTS IN CAPITAL LETTERS or in
>some other way to identify your additions into the text and submit the whole domain back via
email >to<i> jglenn@igc.org.</i><p>

2.  You need not include the full text in your response.  You can simply write the reference
number for the development followed by your additions and email, fax, or mail it back.<p>

<hr>
<center><font size=+2><i><b>Domain 3: Technological Capacity</b></i><br></font></center>
<hr><p>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>Information, Communications</b></i><p></font></center>

15. <b>Development: </b>Extremely smart and flexible computers; real artificial intelligence<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Better problem solving. Some people feel that humans are
inferior to
computers.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>
<p>

111. <b>Development: </b>Availability of continuous speech, user-independent, computer voice
input
systems making possible a new sort of human to machine interface that requires no training.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Computers that listen and speak, like HAL in 2001, but more
importantly, computers that reduce the requirement for training.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
                                 <p>
                                  
136. <b>Development: </b>The spread of the Internet. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>While the present status of the Internet includes a great deal of
confusion and information overload, it is likely to settle down within the next decade to become
one of
the most powerful agents of change throughout the world, affecting education, science, health
care and
commerce profoundly.<br>
<b>Goal: </b>Establish a new agency of the United Nations whose mission it would be to
regulate the
use of this new utility, to foster its application toward human development, and particularly to
exploit its
potential of raising the standard of living in the developing countries.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
                             <p><hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Biomedicine and Psychiatry</b></i><p></font></center>

6. <b>Development: </b> Development of brain-like intelligent systems using neural networks, to
help
achieve a more functional understanding of human intelligence.<br>
<b>Description: </b>New designs for intelligent control are emerging in the neural network field
which
promise real brain-like intelligent systems, can help us to achieve a more functional understanding
of
intelligence as it exists in the human mind, but, on the downside, make scenarios like "Terminator
2" far
more plausible than most scientists would believe today.<br>
<b>Details:</b> I would prefer to leave that to the citations. This is the area where I have the
greatest
personal credibility, however, for a variety of reasons. A better understanding of the human mind
could
have some very vast implications, which I leave up to you. Fortunately, most of this work does
not have
"Terminator" kinds of implications.<br>
<b>References:</b> Assuming it has not been badly tinkered with, we have a Web page giving
some
details. Click on "Neural Networks" under: <i>www.nsf.gov/eng/ecs/ecs.htm.</i>  That in turn
cites
some published papers. There is also a more recent paper on the connections to neuroscience by
myself.
in K.Pribram, ed., <i>Learning as Self-Organization,</i> Erlbaum, in press. With luck, some of
the
papers themselves may be up on the web fairly soon.       <p>
                                  
47. <b>Development: </b>Personal health history records in the form of intelligent credit cards --
available to everybody, linked to a central national computer with data bank, medical
practitioners,
hospitals and laboratories have on-line links with this central computer.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Complete and perfect record linkage, reduction of unnecessary
medical
investigations and other procedures; possibility raisingstandards of diagnosis and care by applying
intelligent automatic peer review; possibility of abusing medical (and other personal) secrets; the
scheme
available to "haves" only; possibility of applying effectively and efficiently widespread public
health
interventions;<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Full computerization of personal medical and public health information<br>
<b>Domain: </b>1, 3<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>                   <p>
                                  
62. <b>Development: </b>Symbiosis with the computer - even via the keyboard.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Individuals will develop a 'personality' (especially in terms of 
'memories') which is part internal and part on the computer - with the line between these
increasingly
blurred. This will result in a 'richness' of personality - greater in scope (and capacity) and
distributed
across space. At the fringes it might start to merge with the personalities of others (making group
identity
even more powerful).
On the other hand, it poses problems in terms of the potential for new neuroses to emerge.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>To enrich the powers of the individual, especially in terms of memory<br>
<b>Domain: </b>3, 7 (social)<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>The origin of this work is Ian Pearson's work.<p>
                                  
104. <b>Development: </b>New understanding of the functioning of the brain, leading, perhaps
to the
understanding of self consciousness; integration of knowledge about neurotransmitters, the site of
certain
brain functions, and psycho pharmaceuticals.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Improvements in education, propaganda, training, memory,
diseases of
the brain and mind, understanding of consciousness, and perhaps a "Genome Project" of the brain,
cataloging the myriad interconnections of the neurons of the brain.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
                                 <p>
                                  
123. <b>Development: </b>Ability to change basic human characteristics, through genetic
engineering
or chemical interventions.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>1) Much fear and efforts to prevent its use; 2) If used,
inconceivable
changes beyond our present imagination.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>                <p><hr><p>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>Search for Extra Terrestrial
Intelligence</b></i><p></font></center>

16. <b>Development: </b>Successful scientific search for extraterrestrial intelligence; contact
with a
small probe near the earth and detection of encyclopedic message from afar.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>More sophisticated space exploration. New knowledge and
techniques.
Fresh image of humanity's place in the universe.<br>
<b><b>Potential <b>Goal: </b></b></b>Initiate a major global project to achieve dialog with a
highly
intelligent extraterrestrial probe (perhaps the size of a loaf of bread), through establishing a
"welcome
committee" and security safeguards.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>                   <p>
                                  
45. <b>Summary:</b> Extraterrestrial Life Confirmed.  <br>
<b>Development: </b>Previously secret Post W.W.II projects come to light that confirm that
humans
have been interacting with life from elsewhere for some time. Japanese unveil new museum with
parts
from crashed vehicles. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Could be negative, could be positive, could be both.  In any
case,
massive global shifts in attitudes. Depends upon whether there is any "official" contact that comes
out
into the open and what the "message" is that is  communicated from the aliens.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Become open-minded and knowledgeable enough to be able to make a
contribution to the
huge debate which will follow.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>6 <br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>National Institute for Discovery Science, Las Vegas; <p><hr><p>
                                  
<center><font size=+1><i><b>Search for Knowledge</b></i><p></font></center>

7. <b>Development: </b>Recognition that there is far more to learn in physics and other
disciplines,
that the frontiers of knowledge are unbounded.<br>
<b>Description: </b>Fundamental physics is not nearly so "closed" or "already understood" as
most
people imagine. Though it may take a long time, there are possibilities for truly massive shifts in
technology, based on figuring things out that we do not yet know at a very basic level.<br>
<b>Details: </b>Those who think things are known should read back about the turn of the last
century,
when there was MORE reason than there is today to think that "everything really important to
technology
has already been discovered." There are far more fundamental loose ends in  physics today than
there
were then... ranging from missing neutrinos, to the "age of the universe" (which casts doubt into a
lot
more things than just age), to fundamental mathematical inconsistencies, to nuclear theories we
can't
compute with and cannot therefore apply in detail, and so on. Consider how much technology has
been
changed by physics we had no clue of at the turn of the century... not only nuclear technology, but
quantum technology, which underlies modern electronics and optics....And then multiply it by the
greater
size of our basic ignorance today,  and it gives a clue to the potential for further changes. Though
I have
some more specific speculations, it is probably inappropriate to be specific at this time.<br>
<b>Strategies: </b>There are many, many challenges in stimulating a growth in basic
understanding.
Perhaps the most difficult is simply to restore or sustain the kind of culture which makes basic
discovery
possible. Individual theoretical science, and complex many-body experiments, will still be critical
to what
happens. A culture of over specialization and conformity needs to be broken down, to permit
more 
cross-fertilization and new ideas. But people who are constantly afraid of not finding jobs or
losing the
ones they have -- because of new funding and cultural realities -- may find it hard to give their
minds free
rein to the extent required for theoretical breakthroughs. And, of course, more encouragement of
gifted
children at early ages, would help in this and many other areas. Again, while I have a few more
specific
ideas, it would be inappropriate to focus on them at this time; there is a large set out there.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
                                 <p>
                                  
26. <b>Development: </b>By far the most important thing on the technological horizon is
so-called
'cold fusion' (which is probably neither). There can now be no further doubt that we are tapping
new
energy sources by several different routes.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
                                 <p>
                                  
43. <b>Development: </b>Zero-point energy/cold fusion breakthrough; beginning of end of fossil
fuels.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Energy revolution which effects every aspect of life. Potentially
eliminates most of global air pollution problems.  Allows large undeveloped countries (China) to
move 
ahead economically without adding to the pollution.  Changes the geopolitics of middle east. 
Philosophical shift: potentially decentralized way of producing power; no longer dependent upon
central
provider. <br>
<b>Goals: </b>Manage the integration of the new technology as quickly as possible while not
upsetting
the total world social systems.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>6<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b><i>Cold Fusion,</i> Wayne Green Publishing, Peterborough, NH;
Dr.
Harold Puthoff, Institute for Advanced Studies at Austin.    <p>
                                  
46. <b>Summary: </b>Development of faster than light travel.<br>
<b>Development: </b>Experimental results confirm mathematical theory that space-time can be
"engineered" to allow movement of object from one place to another instantaneously.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Radical shift in military capability (if by country other than
USA),
Rethinking much of physics and ultimately technology. Confirmation of the possibility of
extraterrestrial
travel.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Evolve into new era such that it maintains the integrity of social systems and
doesn't
shake fundamentals too abruptly.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>6<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>Various articles in scientific press.<p>
                                  
51. <b>Development: </b>Decreasing human skills development in concept formulation and
communication in an increasingly complex world.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> The gamut of human activity from perception of self to
personal
interaction to perception of the surrounding milieu has become increasingly technical and
complex. 
Despite this nominal advancement of humankind's knowledge base and capability, there are
decided
indications that such "advancement" is poorly distributed.  Many do not understand or trust
science; and,
many are incapable of communicating with others on a meaningful and workable level.  The
resultant
conflicts at all levels of interaction are readily apparent.<br>
<b>Goals: </b> Establish an understanding that individuals must learn how to learn, before being
able to
learn anything more technically  or socially complex.  There exists a plethora of information; but,
the
question remains of how can humankind best incorporate such information into knowledge?<br>
<b>Domain: </b> 3 and 4.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>  DeBono, E. (1967). <i>New Think: The Use of Lateral
Thinking in the
Generation of New Ideas.</i> New York:  Basic Books.; DeBono, E. (1971a). <i>Lateral
Thinking for
Management.</i>  New York: McGraw-Hill.             <p>
                                  
56. <b>Summary:</b> Need for scientific and philosphical thinking to explore the ethical
foundation of
advanced sciences and the scientific foundation of contemporary ethic.<br>
<b>Development: </b>There is not enough scientific and philosophical thinking that explores the
ethical
foundation of advanced sciences and the scientific foundation of contemporary ethic. This theme
should
be one of the permanent component of  the new intellectual paradigm coming out of the scientific
and
technological revolution of our time.
     Integration of biology and technology for improved bionics enhancing human capacity pose
dramatically the relations between science and ethic. A new ethic has been mentioned with regard
to
human responsibility on environmental problems.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
                                 <p>
                                  
141. <b>Development: </b>New kinds of knowledge production and certification, new carriers of
knowledge (think of environmental groups as one example).  <br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Shifting and perhaps transforming relations between knowledge
and
society, and transforming science as well.
<p><hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Machines</b></i><p></font></center>

5. <b>Summary: </b>Airplanes that can reach orbit at much lower costs than current
methods.<br>
<b>Development: </b>Substantial progress has been made, in a quiet way, towards being able to
build
airplanes that reach earth orbit AS AIRPLANES, at airplane-like costs. The resulting reduction in
transportation costs could be the difference between an "Antarctica" kind of frontier (i.e. space as
an
expensive sideshow that never takes off) versus a "transcontinental railroad" kind of frontier
(something
that starts with subsidies but ends up growing and profitable and huge).<br>
<b>Details: </b>Really cost-effective growth in a space economy requires reduction in costs far
beyond
what is expected even with the important but limited improvements now planned for
single-stage-to-orbit
rockets. Such larger reductions should be possible using Mach 26 airplanes, in effect -- but the
idea here
has traditionally been seen (correctly) as very risky. However, there has been a lot of quiet work
filling in
a lot of the key show-stoppers. For example, one of the really critical problems is to maintain
control of
propulsion systems at high speeds; new control algorithms have been developed in the neural
network
field which appear to be able to solve such problems, in principle. Preliminary tests look good.
The major
hypersonic efforts being explored at NASA now include use of neural network control. NASA,
NSF
(with myself as technical contact) and the Air Force are now acting as partners, joint funding the
LoFlyte
project, which (with its expected extensions) continues US work in this field. In addition, some
innovative concepts for using magneto-hydrodynamic effects and various other technologies show
promise in solving some other problems which have existed in the past. There is a lot more to do,
but it
appears more likely than not that success can be had in this area, if we do things right.<br>
<b>Strategies:</b> It would help to have a new interagency effort in this field, and to bring in
new
players. The biggest challenges are to restore funding, and to build bridges to the very best states
of the
art in different disciplines (as opposed to heritage technology), not only in the US but also in
Russia,
Japan and maybe elsewhere.<br>
<b>Domain:</b><br>
<b>References: </b>AIAA (American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics).  Various
hypersonics
conferences reports. E.g. On the implications, we had a report "Settling Space" embedded in the
1989
briefing book from the National Space Society. Both NSS and AIAA are in DC.<p>
                                  
42. <b>Development: </b>Development of viable hybrid automotive technology.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Massive reduction of carbon dioxide emissions from 
automobiles,
reductions of petroleum requirement, massive improvement in US balance of payments,
substantial
weakening of OPEC, reduced energy cost to aid third world develop.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Balancing US balance of payments, facilitating development of third world while
avoiding
the gluttony of the past.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>3,5<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>Rocky Mountain Institute
(http://solstice.crest.org/efficiency/rmi/index.html) is the best source on hybrid development.  Jay
Forrest
<i>(pteragen@neosoft.com)</i> is working on the resource implications of a transition to hybrid
automobiles.                           <p>
                                  
100. <b>Summary: </b>Power Relay Satellites in geosynchronous orbit, Solar Power Satellites in
Earth
orbits, and Lunar Power Satellites on the lunar surface.<br>
<b>Development: </b> Space Power System options (Power Relay Satellites, or PRS, in
geosynchronous orbit;  Solar Power Satellites, or SPS, in Earth orbits; and Lunar Power
Satellites, or
LPS, on the lunar surface)  can make  major contributions to achieving global sustainable
development
compatible with Earth's ecology.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> Wireless power transmission (WPT), with PRS across
intercontinental
distances, of power generated by terrestrial renewable resources in selected locations and relayed
to
receivers on Earth, is achievable in 20 years.  Conversion of solar energy in orbit and directed
with WPT
to receivers on Earth is achievable in 30 years.  Conversion of solar energy on the lunar surface
and
directed with WPT to receivers on Earth is achievable in 50 years. These space power systems
would
ensure the availability of unfailing, globally-distributed energy for future generations to avoid the
deleterious effects of fossil fuels or nuclear power on the ecology.  <br>
<b>Goals: </b> Space Power Systems based on 100 years of WPT development, have evolved
over a
period of 25 years.  Associated technical, economic and societal issues were, and continue to be,
assessed, and key technologies demonstrated by universities, industry and government agencies in
America, Asia and Europe.  These systems can be developed and can be capable of meeting future
global
energy demands required to achieve the desired higher living standard of the global population,
based on
current engineering knowledge and accomplishments, and considerations of economic viability
and
societal acceptability.  Space Power Systems will ensure that the benefits of relying on solar
energy will
sustain all forms of life on Earth and will be available to all.<br>
<b>Domain: </b> 6<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b> <i>Solar Energy,</i>  Special Issue on Wireless Power
Transmission,
Pergamon -  Elsevier Science Ltd. vol. 56, number 1, January l996, ISSN 0038-092X;   <i>Solar
Power
Satellites - the emerging energy option,</i>  P.E. Glaser, F.P Davidson and K.I. Csigi, editors,
John
Wiley & Sons, New York, NY, 1993, ISBN 0-471 954 284; <i>Space Solar Power Review,</i> 
Pergamon Press, Inc.  Elmsford, NY 10523, USA, vol.1 to 6, 1980 to 1985, ISSN 0191-9067.
<i>Space
Power,  Resources, Manufacturing and Development,</i>   Council for Economic and Social
Studies,
Washington, DC 20005, USA, vol. 7 to 14, 1986 to 1995, ISSN 0883-8272.  As a result of
international
contributions to this field an extensive literature on space power systems is available in Chinese,
English,
French, German, Japanese, Portuguese, Russian, and Ukrainian.<br>
<b>Additional Comments:</b>  Rationale for  Space Power Systems; Space Power Systems
should be
an integral part of the global industrialization goals to meet the insistent demands for higher living
standards of the exponentially growing population, which is estimated to reach 10 billion by
mid-21st
century. An acceptable approach to decreasing  this rate of population growth over time is to
raise the
living standard of the people. To achieve this goal increased energy supplies compatible with the
Earth's
ecology will be required on a global scale. One half of the global population will live in cities by
2000. 
The current migration into cities of 150,000 people per day will increase to 250,000 per day in 25
years. 
     There will be an unprecedented shift in economic strength during this time period, with several
emerging economies growing at least twice as fast as those of nations with mature economies. 
The
impact of these shifts will result in greatly increased consumption of available fuels.  This is
projected to escalate the degradation of the Earth's ecology to meet the energy demands of the
population
in the next century. In addition, the finite terrestrial energy resources have already, or will in the
foreseeable future, pass their peak availability. 
     Alternative energy development paths will become dominant in the post-2000 period, because
of
the growing uncertainties and extended lead times of fossil fuel power plants, refineries, and
associated
energy resource investments.  Over the next three decades capital requirements in the energy
sector are estimated to range between 13 to 20 trillion ($1990) to keep pace with the projected
doubling
of global  energy use.  The latter amount equals the total global economic output in 1990.
     There are vast fossil fuel energy resources on Earth but some are deep in the ocean or so far
underground that they are not yet and may never be economical to recover. Others like shale oil
are
environmentally unacceptable because they would require strip mining and huge amounts of
water. 
Development of oil and gas reserves is increasing at a slower rate when compared with increasing
consumption at a time when more people and countries compete for limited and declining
resources. The
deleterious consequences on the ecology of continued increases in the use of fossil fuels are not as
yet
fully determined, but indications are that placing ever-increasing reliance on these fuels is not
advisable.
     The promise of nuclear power has dimmed because long-term waste storage and safety issues
have yet to be resolved.  The potential of fusion power has not reached the stage of scientific
development to permit the solving of potential engineering challenges, to arrive at credible cost
scenarios,
and to project when it could begin to contribute.
While parts of the solution to meet global energy needs may already exist, current energy sources
are 
unlikely to meet the projected expansion of energy uses on a scale to ensure equitable access to
energy
supplies.  Now is the time to select and develop Space Power Systems that can access renewable
energy
sources on Earth and solar energy in space to sustain all forms of life on Earth.<p>
                                  
101. <b>Development: </b>Satellite systems will provide virtually instant, ubiquitous
communications
connectivity between both fixed and mobile users, including telephony, video, data, and
multi-media.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>The global telecommunications infrastructure will be much less
expensive and much more available than is generally expected. Access to affordable
communication
services will proliferate much more rapidly than current projections, based primarily on terrestrial
media,
indicate.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Deploy high capacity, high bandwidth satellite systems to serve fixed and mobile
global
users.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 3,6<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>I don't believe the full significance of this development has been
publically
discussed.                            <p>
                                  
110. <b>Summary: </b>Nanotechnology (or molecular engineering) - construction atom by atom
on the
scale of a nanometer (one billionth of a meter).<br>
<b>Development: </b> In 1990, Don Eigler of IBM moved individual xenon atoms to spell IBM
on a
nickel plate. The National Nanofabrication Facility (NNF) at Cornell University now has a US $4
million
annual budget and 250 graduate students. Other research labs are also expanding.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Improvement of manufactured products with less pollution,
energy, and
cost making a cleaner industrial revolution economically available to the poorest of countries.
Understanding of how nature's green plants' nanotechnology food factories work. Repair of aged
tissues
and organs extending human life span. Integration of biology and technology for improved bionics
enhancing human capacity. <br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b>Develop nano-robots with artificial intelligence that can be programmed
for
multi-purposes from countering AIDS and other mutating viruses to converting some forms of
pollution.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>2<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b> Ralph C. Merkle's homepage http://nano.xerox.com/nano.
Merkle heads
the Computational Nanotechnology Project at Xerox PARC in PALO ALTO, California. The
National
Nanofabrication Facility (NNF) at Cornell University in Ithaca, New York, is the largest facility of
its
kind and allows external use of its labs for research. Book, <i>The Silicon Man</i> by Charles
Platt
<i>(charles@phantom.mindvox.com)</i><br>
<b>Comment from Round 1 (Godoy):</b> Development of Nanotechnology (or molecular
engineering) is by all means one of the most advanced fields of scientific research in our days.<br>
<b>Domain (Godoy): </b>should be 1, 2, 3, 5 and 6<br>
<b>Reference and notes (Godoy): </b>"The Re-Encounter Between Ethic and Science &
Technology"
H. H. Godoy, Buenos Aires, Argentina, November 1993. Original Spanish. Lecture at the
inauguration of
the Center of Ethic, Science and Technology at the Secretary of State in Science and Technology
of the
Presidency of the Argentine Republic.              <p>
                                  
133. <b>Development: </b>Aging of existing nuclear power plants.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>The eventual safe disposal of the radioactive parts of decaying
nuclear
power plants has of yet not been solved satisfactorily. Moreover, plants of the Chernobyl type,
especially
as they age, threaten to bring about additional and possibly even more severe disasters. This
represents a
potential danger to hundreds of millions of people.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Get the international community to provide financial aid toward the dismantling of
particularly dangerous plants. Establish a well funded international committee to identify the most
reliable
methods of disposing of decommissioned nuclear plants.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b><p>

<hr><p>
Thank your very much for completing the second section of Round 2 of the Millennium Project's
1996 Global Look-Out questionnaire.  Return via Email to <i>jglenn@igc.org</i>  or fax to the
USA at 202-686-5179 or airmail to AC/UNU/ Millennium Project, 4421 Garrison Street, NW,
Washington, D.C. 20016-4055 USA. The results will be sent back to you as Part of Round 3.<p>

