<title>Look-Out Panel, Round 2 Questionnaire, Section 2, Domain 6</title>
<body bgcolor="#96E1FA">
<hr><p>
<center><font size=+3>1996 GLOBAL LOOK-OUT PANEL</font>
<p><hr><p>
<font size=+2>ROUND 2 QUESTIONNAIRE<p><b>SECTION 2</b></font><p>
<font size=+1>FULL-TEXT OF DEVELOPMENTS</font></center><p>
<br>
The second round of the 1996 Global Look-Out questionnaire comes in two sections.  You
should already have Section 1. Section 2 includes the full text of developments in only one of the
six Millennium Project domains.  Selection of the domain sent to you was based on your first
round responses, resume, publications, previous expressions of interest and or our best judgment. 
If you want to comment and add to the full text of developments in other domains, please
download them from the Millennium Project's home page:
<i>http//nko.mhpcc.edu/millennium/Millennium_Project.html</i> or request them from the
Project's coordinating office.<p>

In this second section, you are asked for comments, improvements, or additions to the material
submitted by yourself and others in the first round.  You do not have to comment on every
development in this domain, just those developments that are important to you and to which
you can contribute new consquences, strategies, and references. <p>

You can respond in several ways:<p>

1. If you received the material via email or downloaded it from the homepage, you can simply
insert you YOUR COMMENTS IN CAPITAL LETTERS or in
>some other way to identify your additions into the text and submit the whole domain back via
email >to<i> jglenn@igc.org.</i><p>

2.  You need not include the full text in your response.  You can simply write the reference
number for the development followed by your additions and email, fax, or mail it back.<p>

<hr>
<center><font size=+2><i><b>Domain 6: Integration and Whole
Futures</b></i><br></font></center>
<hr><p>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>Planning and Futures Research</b></i><p></font></center>

1. <b>Summary:</b> The failure of linear thinking about the future.<br>
<b>Development:</b> Increasing awareness regarding the importance of futuristic studies and
researches, between specialists, depending on linear thinking, without achieving integral futuristic
vision.
Also depending on previous experiences and theories related to the principals of the industrial
society,
without understanding the need and articles of creativity.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Partial understanding of the global changes. Failing to reach
sustainable solutions for global, and local, problems. Losing the possibility to reconstruct society
to
match the needs of information society. Also losing the right order of priorities. <br>
<b>Goals:</b> Understanding the interrelations between the main trends, and the basic changes 
affecting human beings these days. From this, trying to compose integral futuristic vision, which
helps to
understand the future of any human activity. Depending always on creative thinking, to free our
brains
from the control of old ways, experiences, and theories.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 6<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> 
                                 <p>
                                  
81.<b> Summary: </b>Increasing the ability of individuals and decision makers to assess a
broader
range of issues and consequences including force and violence.<br>
<b>Development:</b> Panetics: integrated study of the infliction of  suffering and the reduction
of
infliction.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Ability of individuals and decision-makers to see and assess a
broader
picture of issues and consequences in particular in view of time frames and the force and violence
involved. It might help to see in different scenarios alternative ways and help by this increase the
perception of means and effects.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> To reduce suffering in the World and make more conscious and aware.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 1, 4, 5, 6<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> <i>PANETICS Trilogy,</i> International Society for Panetics,
Ralph.
G.H. SIU, ISBN 1-884437-00-1                   <p>
                                  
94.<b> Summary: </b>Growing distance between dreams and expectations, deriving from fear of
dystopic futures.<br>
<b>Development:</b> Difference between one's dreams and expectations in his/her personal
futures and
fears coming from the expectations of dystopic global futures (environmental disasters, wars,
population
growth, etc.) - conflict in making one's dreams come true. The expectations dealing with one's
personal futures arise from a modern conception of the world and the expectations dealing with
the global
futures arise from the postmodern conception and transition from industrial to late-industrial and
information society.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> 
                                 <p>
                                  
97.<b> Summary: </b>The economic value of information is becoming more important than
information
sought for other purposes. <br>
<b>Development:</b> Effectiveness as the criterion for knowledge  In the present society,
information
is produced for sale and knowledge has become a commodity which is available in the terms
regulated by
market economy system.  The user of information is more and more often a buyer and consumer
of 
information (and knowledge), and information is a factor in the production of which the most
important
criterion has been the maximizing of as great a profit on the capital as possible.  The responsibility
of
using this information is not left at the producer but laid on the shoulders of the consumer. 
Lyotard says
that the traditional way of giving grounds to knowledge and science by themselves (by the
importance of
knowledge and science per se) is changing to a form of giving grounds on the basis of capacity
and
effectively.  When the fundamental question of a scientist or other person seeking for information
is no
more "is this true?" but "how this information could be made used of", practice has become the
guiding
force to knowledge. Von Wright speaks of practical sense which is taking over from practical
wisdom. 
Knowledge is worth knowing only in the parts which can be exploited economically.   <br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> 
                                 <p>
                                  
98. <b>Summary:</b> The growth and change of the meaning of expertise.<br>
<b>Development:</b> Firstly, the tendency to lean on experts and leave the future to them to
make
decisions and tell the rest of us what to do and to expect from it.  Secondly, one can become an
expert on
very shallow proof.  One writing or appearance in public media will make an expert. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Knowledge per se becomes superficial. Thirdly, on the other
hand,
one's expertise is extended beyond the original subject area: an expert in one subject is asked for
advice
and opinions in any other possible subject.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> 
                             <p><hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>The Pursuit of Meaning</b></i><p></font></center>

17.<b> Development: </b>The eager pursuit of greater meaning and purpose from work and from
life
(among many groups of people, not just those with plenty of food and possessions.)<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Increased emphasis on the deeper meaning and purpose of work
and
organizations to community and society. Secular religions spring up.<br>
<b>Potential Goal:</b> Initiate several major projects in the social sciences to understand the
desire for
and source of meaning and purpose in various parts of the world.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>                   <p>
                                  
99.<b> Summary: </b>The growing feeling of guilt: we know more and more about all the
human-made
problems, environmental and other, and feel less and less comfortable with our everyday life and
practice.
<br>
<b>Development:</b> Ask a 7-year old about nature and he/she starts to tell you about
the environmental global problems instead of telling about birds and bees.  Instead of more
responsible
behavior, this can lead to total indifference and destructive behaviors in one's personal life: the
problems
are so big that there is nothing one can do, so let's just enjoy it as long as we can.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> 
                             <p><hr><p>
                                  
<center><font size=+1><i><b>Social Change</b></i><p></font></center>

64.<b> Summary: </b>Memes (postulated as the smallest unit of social evolution) becoming a
new
method for planning and directing the evolution of technology and society.<br>
<b>Development:</b> The emergence of memetic engineering as a proactive planning and design
strategy.  Memes, recently postulated as the smallest unit of social evolution will become a
powerful new
method for taking charge of the evolution of technology and society, rather than the present
condition of
adaptation to constant and seemingly random change in the environment.     This development will
introduce many new metaphors and tools for organization, management and development.  These
new
tools and metaphors incorporate strategies and dynamics drawn from self organization, chaos
theory,
Chinese medicine, Taoist philosophy, cellular automata, etc.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Positive: A new renaissance of self organizing creativity and
invention, with self awareness and solidarity pulling cultures together to steward the planet into a
new
era.  An evolutionary convergence.  Negative: A new era of market based designer culture, and
cults.  A
diversity of idiosyncratic and isolated pockets of change, an evolutionary divergence.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> Develop the ability for early detection of new memes and the ability to test,
project and
or simulate the effects of these memes on target populations. Develop the capacity to "invent"
new
memes.  The process of invention will probably be closely related to predicting the negative or
positive
impacts of the new meme. Memes could be developed from an exisiting market/political/social
paradigm
or  memes could be developed through a visioning process such as scenario building or shamanic
journeying.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 6<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> Japan has already taken steps in this direction with their white
paper
approach to technology impact and design.  It has even been tentatively labeled as "Heartware". 
Heartware is an attempt to reverse the process of endlessly having to adapt to new technology.  In
heartware engineering one first visions a preferred future state and then uses this as design criteria
for
consciously evolving technology. Scenario building could be seen as a precursor to memetic
engineering.
Scenarios as currently used offer insight and options to dealing with the future, only on rare
occaisions
are they used in memetic fashion as a proactive tool to consciously engineer the future.<br>
     Bibliography: Eric Janstch, <i>Design for Evolution,</i>  Magoroh Maruyama,
<i>Morphogenetic Joint Ventures,</i>  Dawkins, on Memes.  Unfortunately time and memory
does not
allow a comprehensive bibliography at the moment.  When I have more time I would be happy to
assemble a more comprehensive bibliography.           <p>
                                  
82.<b> Development: </b>Participatory round tables that include the ability to weigh interest and
quality of contributions in given time frames and creating a new form of structuring meetings and
conferences.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Valuing contributions and increasing to talk in a way others
want to
listen to. Will reduce the input of high esteem but no content monologues of invited speakers and
will
help to structure content and meaning. Results were surprise as dialogue lives from timeliness and
exchange which can not be planned. The anticipated result is giving Voice to no-name
participants, and
allow the design of CSCW to have on-line contributions of non physical non-local meetings.
Another
result is the appreciation as time and quality in one currency and a deeper appreciation of
time-sharing
instead time-stealing and ego-exposition.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> To keep people interested and provide a feeling of having value and voice that
matters.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 1, 3, 4, 6<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> Notes on Round Tables and Open Forum as organized by
Anthony
Judge, Heiner Benking and others. The particular Roundtables were organized at the
"Un-Climate"
summit and the International Peace University.          <p>
                                  
95.<b> Summary: </b>The blurring of the borderline between truth and fiction; the certainty of
reality
is disappearing from our conception of the world.<br>
<b>Development:</b> According to Baudrillard, reality is disappearing from our conception of
the
world, because the difference between real and imaginary (illusory) has lost its functionality,
ability to
function - it is no more practical nor useful.  This can be understood so that the purpose of tales,
stories, fantasies has always been to help the human to understand his/her reality and his/her own
place in
this reality.  Now, however, reality itself has become so complex that the old, directly into story
form
translated models of explanation have often lost their ability to explain anything anymore. The
new,
strange world needs new and much more complicated stories to explain it.  It takes much more
words,
symbols, images to take over the present than before.  It is easy to try to simplify that which is
too complicated, with the help of fiction to draw anew the curves of reality, too difficult to
understand
instead of trying to explain them.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> 
                                 <p>
                                  
96.<b> Summary: </b>The blurring of the borderline between private and public. <br>
<b>Development:</b> When the importance of knowledge is growing in the society, the forms of
public
communication are diversifying and the instrumental contacting surfaces of human interaction are
widening.  It has been said often in public that the larger social areas the societal research reaches,
the
less private the life of an individual will be.  As a matter of fact this has become some kind of a
political
slogan, a tool with which certain political interest groups have criticized the size of the sector of
social policy in the society.  On the other hand, reasons for the blurring of the private and the
public
sectors can be found in politics and power conventions of the public sector.<br>
     In the change of the society, growing complexity makes it still more difficult  to perceive and
to
take over the reality.  The image from the world keeps on changing along the new material and
information which comes from the four corners of the globe through the media.  The more a
human  faces
difficulties in defining his/her situation, the more helpless and estranged or even alienated he/she
becomes,
and the more estranged the individual feels him-/herself, the less he/she trusts in the information
coming
in, and at the same time, essential and unessential lose their meaning and get also blurred.  As an
example,
during the Finnish presidential elections the contents of the candidates waste baskets were given
the same
meaning in the media as their political, social and economic points.  <br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> 
                                 <p>
                                  
117.<b> Development: </b>Changing role of women in society<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Perhaps changes in terms of values in society, different ways to
manage and lead; other ways to care for children, the elderly and the sick. This will also imply
changing
roles of men in society.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> To bring up equity in gender roles for the collective benefit.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> social<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> See documents produced in the Beijing Conference.<p><hr><p>
                                  
<center><font size=+1><i><b>New Age</b></i><p></font></center>

44.<b> Summary: </b>Wild Card: Return of the Messiah, Sri Satha Sai Baba <br>
<b>Development:</b> Sri Satha Sai Baba proves himself to be reincarnation of the Christ. Indian
holy
man who regularly does "miracles" including raising people from dead, does, in fact, as he has
promised,
convince world that he is this age's avatar.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> More people than the present millions flock to his small town in
India.  A global spiritual revolution begins.   <br>
<b>Goals:</b> Develop one's self so that they are ready for this extraordinary change<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 6<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> Many books on Baba as well as sites on Web.<p>
                                  
78.<b> Development: </b>Reconsidering consciousness, wholeness, and synthesis.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Destabilization of rigid but new era of  tolerant  and integrative
schools of thought and religions.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> Incorporation of domains, may they be physical or metaphysical.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 6, 7<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> Publications of  IONS; see also Development of  Panethics <p>
                                  
80.<b> Summary: </b>Use of space and visual access as a new way to approach synthetic realms,
making use of Virtual Reality (computer generated sense of reality) and Cyberspace in
design.<br>
<b>Development:</b> Use of space and the assimilation potential of visual access as an
orientation
realm or meaning and understanding and a new way to approach syntetic realms, making use of
VR and
Cyberspaces by providing orientation and easing understanding.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Change in world views, mental models and ways of
presentation, and
the reassurance of imagination and Eidetics.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> Ease communication and participatory exchange over issues of common
relevance.
Widen views, counteract the hardening of categories, give room for transdisciplinary,
metaphorical and
figurative explanation and curricula.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 6, 7<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> Forthcoming issue of World Futures.  Research notes ("Nature as
a 
Blackbox:   Towards a Panorama of Understanding; A Broader Spectrum for Floating Between
and
Beyond  What we Know and Miss") and....
<p>
<hr><p>
Thank your very much for completing the second section of Round 2 of the Millennium Project's
1996 Global Look-Out questionnaire.  Return via Email to <i>jglenn@igc.org</i>  or fax to the
USA at 202-686-5179 or airmail to AC/UNU/ Millennium Project, 4421 Garrison Street, NW,
Washington, D.C. 20016-4055 USA. The results will be sent back to you as Part of Round 3.<p>

