<html>
<title>Look-Out Panel, Round 2 Questionnaire, Section 2, Domain 1</title>
<body bgcolor="#96E1FA">
<hr><p>
<center><font size=+3>1996 GLOBAL LOOK-OUT PANEL</font>
<p><hr><p>
<font size=+2>ROUND 2 QUESTIONNAIRE<p><b>SECTION 2</b></font><p>
<font size=+1>FULL-TEXT OF DEVELOPMENTS</font></center><p>
<br>
The second round of the 1996 Global Look-Out questionnaire comes in two sections.  You
should already have Section 1. Section 2 includes the full text of developments in only one of the
six Millennium Project domains.  Selection of the domain sent to you was based on your first
round responses, resume, publications, previous expressions of interest and or our best judgment. 
If you want to comment and add to the full text of developments in other domains, please
download them from the Millennium Project's home page:
<i>http//nko.mhpcc.edu/millennium/Millennium_Project.html</i> or request them from the
Project's coordinating office.<p>

In this second section, you are asked for comments, improvements, or additions to the material
submitted by yourself and others in the first round.  You do not have to comment on every
development in this domain, just those developments that are important to you and to which
you can contribute new consquences, strategies, and references. <p>

You can respond in several ways:<p>

1. If you received the material via email or downloaded it from the homepage, you can simply
insert you YOUR COMMENTS IN CAPITAL LETTERS or in
>some other way to identify your additions into the text and submit the whole domain back via
email >to<i> jglenn@igc.org.</i><p>

2.  You need not include the full text in your response.  You can simply write the reference
number for the development followed by your additions and email, fax, or mail it back.<p>

<hr>
<center><font size=+2><i><b>Domain 1: Demographics and Human
Resources</b></i><br></font></center>
<hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Population</b></i><p></font></center>

24. <b>Summary: </b>High population growth among poor nations and people.<br>
<b>Development: </b>the prospects of population growth that will continue to tax available
resources of the earth and of various societies; the prospect of huge population growth among
peoples and subgroups that have the least means to support such growth (i.e., poor, uneducated
families, for whom many children means children committed to lives of poverty, misery, lack of
opportunity and education), <br>
 <b>Potential Consequences: </b>Instability and violence, increased class, communal violence,
the growth of the number of people living in poverty. <br>
<b>Goals: </b><br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>Robert F. Chandler, Jr. former president, Univ. of New
Hampshire, former. director, International Rice Research Institute, Philippines, an architect in the
rice revolution in Asia, winner of the World Food Prize (the ceremony for which took place at the
Smithsonian), is an authority in the area of population growth (as a negative phenomenon)<p>

25.  <b>Summary: </b> The growth of use and effectiveness of social marketing.<br>
<b>Development: </b>Family planning offers one type of solution; social marketing (the kind that
Eduerdo Roberto practices -- see attachment) offers another. Raising levels of education and
aspiration, as a antidote to unthinking birthing and family growth.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
<p>

31. <b>Development: </b>Development of a means of extending life span, possibly through
genetic techniques.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>                    
<p>
                     
59. <b>Development: </b> Life extension technologies, primarily bio-drugs (including melatonin,
HGH, DHEA and other hormones), will extend lifespans, enhance health, and increase human
activity during those extended years. Maximum life span could be extended by 25% perhaps even
by 60%. Other medical advances, such as replacement (cloned or grown) organs for implantation,
neural implants (of nerve tissues & electronics), will also increase longevity (for wealthier
individuals). Improved lifestyles and living conditions will allow average human life spans to be
extended and to approach maximum life span.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Longer lifespans - up to 150 years for 1 million people by 2100.
Smaller numbers of people may live beyond 160 (after 2100 AD). Around 50 million centenarians
by 2025 and at least 500 million  centenarians by 2100.  Life expectancy at birth in advanced
countries to approach 120 years by 2100.<br>
     Increased world population caused by lowered death rate. Probably million extra
by 2025 and over 1 billion extra by 2100). Average age of population will rise to almost 60 by
year 2100.  As large numbers of people approach the maximum achievable life span, the death
rate of the oldest old may climb (by the year 2100) leading to stabilization and perhaps some small
shrinkage in total world population. <br>
     Increased activities by older people, in all aspects of life but especially in sports,
tourism,
continued business activities and careers, and reduced retirement.  Bored & poorer old who are
still  physically active may produce phenomenon of delinquent elders. Tomorrow's aged will
require more resources and food than today's aged, but will require lower health care levels,
although over a much longer period. <br>
     Inheritance of wealth will become much rarer as parents require and spend much
of their
wealth. Governments dependent on inheritance taxes may seek alternatives and start to tax other
sources such as life extension drugs, and/or treatments.<br>
     Many new business opportunities will arise catering to the new old, especially in
health,
beauty, sport and travel. The relatively vulnerable older population may be susceptible to virulent
outbreaks of infections such as colds.  Sudden decreases in world population may occur, possibly
causing economic problems and instability.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Establish an unbiased investigation into the realities of life extension drugs and
treatments.  Continue to review the scientific journals for new drugs and therapies for life
extension and produce independent recommendations for their use. [Sorry, this is a duplication of
the efforts being made by the Life Extension Foundation, albeit without their hype and sales
pitch].  Encourage research projects into aging, to understand and make it more viable, and to
enhance prospects for  life extension.  Investigate the likely impacts of the life extension drugs and
treatments, on individuals, their lives, and on World population and its structure.  Integrate these
results with studies of World populations and economics to determine the viability of life
extension (at individual and global levels), and identify strategies to improve that viability.<br>
     Over the medium term, establish (national) departments to review  the
circumstances and
projected circumstances of the new aged.  In addition to humanitarian needs such as pensions and
aged  health matters, these departments should be involved with social integration of older
populations, with retirement age decisions and ways of improving creativity and productivity
throughout active life, as well as with the viability of longer lives-- the economics and
sustainability of longer-lived and older communities.  The departments should have international
links as well as local influence, so as to assist the implementation of programs which may be
politically difficult in the local arena. Although some countries may already have such
departments, (e.g. the U.S. National Institute on Aging), their programs may not be as extensive
(age-wise or in detail), nor as globally integrated as is proposed here.<br>      Establish an
(international?) science review & implementation council, with funding, to encourage basic
scientific research projects, (at national and international levels), and capable of identifying,
promoting and implementing possible technologies and/or strategies  which will enable
productivity or efficiency gains, which create wealth, and which enable people to finance and
enjoy their longer lives.<br>
     Some strategies may involve co-operation or subsidy of commercial
organizations, but the
objective would be to improve material abundance [a good foundation for improved quality of
life, which should reduce stress and crime, and is essential for longevity which otherwise might
become a misery.  Given the basics of life (in abundance), it becomes easier for humans to aspire
to higher creativity & integrity]. assist with ecologically sound advancement of human activities
such as low impact and self-sustaining industries/fisheries/etc. [Damage and loss of resources and
(especially) of our fellow species on this planet, makes life so much poorer; and without
ecological studies and knowledge, all (any) life forms, including human, can easily & unwittingly
be endangered]. <br>
     Promote and make education more freely and easily obtainable, including greater
emphasis on
life preparation, life-values, productivity during life, peace and co-operation, and science
appreciation.  Encourage United Nations to produce and distribute videos and TV programs.<br>
     Discourage all aspects of ageism.  This may include subtle advertising and
legislation where
necessary.  Create business and employment possibilities for older people, including part-time jobs
and job-sharing.  Allow tax concessions for workers who delay retirement and pensions. 
Encourage governments to adopt suitable policies and legislation, and to encourage social
structures which allow older people to remain productive.  These objectives might fall under the
jurisdiction of organizations described above.<br>
     Encourage wider public awareness of longevity and its possibilities including the
decline option
('not for me thank-you'). Self-preparation by individuals for the future (especially with financial
and career plans) is the easiest and most direct way to make later years happier and more
successful.<br>
     Identify the extent and likely impact of life extension, so that appropriate and
timely actions
can be adopted. These might include: A) Inclusion on census questionnaires of appropriate
questions to identify the usage of life extension technologies; B) Analysis of census data to
estimate longevity, and population levels into the future (From ancestor longevity data).  C)
Evaluate economic viability of longevity, and capability of individuals and governments to adapt
to and sustain those economic circumstances.<br>
     Get funding for the preparation and development of the future.<br>
     Past mistakes have often been due to lack of foresight & planning. Most of us will
be around
to appreciate the future, so it's very worthwhile to plan now and to get it right for the future. 
(This would probably be at relatively low cost).  Let's make it our new challenge, now that other
challenges such as the cold war have dissipated.  Without a challenge, we may just stumble along.
Our challenge should be preparation and development of the future, to maximize opportunities,
and minimize the pitfalls. Continuous and moderate economic growth is a keystone to that better
future.<br>
     Economic growth can be achieved through infrastructure and 'sustainable
development' of this
planet.  Greater education and specialization of the human population will follow, allowing more
people to become involved and to contribute (through jobs and interests), to the growth of the
world.  It's important to stimulate and increase the wider diversity of human interests and
activities (much of which IS already occurring).  This expansion of activity and diversity leads to
the creation of many new opportunities and leads to more jobs and greater prosperity.  Longevity
and older populations are also more likely to thrive in such circumstances.  This policy of growth
and diversity should help to avoid economic recessions, unemployment, and their attendant human
distress. The defining limit to human activity is energy in the form of food and fuel. <br>
     Although currently somewhat strained and projected to continue that way, energy
supplies can
be supplemented with solar energy, in its various guises, which is freely available and in vast
quantities.  Getting the designs right and the costs down are the challenge, and this challenge is
being met and won. Wind generated electricity is now priced at similar levels to electricity from
coal powered generators.  Photo-voltaics are approaching similar viability.  These two
achievements (examples of many) have been made possible by foresighted funding and planning. 
Science, including basic research, has much to offer the advancement of our human civilizations. 
And the limits and possibilities for harnessing its potential are almost boundless. But none of it is
possible without the funding. Will you decline the challenge?   GET FUNDED !<br>
<b>Domain: </b>1, 5, and 6<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>The Medline database, at:
<i>http://ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/cgi-bin/birx_doc?medline+nnnnnn nnnnnnn,</i>
contains many abstracts (and leads to further details) of medical and drug related experiments.
The Medline database is searchable and contains references to many bio-drugs with life extension
potential such as melatonin.<br>
     More condensed information is available from organizations such as Life
Extension
foundation.
<p>

38. <b>Summary: </b>Population growth seen as necessary to achieve economic growth and
human vitality.<br>
<b>Development: </b> Growing realization of the fundamental importance of the human resource
factor -- both in quantity and
quality -- in sustaining economic growth and thus the unfeasibility to attain it at the same time
with a global "zero population
growth" policy.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> Humanity will face the need to decide whether human society
will remain limited to existing
on this planet, thus choking expansion and growth, freezing the social status quo and becoming
used to vastly more oppressive
conditions, or allowing for planned population growth, economic expansion and technological
progress in a greatly expanded
environment, including first the solar system and later on the galaxy and the whole universe. This
will bring a reevaluation of
mega and giga technological projects, including planetary exploration and colonization,
terraforming, solar system engineering,
construction of Dyson's rings and spheres, etc., thus opening a vast new frontier for the human
species.  New social and political
structures will have to be built to coordinate such giga efforts.  A long term horizon will have to
be included in decision-making
processes.<br>
Potential Goal:  Expand the temporal and spatial planning horizon. Promote long-term
prospectives studies.  Allow for creative
and adventuresome individuals willing to assume rational risks.    <br>
<b>Domain: </b> 1,2,3<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>                      
<p>

79. <b>Development: </b>Proposed pensions schemes and incentives to invite parents to have
fewer or no children.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Gradual change of population and maintaining a manageable
international system. Dangers:
change in international exchange rates and political instabilities.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>to reduce overpopulation gradually without enforcement and hope to achieve
sustainability and, by being more
aware of time-frames and generation contracts, halting ego-centrism, bad consumption patterns
and life-styles and working
towards dematerialisation.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>1, 4, 5<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>                  
<p>

92. <b>Development: </b>Discovery that the maintenance of the tips of DNA is common to
"immortal cells" (sperm, egg, and
cancer cells) and hence, we may learn how to genetically engineer the age of different parts of the
body.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
<p>

114. <b>Development: </b>The changing age composition of the world population.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> Increased dependency ratio for social security benefits;
increased morbidity and mortality for
chronic diseases (if people do not age in a healthy way); increased health care costs for these
conditions during the last part of
life.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Redesign social security systems in the countries finding new ways to collect and
invest money so that people
have enough resources in their old age. Promote healthy lifestyles, as well as collective
responsibility for health.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>1 (demographics and human resources)<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>PAHO. Health Conditions in the Americas. PAHO, Washington,
Sept. 1994. USHEW. Healthy
People 2000, 1984 and subsequent yearly evaluations. Mesa-Lago, Carmelo. Health care for the
Poor in Latin America and the
Caribbean. Washington, D.C., PAHO Scientific Publication No. 539, 1992. Mesa-Lago, Carmelo;
Ascent to bankruptcy:
financing social security in Latin America. Pittsburgh, University of Pittsburgh Press, 1989;
Feachem, R.G. The health of adults
in the developing world. 1993.                 
<p>

132. <b>Development: </b>Increased life expectancy. During the 20th century, life expectancy
increased substantially
particularly in the developed countries; this trend is likely to continue in the 21st century.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>The retirement age at which social security payments are due to
begin will have to be indexed
to life expectancy. This will increase the total size of the labor force.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>The economies of the affected countries will have to be restructured so as to
accommodate this increased pool of
workers without, if possible, lowering living standards.<br>
<b>References and Notes:       </b>               <p>

122. <b>Development: </b>Development and widespread
availability of a chemical which permits the selection of a male or
female child before conception.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Disruption of the balance between genders, because of
preference for males in many cultures
and societies, which leads to radical and in part inconceivable consequences, such as the end of
monogamous families.<br>
Potential Goal: Stop use of this chemical or enforce selection assuring balance between males and
females, although this may
require harsh enforcement measures.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>1, but implications for all.<br>
<b>References: </b>I know of no good treatment.         <p>

138. <b>Development: </b>Drastic reduction in the quality of human population in the Third
World in the next 15-20 years as
a result of hunger, growth of infections and chronic diseases.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Incapability for simplest work, necessity of large social aid
programmes or changes of human
mentality in developed countries and new tough policy for others.<br>
Goals (Results): Growth of the vulnerability for the developed countries.<br>
<b>Domains: </b>1 and 4<br>
<b>Reference:</b> World Resources 1985-1995. Reports by the World Resources Institute.<p>
                      
<p><hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Migration</b></i><p></font></center>

34. <b>Development: </b> Ecological migration from countries affected by desertification,
floods, deforestation.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Iincrease in migration at regional level.  Increase in the need for
food,  thus enlarging the area
of the disasters,  whether desertification or other.  Need for developed countries and
intergovernmental organizations to
intervene at very high expenses.<br>
<b>Goals: </b> Create observatories that may foresee coming disasters and utilize the already
existing very good forecasts for
such natural disasters. <br>
<b>Domain: </b>2<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>                    <p>
                     
52. <b>Summary: </b>Migration of large numbers of people from the developing world to the
developed world and from rural
to urban settings.<br>
<b>Development: </b> Environmental, economic and social triage.  Social, economic and
environmental pressures are forcing
the migration of large numbers of people from the developing world to the developed world from
rural to urban settings.  In light
of such large scale movement increasingly barriers are being mounted that will likely prove neither
equitable nor effective in
their application.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> The consequences myriad and range from increased disease
incidence to ethnic conflict to
wealth concentration.<br>
<b>Goals: </b> Realistic valuation of the biogeosphere's finite resources; more equitable
distribution of information (and
"wealth") within a stabilized global population.<br>
<b>Domain(s):</b>  1 and 5.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b> As yet, searching for relevant reference.  As I remember there
was a commentary on this subject
by Bostwick Ketchum in Bioscience in the early 1970s.      <p>

<hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Medicine and Health</b></i><p></font></center>

18. <b>Development: </b>Gene therapy becoming a conventional therapuetic approach in
medicine; initiative in the genetic
approach to human health (GAHH)<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Current emphasis on research to explore the complex interplay
of genes, environment and
lifestyle in common diseases, on new diagnostic applications, and gene therapy.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>To address the priority scientific clinical and social issues in this key area.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>                  <p>

19. <b>Development: </b>Completion of the Human Genome Mapping Project (HGMP), leading
to the capacity for predictive
diagnosis and anticipation of behavioral propensities.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Genetic information from other organisms can be used to
develop models of human inherited
diseases.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>To generate a sequence map of the human genome within the next 5 years and
build on experiences gained with
Caenor Habditis Elagans sequencing project which is nearing completion.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>3<br>
<b>References: </b>Coordinating Committee on HGMP (Chair: George Radda) Medical 
Research Council, UK. ISSN 0141-2256 Annual Report, 1994-1995, p. 12. 20 Park Crescent,
London, WIN 4AL. 0171- 636 5422.<br>
                                <p>

32. <b>Development: </b>The spread of sexually transmitted diseases (STDs) to women and
young girls<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Increase and infant mortality due to AIDS infected mothers    
<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Gearing education for young girls between 5 and 15 in the direction of avoiding
AIDS infections, health
information, knowledge of the body and ethical issues.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>1<br>
<b>References: </b>Prof. Aklilu Lemma, Special Program for Youth, Health and Development in
Africa, John Hopkins
University, School of Hygiene and Public Health, 615 North Wolfe Street - Room 5039,
Baltimore, MD 21205-2179. Tel. 410-9553934 fax 410-9557159 <p>

48. <b>Development: </b>Increased frequency of re-emerging and new diseases.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>New very severe diseases will be emerging with an increasing
frequency, every few years,
every year, every few months; old diseases (now mostly under control) will be re-emerging
partners of new diseases; human
technological defenses will not cope, due to the lack of time and resources.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Search for new non-conventional technologies to come to an equilibrium with the
new and re-emerging
diseases.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>3<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>                  <p>

58. <b>Summary: </b>Some governments abdicating their responsibilties in public health as a
result of budget
contractions.<br>
<b>Development: </b>Most governments in countries at all levels of development are
experiencing budget contraction in the
social services, particularly health.  In developing and newly independent states major
development and funding agencies are
encouraging downsizing and privatization in health services that were formally provided by the
government at one level or
another.  While this may be necessary, its needs to be better managed.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Without great care in choosing what is to be reduced or
eliminated from government health
services, very important disease prevention and control functions can be lost.  The negative health
results are often immediate,
e.g. diphtheria deaths in NIS countries.  Governments are basically abdicating their responsibilities
in public health,
responsibilities only they can fulfill.<br>
<b>Goal/Strategy:</b> One idea that is being floated here in WHO is to create a list of "essential
public health functions", now
and those that are expected to be essential in the year 2020, which all countries should ensure are
properly carried out by
government, NGO or community sources.  WHO and other international agencies can assist in
devising assessment criteria and
methods and in strengthening common weak areas, such as disease surveillance, using new
communication technologies.<br>
<b>Domain: </b> You need a new domain for health, otherwise put it in 7, other.<br>
<b>References: </b>We have many references, but hope to be coming forth with an interim
product on this subject soon.<p>

108. <b>Development: </b>Presence of HIV in 25% of the adult population of essentially all
cities in sub-Sahara Africa.
(WHO comments: The 25% level is true in the 5-10 major cities in sub-Sahara Africa).<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Drastic reduction in the number of bright young people who
would ordinarily take over
leadership positions; some forms of re-colonialism; fleeing tourism; acceleration of brain drain;
collapsing population growth.
"By the year 2010, demographers estimate that AIDS will have lowered life expectancy from 66
to 33 years in Zambia, from 70
to 40 in Zimbabwe, from 68 to 40 in Kenya, and from 59 to 31 years in Uganda," according to a
National Academy of Sciences
(USA) report.<br>
<b>Potential Goal:</b> Once immunization and or treatment of AIDS is discovered, production
of a television and radio
program on a new morality that also gives immunization and or treatment delivery information
that is so entertaining that at least
50% of Sub-Saharan Africans listen to it daily.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>1, 4, and 5<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>Caldwell and Caldwell, "The African AIDS Epidemic," Scientific
American, March 1996. And
"Preventing and Mitigating AIDS in Sub-Saharan Africa: Research and Data Priorities," National
Academy Press ISBN 0-309-05480-X<br>
<b>Comment from Round 1 (Godoy): </b>Development: The presence of HIV in 25% of adult
population in practically all
cities of sub-Sahara Africa should not be approached as one of the "African problems". HIV is by
all means a "Global problem"
worth of "Global concern" and "Global responsibility" and, therefore, must be treated "locally"
but with "Global resources" -
scientific, institutional and financial resources - and not only in Africa, but in all places where HIV
is present..
<p>
                     
113. <b>Development: </b>Increasing resistance to antibiotics.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Increased morbidity and mortality for diseases and conditions
that were previously controlled.
Increased health care expenditures, as well as social costs in terms of days lost from school or
work.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>At the macro level, increased efforts to minimize the impact of those determinants
of health with incidence on
certain conditions or diseases (poverty, housing, environment, work, etc.). At the health sector
level development of resistant
antibiotics.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>health<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>Evans, Robert, Morris L. Barer and Theodore Marmor. "Why
some people are healthy and
others not? The determinants of health of populations." Aldine de Gruyter, New York, 1994. (On
resistance to antibiotics, many
articles in scientific journals, I do not have the bibliography right of hand at the moment); Sagan,
L.A. Health of Nations. The
Actual causes of health and illness from an international perspective. 1993.
<p>

<hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Food and Water</b></i><p></font></center>

39. <b>Development: </b>Increased food scarcity owing to population growth and a general
inability to increase production to
keep up with that growth.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>In the developed countries of the world, higher food prices will
lead to inflationary pressures
which dampen economic growth and contribute to increased inequality and political discontent. In
the developing countries,
these same forces will be at work, but to a greater degree, especially in countries which rely
heavily on food imports.
Economically insecure segments of the population may strike to demand higher wages, and/or
pressure their governments to
subsidize food prices. Some governments may forcibly repress such discontent, abandoning
democratic practices, and/or turn
outward and refuse to fulfill their debt obligations to developed countries, thereby further
endangering global economic growth
and political cooperation. In the underdeveloped countries, food will be too expensive or scarce
for a significant number, leading
to increased malnutrition, economic misery, and the unchecked spread of disease. In some of
these countries, the threat of
starvation and political discontent will lead to anarchy and/or civil war, causing economic and
political systems to collapse. Mass
migrations into neighboring countries will lead to tension and hostilities between those states able
to keep their military
institutions intact.  After a prolonged period (perhaps decades),  food scarcity will abate given
that starvation, plague, war, and
violent crime will reduce human numbers and the demand for world food production.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Coordinated global efforts and financial  incentives directed towards
contraception and sterilization to reduce
population growth. Forgive debt owed by poorer nations under conditions that savings will be
used to improve the productive
capacity of their farmers. Educational campaigns and heavy taxes on meat to encourage
consumers in wealthier countries to
adopt diets which to rely on the direct consumption of grain rather than grain-consuming
livestock. Increased investments in
biotechnology to create higher yielding crop varieties.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>1, 4, and 5<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>Kaplan, Robert, "The Coming Anarchy," <i>Atlantic
Monthly</i>, February 1994.; Catton,
William, Overshoot. <i>The ecological basis of revolutionary change</i>, Urbana and Chicago:
University of Illinois Press,
1982.;  Homer-Dixon, Thomas F., <i>Environmental scarcity and global security</i>,   New
York, NY: Foreign Policy
Association, 1993.; Ophuls, William, <i>Ecology and the politics of scarcity : The unraveling of
the American dream</i>, San
Francisco: W. H. Freeman, c1992.; Ehrlich, Paul R., and Anne Ehrlich, <i>The Population
Explosion</i>, New York: Simon
and Schuster, c1990.;  Brown, Lester Russell, and Hal Kane, <i>Full house: reassessing the
earth's population carrying
capacity</i>, 1st ed.  New York: W.W. Norton & Co., c1994.;  Hardin, Garrett, <i>Living
within Limits: Ecology, Economics,
and Population Taboos</i>, Oxford University Press, 1993.;  Meadows, Donella H., Dennis L.
Meadows, & Jorgen Randers,
<i>Beyond the Limits: Confronting Global Collapse, Envisioning a Sustainable Future</i>,
Chelsea Green, c1992. 
<p>
                     
40. <b>Summary: </b>Increased scarcity of fresh water, possibly exacerbated by global
warming.<br>
<b>Development: </b>Increased scarcity of fresh water in localized areas around the world. 
Also, while the severity and exact
effects of global warming remain unknown, any change in rainfall patterns will undermine the
effectiveness of existing water
control, storage and distribution facilities and widen the areas affected by scarcity.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Decreased availability of water is a contributing factor in
limiting global food production.
Competition between urban users and irrigators will typically lead to the retirement of farmland.
In regions where water is
particularly short, and people are relatively poor, increased reliance on polluted or sewage-tainted
waters will increase the
likelihood of disease.  International tensions will arise between nations sharing river basins and
groundwater sources, leading to
possible military action to secure the scarce resource. Those countries or regions currently facing
scarcity include: eleven
African countries, including those sharing the Nile River; nine Middle Eastern countries, including
the politically volatile region
of Israel, Jordan, Syria, and the Palestinian West Bank; northern China, including the country's
capital, Beijing, and the
agricultural lands surrounding it; India, including the country's capital, New Delhi and tens of
thousands of rural villages
dependent on irrigated farming; Mexico, including its capital, Mexico City, and the large,
productive irrigated farmlands in the
country's arid northern portion; and finally, some cities and irrigated farmlands of the western
United States. <br>
<b>Goals: </b>Encourage conservation through the diffusion of techniques and technologies
which improve the efficient use
and management of fresh water resources. Develop water trading and marketing practices which
allow users and managers to
better allocate scarce supplies as well as fund conservation and infrastructure improvements.
Secure treaties and cooperative
agreements between nations sharing water sources before increased scarcity pushes them<br>
into political confrontation.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>2, 3, 4, and 5.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>Postel, Sandra, Last Oasis: Facing Water Scarcity, New York:
W.W. Norton and Company,
1992.; Glantz, Micheal, ed.,  Societal Responses to Regional Climate Change, Boulder: Westview
Press, 1988.
<p>
                     
61. <b>Development: </b>Increasing need to improve water resources, for larger populations,
and to alleviate demand and
pollution pressures on existing waterways.  <br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>In the future, it seems highly likely that demand for water will
increase and that the price of
water will need to rise to encourage economy in water use, and to cover higher production
costs.<br>
<b>Goals/Strategy:</b> Establish a World Water Agency to develop and expedite new water
technology and water
extraction/collection projects.  It also might arbitrate in disputes over water, and be able to
suggest alternative solutions.  By
establishing a 'United Nations' of water, consensus could be established to accept quotas of higher
priced man-made water, and
to equalize water prices, preparing the way for man-made water production projects such as
OTEC ships. World Water Agency
could assist the research and deployment of water conservation technologies, and techniques
which allow better utilization of
water resources, especially in agriculture. Man-made water production methods (e.g. distillation
of seawater) are expensive.
New methods need to be found or cheaper ones such as OTEC (ocean thermal energy conversion)
need to be widely deployed. 
Because it requires cold water from the deep ocean, OTEC technology has not been widely
adopted due to ocean access and
delivery problems.  OTEC can also provide energy and marine food as well as fresh water, so if it
can be developed, it offers a
very environmentally friendly way to enhance World water supplies.  Design, funding and
operation of man-made water projects
(such as OTEC ships), requires greater resources than most corporations are capable, (and less
profitably than their other
activities).  World Water Agency could be the way to expedite inexpensive man-made water
production, probably using
OTEC.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>                                
<p>

102. <b>Summary: </b>Novel protein foods significantly replacing meat.<br>
<b>Development: </b>'Novel Protein Food' (NPF) will get a significant role in the 'processed
meat' market. You should not
think of the vegetarian market, but the novel protein food will be eaten next to meat.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>The reduction of meat production will reduce the environmental
impact with a factor 5-20.
However, this will also have a negative consequence for the employment in the meat
industry.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Further technological developments and health-studies to provide information
about the safety of using NPF.
The acceptance of NPF within our society (culture).<br>
<b>Domain: </b>1,2,5<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>The Dutch project for Sustainable Technology Development,
several reports on Novel Protein
Food.                              
<p>

119. <b>Development: </b>China's buying of food on the world market impedes the ability of
poorer countries to provide
themselves with food.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>                  
<p>

140. <b>Summary: </b>Deterioriation of public and
personal hygiene (public sanitation of water and waste streams).<br>
<b>Development: </b>The re-appearance of (public, personal) hygiene as an issue in the
"prospectives" about environmental
issues (the international one just concluded by the Maison Descartes in Paris, in which I am
somewhat involved). Politically, this
is still invisible, or has no political clout.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>I expect that the  situation will gradually deteriorate, until a
number of epidemics break out,
and something must be done.
<b>References and Notes:</b><p>

<hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Education and Leisure</b></i><p></font></center>

22. <b>Summary: </b>Technological displacement of workers.<br>     
<b>Development: </b> The issue of job development and therefore income
distribution in the
light of technological
displacement of jobs, the skewing of job deployment according to hi-tech, medium-tech, lo-tech,
the skewing of jobs among
post-industrial, industrial, and non-industrial societies, etc.  <br>     
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>the lack of jobs (income, status) may be
particularly
detrimental in industrializing (third-world) societies, where universities are producing graduates
and graduates have little or no prospect of employment
commensurate to their training, status, and expectation potential for alienation and violence
resulting; the lack of income,
individually and collectively for societies; the social instability and personal insecurity that arises.
Finding new types of
employment, professional service, social service, for educated elites for whom the conventional
economy is not likely to
generate. <br> 
<b>Goals: </b>Jobs and job satisfaction; e.g., raising the status of education,
social services,
child care and development,
continuing education, voluntary community action, as possible new avenues for jobs and income,
presumably supported by
governments and by international organizations.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>                  
<p>

84. <b>Summary: </b>Proliferation of information
technology displacing many low- skilled, well-paid workers in the
developed world; simultaneously, shortage of people with adequate skills.<br>
<b>Development: </b>Proliferation of information technology displaces many low-skilled,
relatively well-paid workers in the
developed world (secretaries just the beginning -- customer service reps, mortgage loan officers,
bank tellers, security guards,
administrative support personnel, etc.).  There are concurrent labor shortages in high technology
fields because organizations
cannot find people with adequate IT skills.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> Deteriorating tax base as people unable to find new work at
comparable pay.  Social unrest
and upheaval (crime) with no economic means to fix.  Increasing distance between "haves" and
"have nots." Increasing efficiency
for firms (usually forces competitors to match the efforts of the firm with the competitive
advantage).  Opportunity for 
technologically literate societies.  There is job creation (in the orgs. that develop the IT and
software) but it requires significantly
higher skill than many of the jobs IT displaced. Downsizing may not displace all workers into
unemployment (many find other
jobs, usually at lower levels of pay), but it does cut into the overall ability, of a society to consume
goods and services.  Are
major corporations effectively eliminating each others customer base by laying them off?<br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b>Education, education, education.  Example:  To try and improve the
technological literacy of its
populace, Japan offers incentives (such as overnight electronic transfer of tax refunds to those
citizens who file their income tax
statement electronically).  Millions of people use public kiosks to file, and millions more are finally
motivated to purchase home
PCs to do the same.  PC ownership in Japan goes from about 15% in 1995 to 45% 16 months
later.  Many of these owners are
between that ages of 30 and 50, exactly the citizens who needed to upgrade their IT skills the
most. <br>
<b>Domain: </b> 5<br>
<b>References: </b>See Jeremy Rifkin, William Bridges, Robert Reich, etc.  All have written
about the symptoms of the
problem, perhaps only Reich has written about some of the root causes
<p>                

66. <b>Summary: </b>Distance learning increasingly practical, through the Internet and World
Wide Web multimedia
capabilities.<br>
<b>Development: </b>Distance learning is possible and increasingly practical, thanks to the
growing reach of the Internet and
to the multimedia capabilities of the World Wide Web.  Simultaneously, distance learning is
increasingly needed because rapid
changes in technology, commerce, etc. have rendered the concept of a "completed" education
obsolete.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> Billions of individuals around the world will have a continuing
need to update their skills or
learn new ones.  Compared to traditional classrooms/training centers, virtual classrooms are less
expensive to create, easier to
maintain, and more convenient.  If distance learning can become effective enough, it can help
solve major problems associated
with economic change and dislocation, as well as contributing to human enrichment. <br>
<b>Potential Goals: </b> Accelerate progress in developing the techniques and technologies to
make distance learning more
effective as a substitute for traditional approaches.  Ensure that the Internet, or whatever
supplants the Internet, evolves with the
capabilities that distance learning requires.  Governments, businesses, unions, educational
institutions, and the public can all
benefit from  fulfilling these goals.<br>
<b>Domains: </b>1, 3, 5<br>
<b>Ref.:</b> "Distance Learning on the Net"
<I>(http://homepage.interaccess.com/~ghoyle/).</i>
<p>

71. <b>Development: </b>'Learning Organization' concepts increasingly recognized as the most
innovative and useful new
management technique of the past decade.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>If we do not learn faster than the amount of change that is going
on there is little hope of progress.
Also the ability of an organization to learn faster than its competitors is considered as its only
sustainable competitive advantage.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>To put 'learning' at the top of the agenda for us all as individuals, as well as for
organizations (and societies) to
recognize that it is critical for their survival. (Perhaps there is scope for a major Millennium
Project on 'What can we learn from
history?')<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b><i>The Fifth Discipline</i>, Peter M. Senge, Doubleday
(1990); <i>Knowledge for Action</i>,
Chris Argyris, Jossey Bass (1993).               
<p>
                
73. <b>Development: </b> Through satellite TV/Computer links, instant access to essentially
everyone, and to all the information
that is available in the world. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Unless there is an increasing  easily generate intellectual
exhaustion on the quality of this material.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>To ensure that 'quality' rather than 'quantity' focused management techniques are
developed to help us with the new
knowledge explosion. This leads to (and overlaps with) the need for a new learning revolution.
(Similar to the historic revolutions
that were driven by reading/writing and printing breakthroughs?) Acceptance of the concept of
mental pollution in the same way as
we are increasingly concerned about physical pollution. The media (as a product) needs to accept
responsibility for its (long term)
consequences in a similar way to manufacturers. The importance of increased research to monitor
critical areas and their consequence
needs to be emphasized.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>        
<p>

93. <b>Development: </b>Integration of human consciousness and technology: increasingly
technology is being put into and on
the human body; and intelligent technology is being put in the environment.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Merger of these two trends will make a continuum of
technology and consciousness on a species-wide and global basis. Globally, anyone in one
geographic point can access cyberscpace to affect or be affected by others at any other
locations geographically.  Locally, anyone can shake hands with another transmitting data through
each other's body to computers
located in their shoes.  Locally and globally, the majority of people and intelligent technology
become an integrated whole or a
"Conscious-Technology" civilization.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Enlightenment of Conscious-Technology civilization by deliberately merging the
mystic's attitude toward the world
and the technocrats' management of the world. <br>
<b>References: </b>CBS Television interview of Nicholas Negroponte of the Media Lab, MIT
April 28, 1996.<i> The Human
Interface</i> by Richard Bolt (Lifetime Learning Publications 1984). <i>Future Mind</i> by
Jerome Clayton Glenn (TBS Japanese
version 1994, Acropolis Books English version 1989).
<p>

125. <b>Development: </b>As a result of entry of many countries into the post-industrial era,
growth of unemployment and free
time, and the division of the population into "able" and "unable."<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>The problem of the rate of unemployment and the spending of
free time, the division of the
population into "able" and "unable" to make themselves useful in intellectually demanding
employment, etc. in post industrial
countries. Many other countries will remain for a long time in the stage of industrial development
and some countries will continue
to be in the agricultural stage of development.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>1, 4, 5, 6<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>Gore, A. (1992) <i>Earth in Balance: Ecology and the Human
Spirit</i>. Houghton Mifflin and
Co. Boston; Novacek, P. Mederly, P. et al. (1996) <i>Strategy of Sustainable Development for
the Czech Republic--Case Study
of the County in Transition</i>. G Plus G Publishing House, Prague (in Czech, mscr. in
English).
<p>

139. <b>Development: </b>Non-technological development of natural capabilities for increasing
the effectiveness of the human
brain by three-four times (now 6-8%).<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Jump progress in many directions. Division of the society in two
parts and social vulnerability
growth.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Transition to the new model of development.<br>
<b>Domains: </b>all<br>
<b>Reference:</b> V. Levi. <i>Your Opportunities, Man</i>. Moscow, 1984.
<p>

<hr><p>
Thank your very much for completing the second section of Round 2 of the Millennium Project's
1996 Global Look-Out questionnaire.  Return via Email to <i>jglenn@igc.org</i>  or fax to the
USA at 202-686-5179 or airmail to AC/UNU/ Millennium Project, 4421 Garrison Street, NW,
Washington, D.C. 20016-4055 USA. The results will be sent back to you as Part of Round 3.<p>

