<title>Look-Out Panel, Round 2 Questionnaire, Section 2, Domain 4</title>
<body bgcolor="#96E1FA">
<hr><p>
<center><font size=+3>1996 GLOBAL LOOK-OUT PANEL</font>
<p><hr><p>
<font size=+2>ROUND 2 QUESTIONNAIRE<p><b>SECTION 2</b></font><p>
<font size=+1>FULL-TEXT OF DEVELOPMENTS</font></center><p>
<br>
The second round of the 1996 Global Look-Out questionnaire comes in two sections.  You
should already have Section 1. Section 2 includes the full text of developments in only one of the
six Millennium Project domains.  Selection of the domain sent to you was based on your first
round responses, resume, publications, previous expressions of interest and or our best judgment. 
If you want to comment and add to the full text of developments in other domains, please
download them from the Millennium Project's home page:
<i>http//nko.mhpcc.edu/millennium/Millennium_Project.html</i> or request them from the
Project's coordinating office.<p>

In this second section, you are asked for comments, improvements, or additions to the material
submitted by yourself and others in the first round.  You do not have to comment on every
development in this domain, just those developments that are important to you and to which
you can contribute new consquences, strategies, and references. <p>

You can respond in several ways:<p>

1. If you received the material via email or downloaded it from the homepage, you can simply
insert you YOUR COMMENTS IN CAPITAL LETTERS or in
>some other way to identify your additions into the text and submit the whole domain back via
email >to<i> jglenn@igc.org.</i><p>

2.  You need not include the full text in your response.  You can simply write the reference
number for the development followed by your additions and email, fax, or mail it back.<p>

<hr>
<center><font size=+2><i><b>Domain 4: Governance and
Conflict</b></i><br></font></center>
<hr><p>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>War and Political Instability</b></i><p></font></center>

11. <b>Development:</b> The threat of weapons in outer space, as the proposed Star Wars gains
support among Republicans. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b>  Spreading lethal warfare into outer space, contaminating outer
space
and possibly preventing humanity from taking its natural next step in the development of
resources,
habitats and energy from space.  Losing vital time in establishing a non-terrestrial resource base in
space,
which may prove to be vital to humanity's long range future. <br>
     Development of a 30 years Earth-Space Human Development Long Range Program whose
goal
would be the establishment of an environmental niche for humanity in the solar system with
maximum
benefit to Earth life.  It should be designed as an organic step by step evolution from a closed to
an open
world scenario, as outlined by the late Rockwell Space scientist, Krafft  Ehricke in his
Extraterrestrial
Imperative.  This manuscript is still unpublished, as far as I know, but technical papers are
available. 
SYNCONs , the synergistic convergence process developed by The Committee for the Future,
should be
used to identify and strategize the positive effects of this long-range evolutionary goal on all
systems and
functions in the social body.  New governmental, corporate and public participation should be
invented to
provide maximum international cooperation, public participation and democratic choice in the
great
pioneering effort of the 21st century.   <br>
<b>Domain:</b> (6) <br>
<b>References: </b>Various space reports.            <p>
                                  
23. <b>Summary:</b> Religious, racial, ethnic, ideological wars such as in Rwanda and
Liberia.<br>
<b>Development:</b> the prospect of further increase and scope of collective and communal
violence,
resulting from religious, racial, ethnic, ideological wars; the prospect of collective violence
increasing as
we reach the new millennium (and the intensification of superstitions, mystical, millennial causes,
fringe
religions and cults, etc. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> (It would be a good idea to chart, with whatever data available,
the
slopes and frequencies of forms of collective violence, during the past 100 years: is there a
discernible
increase, in what forms, etc.?) The consequences of these forms of potential violence can be seen
in
Rwanda, Liberia, in Iran (with respect to what is done to its own people as well as what is done to
others), etc. <br>
<b>Goals:</b> More research projects uncovering the causes of collective violence (or
religiously-fanatical-driven violence), etc. <br>
<b>Domain:</b> # 4 (Governance and Conflict)<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>                   <p>
                                  
33. <b>Development:</b> Cultural contrast developing in ethnic wars such as Rwanda and
Liberia.
Spread of cultural conflicts could be avoided by careful observation of cultural trends in a country
and
possibly prevent the spreading of conflicts. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b>  Continuous conflicts. Increase in migration at regional and
interregnal level thus provoking environmental, political and economic tensions. See migration
from
African Countries to South European Countries and within Africa.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> Creation of interdisciplinary observatories to at least foresee the possible
development of
such conflicts and alert  decision makers. <br>
<b>Domain:</b> 7<br>
<b>References:</b><i> The Futures of Cultures, Future Oriented Studies,</i> UNESCO, Paris,
1994.<p>
                                  
36. <b>Development:</b> Mexico's recurrent economic and political crises provoke national
disintegration posing severe and immediate challenges to the U.S. and the North American
Region,
including low intensity conlict.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b>  Low and medium intensity regional conflicts in Mexico
threaten to
spill over the border.  Serious disruption of most nationwide economic processes significantly
increase
poverty throughout the country and with it, the likelihood of riots, famine and widespread
epidemics. 
Worsening economic and political conditions force massive movements of Mexican population.
The flux
of immigrants to the U.S. grows rapidly and without control.  U.S. is gradually impacted by the
turmoil
of its southern neighbor.  First the border areas, then territories farther away.<br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b> To avoid such catastrophic development, economic growth and
political reform are two necessary goals.  The U.S. government should be ready to help Mexico
achieve
political reform by establishing a cautious but firm policy of 1) demanding respect for basic human
rights,
internationally supervised free elections and accountability of public officials;  2) Linking
economic and
financial aid to political reform;  3) Closely supervising Mexico's economic policies;  4) Being
agreeable
to: first a monetary union, and second: economic and political integration.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 4 <br>           
<b>References and Notes:</b>
                                 <p>
                                  
77. <b>Summary:</b> Emergence of nationalism in Asia, e.g. Japan, (including the possibility of
a
Japanese military buildup), in response to the continued pressure from the US, China and Korea.
<br>
<b>Development:</b> Stability of regional relations is challenged. Japanese unconscious
readiness to
allow military buildup is becoming surface in the form of open demands for a constitutional
change and
recognition of its Self Defense Forces as an integral element of international contribution through
a series
of PKD participation. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Together with Chinese and Korean demands for compensation,
even
after 50 years since the end of the war, the US demands for Japanese burden sharing in regional
defense
and economic and trade concessions will invite Japan's resurgence as an independent military
power. This
will cause a serious power rivalry tension in Asia and derail its economic dynamism.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> Establish both official and non official back channels of communication among the
major
nations in Asia and the US. Disseminate information about dangerous developments at an early
stage and
appeal to the common sense of decision makers and the public alike.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 4<br>
