<center><font size=+1><i><b>Terrorism and Crime</b></i><p></font></center>

3.  <b>Development:</b> Nuclear terrorism and proliferation pose far more of a threat to the
survival
of the human species than is generally appreciated. Almost everyone knows that the stuff is "bad,"
but the
INTEGRATED implications for the global system are what's misunderstood.<br>
<b>Description:</b> DOE analyses of things like the diversion of nuclear materials tend to lead
to bad
stuff out there proportional to the product of two variables: (1) the volume of material moving
around;
(2) the average slackness of the control over its movement, at the micro level, wherever it is
moving.
Both variables have been on an alarming growth curve, and will have to grow even a whole lot
faster in
the future, if we don't develop other alternative energy sources (besides nuclear) fast enough.
There are
people responsible for proliferation policy who will say "The cat's already out of the bag anyway"
-- but
the sheer size of the cat can turn into another kind of beast.   Furthermore, once the nuclear
capabilities
do proliferate far enough -- once the number of actors increases by an order of magnitude or two,
the
number of actors with delivery systems also increases, and the level of craziness of the craziest
actors
increases, the probability of a weapon being used on people will grow by orders of magnitude.
This leads
to two possible scenarios: (1) the "Herman Kahn" scenario, where using nuclear weapons no
longer
becomes unthinkable, and the precedent breeds far more use; (2) the extreme revulsion scenario
(which I
tend to believe), where the public overreaction -- a thousand times as powerful as the reaction to
Chernobyl, which was already quite chilling -- leads to violently anti-technological regimes,
regimes
powerful enough to stifle economic growth and innovation to the point where human survival is
really put
into question.<br>
<b>Strategies:</b> Oh do I wish I had the answer to that! But a friend who used to ghost-write a
lot of
the Los Alamos effort in this field tells me that it would help if we simply put things back under
the
purview of people who really care about the issue and are tough-minded about details. Also, I can
imagine some hopes for improved US-China collaboration straightening things out, but that in
turn would
take a lot of effort. The general effort to reduce famine and despair by limiting population growth
would
certainly help a little, in the long-term. In the short term, the India-Pakistan situation is an obvious
one to
work harder on.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 6<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> 
                                 <p>
                                  
134. <b>Summary:</b> The rise of international terrorism. <br>
<b>Development:</b> As the gap in living standards between developed and under developed
countries
increases, the latter, in view of the fruitlessness of traditional methods of warfare are likely to
resort,
more and more, to the use of terrorism, possibly including nuclear blackmail.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Too obvious to mention.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> A massive shift in resources from traditional national defense to anti-terrorism.
While
current expenditures in these respects may on the order of 10:1 they may well have to tend
toward a 1:1
ratio.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
                                 <p>
37. <b>Summary:</b> High-tech terrorism.<br>
<b>Development:</b>  Single individuals and small groups will be able, through technological
advances,  to decisively affect and/or disrupt regional, national and global processes, even
worldwide
development.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b>  Increased fragility of global systems allows for massive
transfers of
power to individuals and groups unconstrained by commonly accepted rules of behavior. 
Terrorism and
blackmail in unprecedented scales will become major threats to world civilization.   Indecisive or
untimely
responses by society to these challenges will reinforce existing incentives to challenge all
established
rules.  Many concerned groups will advocate limiting freedom and increased government
surveillance and
repression.  Some others will even try to limit technology's development. <br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b> Plan to build resilience and redundancies into socio-technical systems to
avoid possible catastrophic disruptions.  International cooperation in tracking and punishing
terrorists.<br>
<b>Domain:</b>  3,4                       <br>
                    <b>References and Notes:</b>
                                 <p>
                                  
70. <b>Summary:</b> Organized crime groups are becoming sophisticated global enterprises
with the
technical know-how to yield enormous illegal profits (information fraud, organ traffic, arms
traffic, etc.).
<br>
<b>Development:</b> (Examples include: 1991 bank fraud of $2.2 billion; telephone fraud $4
billion,
credit card fraud, $1.5 billion). Information technology is accelerating the movement and quality
of
money and information. (US financial institutions transfer over one trillion dollars via computer
networks
daily). Facilitates global operations.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> Get ahead of organized crime networks using more advanced technology and
establishing international criminal law; address new crime areas such as illegal waste disposal,
human
organ traffic and arms traffic.<br>
<b>Domains:</b> 2, 3, 5<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> R. Moore, "21st Century Law to Meet the Challenge of 21st
Century
Organized Crime," <i>Technological Forecasting and Social Change,</i> vol. 52, no 2/3 
(1996).<p>
                                  
