<center><font size=+1><i><b>Therapies for Conflict</b></i><p></font></center>

55. <b>Development:</b> Globalisation: increasingly clear demand for global thinking,
responsibility,
ethics, approach, effort, action, and results. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> The global process is a result of a naked power process without
legal
rules and without ethical foundation. I repeat here what I said before: There is a clear demand for
"global
thinking", "global responsibility", "global ethics", "global approach", "global effort", "global
action" and
"global results". And should be added "global institutions, global implementation of global
solutions to
global problems" Three main areas should be considered : a) the global process as it is, as it
appears on its
reality. This is a matter of a diagnostic and futures research; b) the cyberspace and Internet  and
all
networks of networks to come as the infostructure of the new global order. This is a mater of
socialware
and interdisciplinary approach of social sciences combined with digital technologies of
information,
communication, decisions and organization; and c)  the Global Common Good as the
philosophical
foundation of global law, global institutions, global ethic and global culture.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> To consider the global process from a global point of view: not only the advance
of
industrialized countries over the developing countries, but also as the possibilities of developing
countries
to act in the world arena. To achieve a balance of activities from global to regional and local as
well as
from local to regional and global..<br>
<b>Domain:</b> all.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> John Naisbitt: "Global Paradox : The Bigger the World Economy,
the
More  Powerful Its Smallest Players".  William Morrow. N.Y. 1994. There is an impressive
bibliography
about the United Nations change from an "International Institution" to a "Global" one. See the
very
important references about the Global process in the Future Annual Survey, edited by Michael
Marien,
World Future Society, Bethesda, Maryland., since 1990 to 1996.   <p>
                                  
