<center><font size=+1><i><b>Governance</b></i><p></font></center>

2.  <b>Summary:</b> The global Islamic community beginning to adopt futures thinking in
establishing
its plans and goals.<br>
<b>Development:</b> Discussions about use of futures research in development of Islamic
thought re
futures. At a high level conference in March 1996, at Kuala Lumpur, speakers argued that new
simulation
models were necessary using Islamic renderings of concepts of population, ecology, social justice
and
unity and non-linear approaches to understanding the future. To begin this task it was first
necessary for
the Ummah, the Islamic community, to rescue itself from limited nationalistic/dynastic discourses
and
from Western language frames.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Convergence of Western and Islamic views or the future and
development of a new basis for discourse.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> To foster this development.<br>
<b>References:</b> Report of conference by Dr. Sohail Inayatullah, The Communication Centre,
Queensland University of Technology, Box 2434, Brisbane 4001, s.inayatullah@qut.edu.au<p>
                                  
12. <b>Summary:</b> Increasing complexity of issues that lead to conflict, outstripping ability of
institutions to anticipate and deal with the issues.<br>
<b>Development:</b>  The complexity of conflict, and of potential conflict issues, is growing
faster
than the ability of people to comprehend and explore effectively.  Concurrent availability of
educated,
retired individuals willing to contribute their professional skills. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b>  Increasing difficulty in identifying emerging conflicts and in
approaching them competently.  Lack of societal resources being devoted to the problem is likely
to
compound the problem by preventing the development of structures that can anticipate conflicts
at all
levels of societies and in the international community, and address them rapidly and efficiently. 
Waste of
valuable human resources.<br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b> Volunteers in monitoring systems, and as mediators, to identify and
intervene in
emerging conflicts at the local, national and/or regional level, within a coordinated structure that
provides
logistic, training and continuity support.<br>
<b>Domain:</b>  4 <br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
                                 <p>
                                  
13. <b>Summary:</b> Failure of education system to develop leadership skills <br>
<b>Development:</b> Fewer and fewer resources are being devoted to management /leadership
competence development (as distinct from the functional/job-specific skills, like accounting, health
care,
research, MIS, etc.), just when these competencies are becoming increasingly critical in solving
the
mounting stress and other people problems in organizations.  In the private sector and even in the
public
arena, replacement needs of retiring workers will probably maintain a fairly high level of
employment, at
least for some time.  Still, the personal stresses associated with reduced security in the face of the
need to
avoid technological obsolescence, will require ever higher leadership skills from middle and lower
level
managers. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b>  Increasing social and workplace strife; growing disenchantment
by
people who have worked and cannot find new employment, because they were not coached and
counseled in basic work competencies at their previous positions; more individuals without
adequate
education out on the street; more waste of human and material resources, etc.<br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b>High level competence at the middle and lower management levels with
strong
skills in all areas connected with setting appropriate, challenging and realistic goals, achieving a
highly
motivational climate with strong positive discipline, avoidance of conflict, continuous
improvement of
competencies and quality, etc. <br>
<b>Domain:</b>  4 and 5 <br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
                                 <p>
                                  
67. <b>Development:</b> Increasing failure of governance in 1st world countries due to inability
to
manage complex systems in a global village -- widening gap between rate of technological change
and
societal/institutional change.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Growing popular discontent offers a ready opening for
demagogues
and fundamentalists, possibly even an anti-technology movement as technology is blamed for job
insecurity, certainly pressures for populist dictatorships (left and right).<br>
<b>Goals:</b> Reduce the widening gap between tech and societal/institutional change by
promoting
fluidity and experimentation to develop new institutional concepts.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 3-4<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>H. Linstone, "Tech Slowdown or Societal Speedup: The Price of
System Complexity," <i>Technological Forecasting and Social Change,</i> vol. 51 (1996) pp.
195-205.;
D. Kash and R. Rycroft, "Synthetic Technology- Analytic Governance," <i>Technological
Forecasting
and Social Change,</i> vol. 53( 1996), no. 3; S. A. Rosell, <i>Governing in an Information
Society.</i><p>
                                  
68. <b>Development:</b> Information/communication technologies increasing the ability to
simultaneously decentralize/localize/fragment and to centralize/globalize/integrate.<br>
<b>Potential Consequence:</b> Decline of the role of the nation state and the rise of sub national
(e.g.
local) and super-national (e.g. global) power, decentralization and globalization of corporations;
localization and globalization of media (e-mail and CNN).<br>
<b>Goals:</b> Restructure and rethink governance to achieve a good balance between local-
national-
global aspects of management and control ( e.g. coordination- intensive structures).<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 3,4, 7 (private sector business).<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> H. Linstone and I. Mitroff, "The Challenge of the 21st Century,:
SUNY
Press 1994; H. Linstone, "Mediacracy, Mediocracy, or New Democracy?" Technological
Forecasting and
Social Change, vol. 36 (1989), pp. 153- 169.           <p>
                                  
72. <b>Development:</b> A pre-occupation with  power at all levels of society (and in our
education
system).<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Although power driven individuals might appear successful in
the
short term those behavior patterns inevitably lead to destruction (usually through the abuse of
power/corruption) in the longer term.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> To encourage everyone (particularly those with 'power) to take a more
responsibility-
driven approach to decision-making.<br>
<b>References: </b><i>Trust: The Social Virtues and the Creation of Prosperity</i>. Fukuyama,
F.
Hamish Hamilton (1995).                      <p>
                                  
124. <b>Development:</b> Ineffectiveness of political and economic institutions, above all on
supranational level.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> Growing tensions between states, growing nationalism; ethnic
groups
or nations within existing states can fight for establishing new, sovereign states; growing
difficulties to
deal with global problems which cannot be solved at a national level (environmental problems,
refugees,
etc.)<br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b>To decentralize certain powers (the principle of subsidiaity -- let
everything be
decided at the lowest level at which it is possible), to centralize other powers in the hands viable
and
effective supranational institutions (how big a challenge is clear from observing the present
functioning of
the UNO and the negotiations concerning the principles of the functioning of the European Union,
etc.)<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 4<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> The Commission on Global Governance (1995); <i>Our Global
Neighborhood.</i> Oxford University Press, Oxford.    <p><hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Economic Systems</b></i><p></font></center>

65. <b>Development:</b>  Capitalism stands essentially unchallenged as the dominant economic
system
throughout the world.  During the 20th century, a number of alternative approaches to organizing
economic activity have failed to establish credibility.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b>  Average living standards may rise as rates of growth associated
with
capitalism become the norm worldwide.  Political freedom may spread along with free markets. 
But, the
challenge to existing political and cultural values may lead to societal breakdown, reaction and
violence. 
The unchecked political-economic power of global corporations may become increasingly
problematic, as
their values do not necessarily reflect the interests of people in general.  Popular alternative
ideologies
may gain in strength, and may well lead in non-democratic directions.<br>
<b>Potential Goals:</b>  Develop economically sophisticated theory and democratic institutions
that
can appropriately "control "global capitalism, prevent excesses, and protect people's rights to
make their 
own cultural and political choices.  Ideally, do this with minimum negative impact on economic
growth.<br>
<b>Domains:</b> 1,2,3,4,5,6<br>
<b>Ref.:</b> Combined news media reports on business, labor, culture, society and  politics.  I
have not
seen any books or studies that frame the issue in this way, though they may exist.<p>
                                  
121. <b>Development:</b> Europe turns into a major world player, rejuvenates and creates a
new
identity of the occident.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> The US is invited to join. Other world players are US (including
NAFTA), India, China, South East Asia under Japanese supremacy, and some conglomerate of
the
Islamic world. Europe stays defensive, predominantly anti-military, anti-imperialistic and
anti-invasive.<br>
                    <b>References and Notes:</b>
                                 <p>
                                  
126. <b>Development:</b> The uneven and unfair distribution of wealth among nations
(North/South
divide) and also within nations (rate of incomes between the 20% of the population with the
lowest
incomes is in Columbia, e.g., roughly 25:1; in western European countries it is about 8:1).<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> The developed world can be faced with the threat that it will
become
a "ghetto of the rich" surrounded by overpopulated, poor, frustrated and aggressive "rest of
mankind."
Even inside the developed countries, ethnic tensions will increase not only as a result of a wave of
immigration from poorer and unstable regions but also because of unbalanced population growth
among
single ethnic groups.<br>
<b>Potential Goals:</b> Creation of limited "global governance" by establishing effective and
viable
supranational institutions (reformed UNO...) and implementation of the "Global Marshall
Plan."<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 1, 2, 4, 6<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> Gore, A. (1992) <i>Earth in Balance: Ecology and the Human
Spirit.</i> Houghton Mifflin and Co. Boston; The Commission on Global Governance (1995)
<i>Our
Global Neighborhood.</i> Oxford University Press, Oxford.    <p>
130. <b>Development:</b> The increasing deterioration of the international monetary system,
based
mainly on US dollars.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences:</b> International monetary instabilities and crises<br>
<b>Goals:</b> A workable international monetary system.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>
<p><hr>
<p>
Thank your very much for completing the second section of Round 2 of the Millennium Project's
1996 Global Look-Out questionnaire.  Return via Email to <i>jglenn@igc.org</i>  or fax to the
USA at 202-686-5179 or airmail to AC/UNU/ Millennium Project, 4421 Garrison Street, NW,
Washington, D.C. 20016-4055 USA. The results will be sent back to you as Part of Round 3.<p>

