<title>Look-Out Panel, Round 2 Questionnaire, Section 2, Domain 5</title>
<body bgcolor="#96E1FA">
<hr><p>
<center><font size=+3>1996 GLOBAL LOOK-OUT PANEL</font>
<p><hr><p>
<font size=+2>ROUND 2 QUESTIONNAIRE<p><b>SECTION 2</b></font><p>
<font size=+1>FULL-TEXT OF DEVELOPMENTS</font></center><p>
<br>
The second round of the 1996 Global Look-Out questionnaire comes in two sections.  You
should already have Section 1. Section 2 includes the full text of developments in only one of the
six Millennium Project domains.  Selection of the domain sent to you was based on your first
round responses, resume, publications, previous expressions of interest and or our best judgment. 
If you want to comment and add to the full text of developments in other domains, please
download them from the Millennium Project's home page:
<i>http//nko.mhpcc.edu/millennium/Millennium_Project.html</i> or request them from the
Project's coordinating office.<p>

In this second section, you are asked for comments, improvements, or additions to the material
submitted by yourself and others in the first round.  You do not have to comment on every
development in this domain, just those developments that are important to you and to which
you can contribute new consquences, strategies, and references. <p>

You can respond in several ways:<p>

1. If you received the material via email or downloaded it from the homepage, you can simply
insert you YOUR COMMENTS IN CAPITAL LETTERS or in
>some other way to identify your additions into the text and submit the whole domain back via
email >to<i> jglenn@igc.org.</i><p>

2.  You need not include the full text in your response.  You can simply write the reference
number for the development followed by your additions and email, fax, or mail it back.<p>

<hr>
<center><font size=+2><i><b>Domain 5: International Economics and
Wealth</b></i><br></font></center>
<hr><p>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>Rich, Poor, and Other Gaps</b></i><p></font></center>

9. <b>Summary:</b> Increasingly apparent conflicts between economic and societal aims:
economic
measurement and incentives subvert social growth.<br>
<b>Development:</b>  The past few decades in particular have demonstrated that the ease with
which
economic goals can be quantified has caused societal aims, based mainly upon non-quantifiable
human
values, to either  become converted into economic commodities or to become neglected entirely. 
In
essence, all the ills of present inequities, topics and issues which place our future at risk and
pervert
individuals and entire governments at present can be traced to this conversion and the neglect of
those
characteristics which imply civility within a civilization. <br>
     Most of the basic tenets of free market economic are so closely matched to the natural and
inherent properties and aspirations in man that constraining the excesses of free market economics
is
widely assumed to undermine fundamental human freedoms, risk the survival of governments,
organizations and people and must therefore be accepted as an undesirable but necessary penalty
for
exercising free choice, as a prerequisite to survival.<br>
     Those familiar with system theory know that natural systems, and this includes societies,
ecosystems and others, reach stability through complexity of the interactions and
interdependencies of its 
subsystems.  Free market economic behavior more so than economic theory tends to strive for
simplicity
which undermines systems stability.  The rising tide of discontent within societies indicates that
societal
systems have already become less stable through the process of simplification through economic
quantification and evaluation.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> Economic colonialization is markedly different from traditional
colonialization because there is no single society or group of societies which does the colonizing. 
The
presumed economic colonizers such as the United States, Germany, Japan and others are
themselves
becoming colonized because their societies become perverted by the same economic system which
is
spreading globally with noble aims but sinister in its consequences.<br>  
     Basically, therefore, societies everywhere are being exploited by a virtual colonial power, by a
concept, by practices, by the invisible hand which has become an assertive fist.  Metaphorically 
speaking,
man has allowed, by default, to extend the food chain which is now dominated by a virtual species
which
has relegated man to the role of the foodstuff that maintains its existence, growth, multiplication
and
dominance.<br>
     It has created a new uni-culture which subscribes to economic values over human values, yet it
were human values that allowed mankind to arrive in the present time frame.  The consequences
of  this
transformation of human values into bankable currencies is a root cause which drives all other
topics and
issues with few exceptions.<br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b>Constrain economic practices into compliance with human goals. 
Without
fundamentally altering economic theories which is inherently hazardous and largely unnecessary,
encourage the disciplined development of means for quantifying human goals and for linkages of 
these
goals to economic theories and practices which preserve free market economic concepts but limit
economic excesses.  <br>
<b>Domain:</b>  5, 6<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> <i>Forging A New Economy.</i>  Journal of the Wisconsin
Institute,
1994, 29-38, Eberhard Weber.  The article is also available at: 
<i>http://csf.colorado.edu/ecolecon/authors/Weber.Eberhard/forging</i> or by e-mail to:
<i>glosys-pubs@netcom.com.</i> With the in-body command: send forging Research On Global
Systems
<i>(glosys@valleynet.com).</i>                  <p>
                                  
10. <b>Summary:</b> Growth in the number of aging seniors places burden on younger
generation.<br>
<b>Development:</b>  As benefits of industrial society are realized, the life span increases, birth
rate
decreases and there are increasing numbers of aged seniors, causing ever greater burden on
younger
generation. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> As Ted Roszak writes: "Barring another Black Plague, the
future of
industrial nations is filled with increasing numbers of seniors all of whom will eventually claim the
retirement benefits they have been guaranteed.  Longevity is the new population problem.  Ever
more
dependent seniors filling hospitals, nursing homes, and retirement communities, living out a
second life
that frequently stretches twenty and thirty years beyond retirement. The cost of maintaining a
growing
population is astronomical.   <br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b>To revision aging as a time to realize untapped human potential needed
to care
for and rebuild the  human community.  Find the way to activate meaningful functions for seniors
in
contributing to their communities.  Realize that the issue of life purpose and meaningful work will
become ever more pressing,  as not only for seniors, but also adults will be "downside," under or
unemployed.  As Jeremy Rifkin writes, we are approaching "the end of work" as we have known
it.  This
can be a great opportunity to release creativity for vocation, life purpose and life-long learning. 
We must
develop an economic system that supports people in doing their best.  We need a combination of
Louis
Kelso's Two Factor Theory of Universal Capitalism, whereby workers and even those on welfare
borrow
on the future earnings of stocks and become owners of the increased productivity of the machines. 
We
also need to develop local community-based currencies outside the commercial monetary system,
and
perhaps some sort of guaranteed annual income as proposed by Robert Theobald and others. 
<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 1 <br>
<b>References:</b> <i>The Grey Peril:  Reflections on the Ecology of Aging and the Ultimate;
</i><i>
Limits to Growth</i> by Theodore Roszak  (unpublished, available from author); Jeremy Rifkin:
<i>The
End of Work.</i>  Louis O. Kelso and Patricia Hetterer: <i>The Two Factor Theory -- The
Economics
of Reality.</i> (Random House, N.Y. 1967)             <p>
53. <b>Summary:</b> The inability of developing countries to use developed technology.<br>
<b>Development:</b> The USTeD syndrome: (In Spanish <i>el Uso Subdesarrollado de las
Tecnologias Desarrolladas</i>) The Underdeveloped Use of Developed Technologies. This
syndrome  is
the result of a complex relation between Advanced Technologies and Social Systems whereby the
power
of technology is limited by the ignorance of the user.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>The expansion of digital technologies does not mean effective
use of
these technologies in the developing world. Therefore, developing countries are attractive markets
as
"consumers" of digital technologies---PC's and accessories-- without the benefit of the correct use
of
information, communication, decision and organization technologies. Hence, advanced
technologies are
really making the rich richer and the poor poorer. <br>
<b>Goals:</b> Reverse the tendency denounced by the USTeD syndrome through extended
programs
in education and special training emphasizing the human factor in information/ communication
systems.
Apply information/communication technologies in developing  countries in such way that improve
productivity in small low level popular communities.  Digital or electronic communities should
flourished
in China, India, Indonesia, Brazil, Mexico, Argentina, and, in general in Africa, Asia and Latin
America.
<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 1, 3, 5, and 6. <br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> "Socialware: Advanced Technologies of Information,
Communications
and Decisions in Post-Industrial Societies and Developing Countries". Horacio H. Godoy,
INFODEC
Consultores Asociados, in <i>The World Community in Post-Industrial Society, vol. 2:
Continuity and
Change in Communications in Post-Industrial Society,</i> 1989, pp.120/154; David Horten and
Rudi
Klauss (editors), <i>People Centered Development Contributions toward Theory and Planning
Frameworks.</i> West Hartford, Connecticut, Kumarian Press, 1986.<p>
                                  
57. <b>Development:</b> Improving the economic status of many "developing" countries, thus
increasing global demand for food, energy and manufactured products.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Consumer demands in "developing" countries will  have more
influence
on world markets and economies. In heavily populated countries like China, a very small increase
in
affluence and consumer demand will have significant implications for the global economy and the
environment. <br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b>Encourage environmentally-sustainable development in these growing
economies. Educate consumers globally about the social and environmental implications of their
demands
and choices. Expand education programs related to reproduction options and population
control.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 5<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> In Vital Signs 1994,  Lester Brown et al. from the Worldwatch
Institute
note double digit growth of the Chinese economy in 1992 and 1993. Other statistics and analyses
are
likely readily available.                    <p>
                                  
74. <b>Development:</b>  The widening economic gap between the 'haves' and 'have nots' within
and
between countries.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Increased instability and conflict; both by groups and
individually. <br>
<b>Goals:</b> More policies that focus directly on this area--or in a decade or two all we will be
doing
will be attempting to deal with the damaging consequences of neglect.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>
<p>

85. <b>Development:</b> High population growth and high educational achievement of many
developing nations produces more highly educated citizens than their economies can productively
employ<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> Rich source of talent for economies with flat or negative
population
growth rates (developed nations).  Also rich source for developed-world organizations seeking to
develop a presence in the developing world.   Disgruntlement of populace forced to settle for
underemployment. Educated women may question long-held cultural norms/practices (for
example,
birthrates).  Disgruntlement with government that cannot create enough jobs. <br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b> Education drives entrepreneurial economic expansion on an
unprecedented
scale.  Governments foster  it by making capital available for small-business start-up.<br>
<b>Domain:</b>  1<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> 
<p><hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Work</b></i><p></font></center> 

29. <b>Development:</b> Interactive information technology (IT) systems become widely used
in
work, education, and other social functions.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Increase in social mobility, economic efficiency,
entrepreneurship,
isolation, complexity, risk of system failures, etc.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> Develop effective IT systems to serve these purposes, as well as protocols that
avoid
social disruption.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 3<br>
<b>References:</b> W. Halal, "Forecasting the Information Revolution," <i>Technological
Forecasting
& Social Change </i>(1993).
<p>

35. <b>Development:</b>  Increase in the impact of new technologies, especially in the service
sector.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Growth of unemployment in service sector and need to devise
social 
security systems which are very difficult given the current world economic situation.<br>
<b>Goals:</b>  Invest in information,  updating of professional employees, and increase
knowledge of
the new technologies emerging  that might influence employment in the service sector.<br>
<b>Domain:</b>  1<br>
<b>References:</b> Jacques Delors "Growth, Competitively, Employment"
ECSC-EC-EUROTOM,
Brussels, 1994                          <p>
                                  
137. <b>Summary:</b> Changing composition of the workforce; shift in labor from industrial to
service
sector<br>
<b>Development:</b> Workplace opportunities in traditional "production" occupations has fallen
below
30% of the workforce, whereas the "management and administrative" opportunities now approach
40%
of the workforce. Furthermore,"technical and professional" occupations which now represent
20% of the
workforce, far exceed the "service" category. These relentless trends make obsolete our
traditional
approaches to training and educating new workers as well as the approaches to retraining and
educating
the existing workforce.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>The human capital implications of these trends has created an
acrimonious political debate as the economy is restructured by technological and social forces
now
exerting their powerful influence. Populations are frightened for their economic security; society
could be
polarized more strongly between those with and without employable skills; conspiracies,
constructed and
amplified to "explain" to those who do not benefit could lead to social unrest and disruptions;
terrorist an
luddite responses could result.<br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b>To respond to these rapid socioeconomic changes, recognize the
fundamental
changes required in the educational, training, and vocational systems as well as reconfigure the
nature of
work and of knowledge workers as the information economy developes. Exploit new knowledge
and
implications of cognitive science for designing learning environments. Exploit the emerging
information
technologies as enablers in achieving educational/training goals.<br>
<b>Domains:</b> 1, 2, 3, and 5.   <br>
<b>References:</b> "The Workforec of U.S. Manufacturing in the Post-Industrial Era" by Dennis
Swyt,
<i>Techological Forecasting and Social Change,</i> Vol 34, pp231-251 (1988). "The Double
Helix of
Education and the Economy" by Sue E. Berryman and Thomas R. Bailey, Institute on Education
and the
Economy, Teachers College/Columbia University ISBN 1-882217-00-4 (1992). "Will We Be
Smart
Enough: A Cognative Analysis of the Coming Workforce", by Earl Hunt, Russel Sage
Foundation, NY
ISBN 0-87154-392-3.
<p><hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Organization</b></i><p></font></center>

28. <b>Development:</b> Decentralization of institutions; big corporations are breaking up into
small,
self-supporting units, big government welfare state policies are being dismantled.<br>
<b>Consequences: </b>People will become dependent on themselves for financial and social
support,
producing a rise in poverty, crime, political disruption.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> Define a workable model of self-governance for semi-autonomous business units,
local
communities, and other social structures.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 4, 5<br>
<b>References:</b> W. Halal, <i>The New Management: Democracy and Enterprise and
Transforming
Organizations</i> (Berrett-Koehler, 1996)            <p>
                                  
69. <b>Development:</b> The human tendency to discount distant space and time (i.e., focus on
the
"here and now") is increasingly dangerous in an age when information/communications
technologies are
shrinking space and time (the global village).<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>The need to expand our space-time horizons.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> Rebalance the attention paid to the near and the far in space and time; use "virtual
reality" and other concepts to assists in correcting the imbalance.<br>
<b>Domains:</b> 2, 3, 5, 6<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> H. Linstone and I Mitroff, <i>The Challenge of the 21st
Century,</i>
SUNY Press 1994; R. U. Ayres and R. Axtell, "Foresight as a Survival Tactic," <i>Technological
Forecasting and Social Change,</i> vol. 51 (1996) pp.  209-236. <p><hr><p>
                                  
<center><font size=+1><i><b>International Economics</b></i><p></font></center>


75. <b>Development:</b> Natural resources are being bought up by international cartels, with
unprecedented speed and scale, as much as 60% of gold, 30% of silver, and 80% of platinum.
Besides
these strategic metals, grains and even water are being targeted. In a decade, 70% of the natural
resources in the world will be controlled by private financial powers.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>World politics and business will be influenced by these cartels.
Manufacturing sites as well as government planning will be at the mercy of these power-hungry
cartels.
As a result, tension will be increased over limited natural resources. <br>
<b>Goals:</b> Establish a monitoring mechanism of these destructive activities of cartels and
provide an
early warning signal for nation states to conduct their smooth production of goods enacting an
international code of resource protection.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 5<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> 
                                 <p>
                                  
76. <b>Summary:</b> Family business increasing its presence, power and influence over many
aspects
of politics, economics and culture.<br>
<b>Development:</b> Multi-generational family enterprises are exerting a predominant power in
each
field without proper market competition or public scrutiny. More than 1/3 of Fortune 500 and
85% of all
companies are family controlled.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>A small number of political and business families will control the
government and private institutions. Their concern will be their own family succession and
protection of
their wealth, not public welfare nor general well being in each country. Such accumulation of
wealth and
power will inevitably invite a revolt from the suppressed public and bring about a social unrest on
a global
scale.<br>
<b>Goals:</b> Increase awareness of the danger associated with these monopolies by political
and
economic families among the media and public. More governments enact an anti-monopoly law
on the
international scale and standard.<br>
<b>Domain:</b> 4<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b> 
                                 <p>
                                  
88. <b>Development:</b> Environmentally-adverse forms of energy perpetuated in part because
of
economic distortions and incomplete accounting for costs.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> The world continues to use fossil fuels as its dominant energy
source
to a greater extent, vis a vis renewable sources, than is warranted because, for various historic and
political reasons, such forms are protected and subsidized, prices are kept low, encouraging
waste, and
the situation is exacerbated by lack of agreement on an appropriate methodology to achieve
full-cost
accounting for external and environmental effects and impacts.<br>
<b>Goal:</b> Achieve a better balance of energy sources by implementing full-cost accounting
for
external and environmental effects and impacts.<br>
<b>Domain(s):</b>  2, 4, 5<br>
<b>References:</b> Ottinger, Richard L., et al, <i>Environmental Costs of Electricity,</i>
Oceana
Publications, Inc., New York, 1991. Erb, R. Bryan, "Power From Space - Can it Compete?", 45th
Congress of the International Astronautical Federation, Paper IAF-94.R2.372, Jerusalem, Israel,
October
9 - 14, 1994.; World Energy Council, Round Up, 16th WEC Congress, Tokyo, Japan, 1995.<p>
                                  
91. <b>Development:</b> Tele-national citizens (Third World people who live and work in First
World
but help develop their countries via tele-commuting)<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>
<p>
<hr><p>
Thank your very much for completing the second section of Round 2 of the Millennium Project's
1996 Global Look-Out questionnaire.  Return via Email to <i>jglenn@igc.org</i>  or fax to the
USA at 202-686-5179 or airmail to AC/UNU/ Millennium Project, 4421 Garrison Street, NW,
Washington, D.C. 20016-4055 USA. The results will be sent back to you as Part of Round 3.<p>

