<html>
<title>Look-Out Panel, Round 2 Questionnaire, Section 2, Domain 2</title>
<body bgcolor="#96E1FA">
<hr><p>
<center><font size=+3>1996 GLOBAL LOOK-OUT PANEL</font>
<p><hr><p>
<font size=+2>ROUND 2 QUESTIONNAIRE<p><b>SECTION 2</b></font><p>
<font size=+1>FULL-TEXT OF DEVELOPMENTS</font></center><p>
<br>
The second round of the 1996 Global Look-Out questionnaire comes in two sections.  You
should already have Section 1. Section 2 includes the full text of developments in only one of the
six Millennium Project domains.  Selection of the domain sent to you was based on your first
round responses, resume, publications, previous expressions of interest and or our best judgment. 
If you want to comment and add to the full text of developments in other domains, please
download them from the Millennium Project's home page:
<i>http//nko.mhpcc.edu/millennium/Millennium_Project.html</i> or request them from the
Project's coordinating office.<p>

In this second section, you are asked for comments, improvements, or additions to the material
submitted by yourself and others in the first round.  You do not have to comment on every
development in this domain, just those developments that are important to you and to which
you can contribute new consquences, strategies, and references. <p>

You can respond in several ways:<p>

1. If you received the material via email or downloaded it from the homepage, you can simply
insert you YOUR COMMENTS IN CAPITAL LETTERS or in
>some other way to identify your additions into the text and submit the whole domain back via
email >to<i> jglenn@igc.org.</i><p>

2.  You need not include the full text in your response.  You can simply write the reference
number for the development followed by your additions and email, fax, or mail it back.<p>

<hr>
<center><font size=+2><i><b>Domain 2: Environmental Change and
Biodiversity</b></i><br></font></center>
<hr><p>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>Pollution</b></i><p></font></center>

4. <b>Development: </b>Development of affordable cars that produce 1/3 the amount of CO2,
are
otherwise pollution free and do not require petroleum. <br>
<b>Description:</b> We are very close, technologically, to being able to mass produce affordable
cars
which don't need to use oil, and are virtually pollution free (if you don't count CO2, which is only
reduced
by a factor of three...). But the engineering and deployment challenges are considerable.<br>
<b>Details:</b> Maybe this is generally known; maybe not. The White House has hosted several
meetings and press conferences, anyway, on the "Partnership for a Next Generation Vehicle"
(PNGV),
for which most of the government money goes into fuel-cell electric cars, which have the
attributes listed
above.<br>
<b>Strategies:</b> A big issue. Clearly, there is a need for both government and industry activity
-- but
the right mix seems to be an issue that gets revisited every two months or so. One strategy is to
push
FOR THE TIME BEING for new fuel processors which make it possible to use natural gas or
diesel fuel
or home heating oil (!) in the short-term, in these kinds of cars, to get them out onto the market;
then,
this opens the door for new fuels like methanol and hydrogen. Many of us believe that hydrogen is
less
practical than claimed, but that methanol can be made in the long-term in a sustainable way that
does not
even produce net carbon dioxide. Even in the short-term, co-production of methanol and
electricity will
permit low methanol prices, enough to displace oil sooner than many believe. This is another area
where
international cooperation could be extremely valuable, for a number of reasons, if the US
technology
holders can be reassured that their rights will be protected even as they provide a product that
other
countries badly need and can help produce.<br>
<b>References: </b>A little is discussed in P. Werbos in L. Grant, ed., <i>Elephants in the
Volkswagen.</i>  W. H. Freeman  (paper on energy and population; volume on population
issues.). 
More recently, there are program reports from the DOE Fuel Cell Automobile program,
obtainable from
the office of Pandit Patil at DOE. There are also the PNGV annual reports from the PNGV office
at the
Department of Commerce. (202-482-6268.) There is also Topic 26 of the NSF SBIR solicitation,
and the
material it cites.                        <p>
                                  
27. <b>Development: </b>Doubling of the demand for energy in less than 30 years as a result of
population and economic growth.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> A new shortage of oil could occur before 2020. Greenhouse
gas
emissions could rise to intolerable levels.  Nuclear energy will not be able to close the gaps.<br>
<b>Goals: </b> A quadrupling within 30-50 years of energy productivity, i.e. the output in energy
services per primary energy input.  This appears to be technically feasible according to a new
book,
<i>Factor Four - Doubling Wealth, Halving Resource Use</i>.  This amounts to nothing less than
redirecting technological progress from pure labor productivity towards labor and resource
productivity. 
I assume it should be profitable in macroeconomics terms.<br>
<b>Domain: </b> 6<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b> Ernst Ulrich von Weizsacker, Amory Lovins, Hunter Lovins:
"Factor
Four - Doubling Wealth, Halving Resource Use".  The new Report to the Club of Rome, due for
publication autumn 1996 by Earthscan, London.  German version was published in 1995, ISBN
3-426-26877-9.  Spanish, Korean and Czech editions are underway.<p>
                                  
30. <b>Development: </b> Industrialization of China, India, etc., increasing load on the
environment by
a factor of 5-10.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Catastrophic increase in pollution, human mortality, extinction
of
species.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Develop manufacturing systems that are ecologically safe.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>2<br>
<b>References: </b>Schmidheiny                  <p>
                                  
135. <b>Development: </b>China is becoming an economic world power. While this is not
imminent, it
is likely to occur within the first few decades of the new century.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>All major industrialized countries will be affected, possibly
leading to
intense trade wars or even military action.<br>
<b>Goal: </b>Seek to induce China in a timely fashion to participate in firm international trade
pacts
while conforming to internationally acceptable human rights standards. To achieve this it may well
be
necessary to create a Union of Democracies, aside from and parallel to the United Nations, that
through
united actions forces recalcitrant nations such as present day China to abide by set standards of
international commerce.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
                                 <p>
83. <b>Development: </b>Gridlock: Excessive urban motor vehicle traffic congestion,  resulting
pollution, and political backlash.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> Significant economic impact due to gridlock. Carless urban
corridors. 
Active promotion of non-polluting alternatives. Purchase price or tax on vehicles being linked to
resource
consumption. Community planning for pedestrian, human powered transport.  Use of  IT to
decrease
need to travel (e-cash doesn't require trip to bank/ATM), suburb ban works sites or
telecommuting
reduces need to travel to urban core).          <br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b> Create vehicles which actually clean the atmosphere (exhaust of vehicle
is
cleaner than the air coming into it). Cooperative/public travel arrangements and/or long-range
community
planning to minimize congestion. Double-decker freeways (outside earthquake areas!). Human
powered
modes of transport with infrastructure (roads, lockers, etc.) to support it, make it safe).<br>
<b>Domain: </b>2,4<br>
<b>References: </b>Recent <i>Scientific American</i> (march or April 1996) article on city in
Brazil
and their transportation policy. California vehicle laws, policies in several European cities
restricting
motor vehicle use.                                         <p>
                                  
109. <b>Development: </b>Increasing appearance of estrogen mimicking compounds in the
environment resulting from the breakdown of plastics, insecticides, and other manufactured
materials. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>  Potentially diminished fertility and reproductive capacity of
males of
all species, including human males, disappearance of some species, backlash against chemical and
industrial industries, rise in organic agriculture, pressure for cloning research, sperm banks more
popular.<br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b>Coordinated research and funding by producers of these compounds to
produce
substitution compounds that do not affect reproduction, and production of a simple
self-administered
diagnostic test to determine current status of these compounds' existence in the body, current
effect on
the subject's body, treatment options.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>2<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b> "Our Stolen Future: How We Are Threatening Our Fertility,
Intelligence
& Survival - A scientific Detective Story" by T. Colbourn, D. Dumanoski, and J.P. Myers,
1996.<br>
<b>Comment from Round 1 (Godoy): </b>The increasing appearance of estrogen mimicking
compounds in the environment resulting from the breakdown of plastics, insecticides, and other
manufactured materials is one specific aspect of the universe of environmental problems suffering
humankind. While environment problems do not recognize political boundaries, political systems
does. It
should be accepted by all governments that unless a dip change happened at the political level,
there will
not be a solution to any of the most dangerous environmental problems. It is perhaps "the" most
clear
demand for "global thinking", "global responsibility", "global ethics", "global approach", "global
effort",
"global action" and "global results".              <p>
                                  
112. <b>Development: </b>Environmental issues on the horizon include: chlorine,
electromagnetic
fields, life cycle assessment, ultraviolet exposure, environmental hormones, and biological
contamination
standards for drinking water.<br>
<b>Reference: </b>Report 1546-1-45; 1994 Environmental Trends Update<p>
                                  
116. <b>Development: </b>Deterioration of the physical environment.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Illness, conflict, starvation, death.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Improve the quality of the environment, making governments and people more
responsible for the legacy we leave to our children NOW.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>Health<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>All the documents of the UNCED conference, for example.<p>

<hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Biodiversity</b></i><p></font></center>

8. <b>Summary: </b>Increasing number of micro-organisms that are immune to pharmaceuticals
or
pesticides.<br>
<b>Development: </b>In medicine as well as in agriculture, an increasing number of
micro-organisms
and insects have become immune to intervention by pharmaceutical means or pesticides.  In
addition to
natural agents which are hostile to human interests, man has created the paradox of increasing the
potency of this hostility through ill-managed innovations originally conceived to overcome it.
     In medicine - A net increase in the vulnerability of humans to diseases for which cures are
becoming more difficult, more costly and perhaps unable to obtain.  While diseases such as HIV
do not
spread through casual exposure, other air and water-born diseases can be spread readily and pose
a
perhaps more menacing threat than HIV, Ebola and others which receive more attention. 
Resistant
strains have the potential to more rapidly and more quickly affect a far larger number of people
and with
far more devastating consequences than any other presently known threat.
     In agriculture - Increasing the potency of herbicides and insecticides increases the potential for
significant and perhaps more stealth health risks for humans, not only through the food grown but
also
through drinking water and aquatic life polluted by runoff from chemically treated fields.<br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b> 
A  Medicine
a  Impose severe disciplinary measures on physicians who  prescribe antibiotics indiscriminately
b    Provide a combinations of incentives and disincentives  for pharmaceutical companies to
produce still
effective antibiotics for which patents have expired.  Since these antibiotics reduce the profitability
of
their production in favor of more exotic proprietary pharmaceuticals, new approaches are called
for to
facilitate their production and use.
c    Provide for more controlled environments and/or conditions  to assure that patients who take
antibiotics take them beyond the point where symptoms subside.  Early termination of a
prescribed rigor
for taking certain medications encourages the survival of the most resistant micro-organisms
which
fosters the emergence of new resistant strains on a grander scale.
B    Agriculture
a  Provide incentives to dramatically increase the number of cultivators of insects (for example)
that are
natural enemies of organisms which are now being fought with chemicals.  Examples are ladybugs
feeding
on aphids. Provide dis-incentives for the use of chemicals which can be eliminated in cases where
cultivated natural organisms can be successfully employed.<br>
<b>Domain: </b> 1, 2<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>  Multiple media          <p>
                                  
49. <b>Development: </b>Essentially full control of the genetic and biochemical processes of
living
organisms.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Eradication of existing communicable and non-communicable
diseases;
limitation of these achievements to the rich areas of the world; increase of differences between
areas
ending in a global destructive conflict.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Equitable and ethically justified development and implementation of progress in
biology
and medicine.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>3, 4, 5<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>                   <p>
                                  
50. <b>Summary: </b>Adoption of an effects-oriented approach to the monitoring of ecological
systems, rather than measuring contaminents or physical-chemical properties.<br>
<b>Development: </b> Monitoring the condition of ecological systems for assessment and
decisionmaking.  Rather than separately measuring contaminants only, or physico-chemical
properties
only, of the environmental media (a practice typical of compliance monitoring), an effects oriented
approach is adopted (similar to the practices of medical diagnosis and epidemiology). Various
indicators
of the condition of ecological resources disclose status of as well as trends and changes in
condition.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Such approaches hold the promise for the conduct of more
proactive
(rather than reactive) environmental protection and management activities.  <br>
<b>Goals: </b>While the scientific community has long called for support of such approaches
(and the
public has indicated interest in having simple metrics for discerning the condition of ecological
systems,
the approaches have not garnered, as yet, high-level governmental support due to the necessarily
long-term nature of investment needed for generating the data for programs operating under such
approaches.<br>
<b>Domain(s):</b> 2, 4.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>Messer, J. J., R. A. Linthurst, and W. S. Overton. 1991. "An EPA
program for monitoring ecological status and trends." <i>Environmental Monitoring and
Assessment</i> 
17 (1):67-78. ; Messer, J. J. 1992.  Indicators in regional ecological monitoring and risk
assessment.  In:
<i>Ecological Indicators</i>, Vol. 1, D. H.  McKenzie, D. E. Hyatt, and V. J. McDonald, eds. p.
135-46. 
(EPA/600/9-91/039, PB92-114131). New York, NY: Elsevier Applied Science.; Lear, J.S., and
C.B.
Chapman, eds. 1994. <i>Environmental Monitoring and Assessment Program  (EMAP)
Cumulative
Bibliography.</i> EPA/620/R-94/XXX. Research Triangle Park, NC: U.S. Environmental
Protection
Agency, Office of Research and Development, Environmental Monitoring and Assessment
Program,
EMAP Center.                           <p>
                                  
60. <b>Summary: </b>Initiate a search for and catalog the vast variety of bacteria of the planet.
<br>
<b>Development: </b>Uncover new resources, e.g. the flora of this planet has at least a million
different
species of bacteria, of which about are known and (partially) understood.  Considering what little
we do
know, and their usefulness and basically benign character, it seems that a simple, easily available
resource
is going untapped.  A project (similar to the Human Genome mapping project) to identify, study,
and
utilize bacteria could discover new and cheaper foodstuffs.  Also bacteria could have great
importance to
health and welfare of humans, perhaps even for the viability of the World (viz. less pollution from
improved industrial processes).<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>
                                 <p>
                                  
127. <b>Development: </b>Destruction of the environment, especially loss of biodiversity.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Because of the destruction of the environment (depletion of
rainforests,
desertification...) the generic variety of life is threatened -- genetic, generic, ecosystemic --  but
with
people, and also cultural diversity. Euro-American culture is dominant on the planet; Islamic,
Hispanic,
Chinese and some other cultures may try to resist, but tropical forests disappear.<br>
<b>Potential <b>Goals: </b></b>Political priority for international environmental protection and
sustainable development, implementation of Agenda 21 from "Rio 92 Conference". (UN
Conference on
Environment and Development.)<br>
<b>Domain: </b>2. 4.<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b>Barber, B., "World Environment a US Priority," <i>The
Washington
Times,</i> 04.15.96; Documents from the Rio Conference; Novacek, P. Mederly, P. et al. (1996)
<i>Strategy of Sustainable Development for the Czech Republic--Case Study of the County in
Transition</i>. G Plus G Publishing House, Prague (in Czech, mscr. in English).<p>

<hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Sustainability</b></i><p></font></center>

14. <b>Summary: </b>A false sense of security about the extent of natural resources.<br>
<b>Development: </b> The attention to diminishing natural resources which was prominent in the
literature during the 60s and 70s has faded into the background, especially since the early 80s.
There is a
widespread, yet probably inappropriate optimism that either resources are so vast that there is no
need to
address the problem now, or that new discoveries and technology can overcome any problems
that might
arise.  The optimism does not extend to some resources such as water and possibly air, but it does
extend
to almost all metals and fossil fuels.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> Serious disruptions, even crises, and possible international
conflict, as
shortages develop, possibly as far as decades in the future. <br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b>National and international material conservation agreements and
procedures,
with competitive incentives for conservation of natural resources in production and possibly also
in
consumption.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>5, 3 and 2 <br>
<b>References: </b>Landsberg, Fishman and Fisher,  1963. <i>Resources in America's
Future</i>. 
Baltimore, MD: Johns Hopkins Press;  Gerald O. Barney/Council on Environmental Quality, 
1982.
<i>The Global 2000 Report to the President</i>. Penguin Books;  Oxford Analytica, 1986.
<i>America
in Perspective</i>. Boston, MA: Houghton Mifflin.         <p>
                                  
20. <b>Development: </b>Environment and Climate Program (CEC)<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>To support the investigation and further advanced education on
specific
topics at the forefront of scientific and technological development in Europe.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>Sea level change; biogeochemical cycles of nutrients; atmospheric chemistry and
stratospheric ozone' human dimension of environmental change.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>2<br>
<b>References: </b>European Commission, DGXIIID, Environment and Climate Program, Rue
De La
Loi/ Westraat 200, B-1049 Brussels, Belgium. Fax 32-2 296 3024. <p>
                                  
21. <b>Development: </b>Consortia for International Earth Science Information Network
(CEISIN)<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Recognition by many expert bodies and national governments
that an
understanding of human interactions in the environment is indispensable to understanding
environmental
change.<br>
<b>Goals: </b>To develop and deliver information products and services that integrate.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>2<br>
<b>References: </b>Human Dimensions of Global Environmental Change (HDP), International
Social
Sciences Council (ISSC), SEDAC User Services (1) 517 797 2727. ciesin.info@ciesin.org.<p>
                                  
41. <b>Development: </b>Corporate support for sustainable concepts<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>The most immediate result is increased resource efficiency
within
practical economic limits. Reduced pollution.  Shift to a longer term, holistic or systemic
perspective. <br>
<b>Goals: </b>Two primary <b>Goals: </b>1) Support for legislation/international agreements
leading
to support of sustainable development; 2) Responsible sale/transfer of technology to emerging
countries. 
(Avoid events similar to the sale of inefficient refrigerator technology to China.)<br>
<b>Domain: </b>3,4<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b>                   <p>
                                  
86. <b>Development: </b>More than 60 provincial and 22 national Comprehensive Experimental
Community for Sustainable Development (CECSD) have been set up in China since 1992. Much
progress
has been made on the social, economic and environmental development in CECSD.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Fulfill sustainable development catalyzed by science and
technology
involving many aspects as economy, society, population, resources and environment.
Development of
people are the core of and economic development is the central task of CECSD. Environmentally
sound,
economic productive and systematically responsible production, institution, life style, people's
capacity
and ecological order will be encouraged in CECSD.<br>
<b>Potential <b>Goals: </b></b>Through building CECSD to realize a resource saving type of
economic development model, to development human resources and pay great attention to
capacity
building, to meet and satisfy the increasing basic needs of people and improve over all quality of
life, to
create and maintain a clean and healthy environment.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>6<br>
<b>Reference and Notes: </b><i>Wealth, Health and Faith--Sustainability Study in China,</i>
China
Environmental Press, 1995.; Newsletter of China Network for Sustainable Development, No. 2,
1995.<p>
                                  
87. <b>Development: </b>Sustainable Technology Demonstration Project (STDP) is sponsored
by the
State Science and Technology Commission (China) to introducing environmentally sound,
economically
productive and systematically responsible technologies to the demonstration towns and
communities for
community sustainable development. <br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Enhance the role of science and technology in community
development
and introduce the mechanism and develop an instrument for technology transfer. Evaluate, select
and
aggregate systematic technologies for sustainable development. Test several kinds of typical
sustainable
technology for demonstration. Setup scientific and technological information system and
consultation
network for demonstration communities.<br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b>Set up 5 technological systems for community development including (1)
Capacity building and technology consultation, (2) Comprehensive utilization of agricultural
resource, (3)
Deepening processing and regeneration of industrial resource and wastes, (4) Town ecological
construction and restoration, (5) Community service and social welfare.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>6<br>
<b>References and Notes: </b><i>Hotpoints in Contempary Ecology, </i>China Science and
Technology Press, 1995. Newsletter of China Network for Sustainable Development, No. 2,
1995<p>
                                  
142. <b>Development: </b>Increasing pressure under the seabed associated with the plates'
movement,
accumulating energy to cause earthquakes, especially around Tokyo area.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b>Potential risk of earthquakes of a large scale, causing fires and
tidal
waves, human losses; if happened to Tokyo area (it is said that a large scale one can hit Tokyo at
anytime, since they tend to occur every 70-80 years these centuries, and the last one was in 1920
or so),
that would be disastrous not only for Japan but also for the rest of the world, causing high
casualty, fires,
and floods, making people lose houses and starve, making Tokyo unable to function politically,
economically, and socially, and thus making the world economy negatively affected; the end of the
era of
Japan as economic giant.<br>
<b>Potential Goal: </b>coordinated research and funding primarily by Japanese governments and
experts, but also jointly by other governments and experts from other parts of the world; planning
by
Japanese government to move some parts of governmental functions away from Tokyo; planning
by
governments to store necessary foodstuffs, clothes, medicines, medical equipment, etc., for the
worst
case scenario.<br>
<b>Domain: </b>2, 3, 4, and 5<br>
<b>Reference and Notes: </b>only references available were all in Japanese.<p>
                                  
<hr><p>

<center><font size=+1><i><b>Policy</b></i><p></font></center>

89. <b>Summary: </b>Key opinion shapers or leaders making light of the risk of global climate
change;
the existence of uncertainty is being widely interpreted as meaning that there will be little or no
effect.<br>
<b>Development: </b>Key opinion shapers (in government and industry) are making light of the
risk of
global climate change because there are uncertainties. The eventual situation could well be more
serious
than projected, whereas the existence of some uncertainty is being widely interpreted as meaning
that
there will be little or no effect.  In some circles this interpretation is labeled "junk science", a
pejorative,
but not totally unwarranted term.  The result is that many policy makers are either confused or
have a
lessened concern than they should in the face of a major potential global problem.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> Widespread and relatively sudden changes to the global climate
will
have serious  and mostly adverse effects on the economy, on human health, on the planetary
environment
and on the quality of life.<br>
<b>Goal:</b>  Persuade policy makers that the uncertainty surrounding potential global climate
change
does not mean the effects will be negligible or manageable.  <br>
<b>Domain: </b> 6<br>
<b>References: </b>Cline, William R., <i>The Economics of Global Warming, </i>Institute for
International Economics, Washington, DC, June 1992;."Possible Climate Change", paper by Prof.
Bert
Bolin, Chair, Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, World Meteorological
Organization/United
Nations Environment Program, presented at 16th World Energy Congress, Tokyo, October,
1995; World
Energy Council, 16th Congress, Tokyo, October, 1995.  Congress Conclusions and
Recommendations;
"The Long Term Starts Now", observations on the 16th World Energy Congress by John Hollins,
Environment Canada.                       <p>
                                  
105. <b>Summary: </b>Environmental security becoming an important concern in foreign policy.
<br>
<b>Development: </b>Secretary Christopher announced that this issue would be a focus of the
US
Department of State, but no agency has a clear policy about how to handle environmental issues
overseas
that may impinge on US interests.<br>
<b>Potential Consequences: </b> Some soul searching as the roles for various agencies shake
out.
Internationalization of currently national environmental issues. A new source of friction or
cooperation.<br>
<b>References and Notes:</b><p>
<hr>

<p>
Thank your very much for completing the second section of Round 2 of the Millennium Project's
1996 Global Look-Out questionnaire.  Return via Email to <i>jglenn@igc.org</i>  or fax to the
USA at 202-686-5179 or airmail to AC/UNU/ Millennium Project, 4421 Garrison Street, NW,
Washington, D.C. 20016-4055 USA. The results will be sent back to you as Part of Round 3.<p>

